INSERT INTO `wp_comments` VALUES (2,6,'Steini Jonsson','steinilux@gmail.com','','','2006-02-22 09:20:24','2006-02-22 09:20:24','Just what I was looking for...\n\nThanks,\n\nSteini',0,'1','','',0,0),(3,6,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2006-02-23 01:57:02','2006-02-23 01:57:02','Glad I could help.  Although even though I came up with the thing in the first place, what would you actually use it for?',0,'1','','',0,0),(4,8,'Dan','dan@alig.net','http://blog.alig.net','','2005-02-07 08:35:37','2005-02-07 08:35:37','...and some of us are more exited than others.  See <a href=\"http://www.macromedia.com/software/coldfusion/productinfo/reviews_news/\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.macromedia.com/software/coldfusion/productinfo/reviews_news/</a> (about 2/3 of the way down the page).',0,'1','','',0,0),(5,8,'Terrence Ryan','terry@citizenwumpus.com','http://www.citizenwumpus.com/terry/','','2005-02-07 11:52:27','2005-02-07 11:52:27','Kendall Whitehouse is everywhere.',0,'1','','',0,0),(6,9,'Janice','janiceskates@gmail.com','http://citizenwumpus.com/janice','','2005-02-28 10:38:33','2005-02-28 10:38:33','That was awesome, thanks for the link.  I love that stuff.',0,'1','','',0,0),(7,11,'Dan','dan@alig.net','http://blog.alig.net','','2005-03-23 09:15:08','2005-03-23 09:15:08','Gotta love the Ben.  I have to admit, I wasn\'t sure if it was you or this guy (<a href=\"http://www.mj12.net/terrence/),\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.mj12.net/terrence/),</a> who apparently consults for Macromedia.',0,'1','','',0,0),(8,11,'Scott','smcnulty@gmail.com','http://blankbaby.typepad.com','','2005-03-23 20:49:08','2005-03-23 20:49:08','Ben gave me a shout out but no link (I did send him the URL of Blankbaby).\n\nAnyway, good job!',0,'1','','',0,0),(9,12,'donna','theprintshop1@verizon.net','','','2007-11-08 12:11:55','2007-11-08 12:11:55','What is this font',0,'1','','',0,0),(10,12,'Jennifer','jenmcentyre@yahoo.com','','','2007-11-13 17:10:22','2007-11-13 17:10:22','Hi my name is Jennfer and I really need help figuring out what this font is. If you can help I would appreciate it so much. Thanks in advance..\n\nJennifer',0,'1','','',0,0),(11,13,'Jason','jason@spiderwebstrategies.com','','','2006-06-07 13:03:08','2006-06-07 13:03:08','Thanks for this.  I am trying to use it but it takes forever then I get a \" Connection reset\" error.\n\nAny ideas?\n\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(12,13,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2006-06-07 17:38:17','2006-06-07 17:38:17','I\'ve gotten that sometimes when https is not active on the webserver I\'m contacting.  Alternatively, it doesn\'t like the ssl cert the webserver is using.\n\nHave you tried connecting to multiple webservers? ',0,'1','','',0,0),(13,15,'Ryan','ryan@digitalbackcountry.com','http://www.digitalbackcountry.com','','2005-08-04 21:43:52','2005-08-04 21:43:52','\"Doesn\'t handle web design?\"  That\'s a con? WYSIWYG is for people who can\'t handle CSS.\n\nSeriously though, it\'s about time you fully converted to the dark side.  We choke people without touching them.  /starwars\n\n-Ryan',0,'1','','',0,0),(14,15,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2005-08-04 22:18:54','2005-08-04 22:18:54','There are people who still use Dreamweaver for it\'s design portion. Come to a few more code reviews, and you\'ll believe me.\n\nAdditionally I can cause people pain with just my voice! /Aarrgghh!!',0,'1','','',0,0),(15,16,'Ryan','ryan@digitalbackcountry.com','http://www.digitalbackcountry.com','','2005-08-09 22:04:29','2005-08-09 22:04:29','That\'s pretty sweet.  I don\'t use Sharpreader, but if I did, I\'d steal that code Thomas Crowne Affair style.\n\nAlso, where are the cigar posts?',0,'1','','',0,0),(16,16,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2005-08-09 22:11:08','2005-08-09 22:11:08','Does that make me Rene Russo in this scenario?  I\'m not sure if I\'m comformtable with that.\n\nCigar posts are coming.  I haven\'t had a lot of new cigars lately. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(17,18,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2005-12-27 23:20:39','2005-12-27 23:20:39','I\'m not exaclty what you mean.  But you would have to get the file onto the server\'s file systems before you could do anything with it. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(18,18,'Hector','hecmor@gmail.com','http://www.tecito.com','','2005-12-24 21:35:56','2005-12-24 21:35:56','I hade a copy of TMT_IMAGE for a while but i cold never figure out how to make it to work using a input field of type file. I had a look at your code, its nice, but how do you go about calling your component from a form page?',0,'1','','',0,0),(19,19,'Janice','janiceskates@gmail.com','http://www.numtopia.com/janice/blog','','2005-08-24 00:22:57','2005-08-24 00:22:57','Ryan, I tried once to get the laptop away, but he bit my arm and then looked at me suspiciously all day.  It really wasn\'t worth the trouble.',0,'1','','',0,0),(20,19,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2005-08-24 00:24:32','2005-08-24 00:24:32','You\'re sitting right next to me!  There is nothing from stopping me from...',0,'1','','',0,0),(21,19,'Janice','janiceskates@gmail.com','http://www.numtopia.com/janice/blog','','2005-08-24 00:25:35','2005-08-24 00:25:35','EEeekk!  My shoulder, my shoulder!  Am I going to need shots?',0,'1','','',0,0),(22,19,'Ryan','ryan@digitalbackcountry.com','http://www.digitalbackcountry.com','','2005-08-24 00:39:14','2005-08-24 00:39:14','Disclaimer: Commentor is not responsible for any bodily harm caused by comment.\n\nWas that too late?',0,'1','','',0,0),(23,19,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2005-08-24 00:41:15','2005-08-24 00:41:15','Nope too late. Janice already is in the fetal position foaming at the mouth.  But in fairness, it may be unrelated to my bite.',0,'1','','',0,0),(24,19,'Dan','dan@alig.net','http://blog.alig.net','','2005-08-23 08:45:17','2005-08-23 08:45:17','Hmm...who would win the Terry v. Janice smackdown?\n\nBut really, Terry, how could you compete against http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Janice?',0,'1','','',0,0),(25,19,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2005-08-23 10:04:08','2005-08-23 10:04:08','\"janice\" defeats \"terry\"\n5642 characters to 585 characters.\n\nI lose. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(26,19,'Ryan','ryan@digitalbackcountry.com','http://www.digitalbackcountry.com','','2005-08-23 23:06:36','2005-08-23 23:06:36','I think someone should take away your laptop when you have vacation days.\n\nBut I\'m impressed that you\'ve been blogging it up lately.  With other people\'s (blog.alig.net) blogs you have to clear out the cobwebs before reading.',0,'1','','',0,0),(27,19,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2005-08-23 23:26:53','2005-08-23 23:26:53','Talk about cobwebs, you should check out: http://bobz01.blogspot.com/. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(28,19,'Dan','dan@alig.net','http://blog.alig.net','','2005-08-24 10:10:43','2005-08-24 10:10:43','Hey!  Keep it down Cronkright....',0,'1','','',0,0),(29,22,'Scott','smcnulty@gmail.com','http://blankbaby.typepad.com','','2005-08-30 00:10:34','2005-08-30 00:10:34','Wordpress took me less than 5 minutes to install.\n\nI\'m just saying.',0,'1','','',0,0),(30,22,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2005-08-30 00:15:55','2005-08-30 00:15:55','Trust me, that thought has crossed my mind.  However I like the fact that Movable Type just spits out any old files, which allows me to dynamically create CFML.  Which I use to power my picture tools, code displayer, and a couple other features.\n\nI believe that Wordpress requires you to create php files, and since this site is for my enjoyment, no php.\n\nAlso cognitive dissonance has set in.  If it\'s this hard to install, it must be good. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(31,22,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2005-08-31 15:44:16','2005-08-31 15:44:16','Well first off, I am sticking with Movable Type, for many reasons, only some of which I listed here. I also like the interface. I like ease of extending it, and the developer community built up around it.  Second, I do recognize that it\'s not necessarily hard to install Movable Type 3.2, but is has been hard for <strong>Me</strong> to install MT 3.2.\n\nHowever, support has been slow in my perception. Now I recognize that with a major update you\'re going to need to do more support than usual, and my case manager has been very polite, and has (as of last night) alerted me to the high number of calls Six Apart has been getting. Additionally some of my frustration is due to the fact that I have never needed support before with Movable Type, which is a compliment to Six Apart.\n\nAll in all, I\'m impatient to get it working, and that\'s the bottom line.  However that impatience is driven by my excitement for the product... and maybe a little bit of cognitive dissonance thrown in.\n\nNow i have to ask, how did my little corner of the internet get on the radar screen of the Vice President of Six Apart? ',0,'1','','',0,0),(32,22,'Dan','dan@alig.net','http://blog.alig.net','','2005-08-31 19:19:29','2005-08-31 19:19:29','Movable Type 3.2 took me less than 5 minutes to install.\n\nI\'m just saying...to <a href=\"http://blankbaby.typepad.com/\" rel=\"nofollow\">Scott</A>, that is.',0,'1','','',0,0),(33,22,'Scott','smcnulty@gmail.com','http://blankbaby.typepad.com','','2005-09-01 13:57:50','2005-09-01 13:57:50','Hey, I wasn\'t knocking Movable Type.. well maybe I was.  I\'m a happy user of Typepad, and I know that the install of MT has gotten much better since I lasted tried (and failed miserably, which has kind of pooched the hootch for me re: MT).\n\nPerhaps, I\'ll give it another go.\n\nAnd I think Anil has some searches on blog search engines (like Technorati) that look for Six Apart stuff.  He commented on an entry of mine when I complained about the, then, new comment notifications from Typepad (I said they <a href=\"http://blankbaby.typepad.com/blankbaby/2005/03/new_typepad_com.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">sucked</a>, and they did).',0,'1','','',0,0),(34,22,'Anil','anil@dashes.com','http://www.anildash.com/','','2005-08-31 14:32:25','2005-08-31 14:32:25','We\'re definitely working hard to be as responsive as possible... there\'s a huge number of people who\'ve upgraded or started new with Movable Type 3.2, so we\'re not as quick as our usual standards.\n\nRest assured, the dev team is plugging away at any possible Windows issues to see if there\'s anything we can simplify for you. And one of the benefits of Movable Type is that you can not just output CFML, but get friendly URLs by default on a Windows server running IIS. Other tools that require an .htaccess file (which is only for Apache servers) won\'t allow you to do that.\n\nGive us a little bit to catch up with the overwhelming (and overwhelmingly positive!) response to the MT3.2 launch, and I\'m sure you\'ll see why people rave about our support. If you\'ve got any concerns in the meantime, feel free to get in touch.',0,'1','','',0,0),(35,23,'Dana','danarashad@yahoo.com','','','2007-05-14 09:19:15','2007-05-14 09:19:15','I am having problems using cfdocument flashpaper.  It works on all of the mac browsers.  On windows it works on firefox.  But in IE7 it does not work.  Can anyone tell me a work around.  I could use pdf\'s, but flashpaper is faster.  Here\'s my code its pretty simple.\n<cfdocument format=\"FlashPaper\">\n<cfoutput>\n<div align=\"left\"><br><br>\n<table width=\"712\" border=\"0\" align=\"center\" cellpadding=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\">\n	<tr><td height=\"22\"> <div align=\"left\">#form.date#</div></td></tr>\n	<tr><td>#form.fname# #form.lname#</td></tr>\n    <tr><td height=\"19\">#form.school#</td></tr>\n    <tr>\n</cfdocument>  I am using flash player 9, and that seems to be the problem.  It works in the older players, but with IE 7 and flash player 9, they dont work.  Help?????!',0,'1','','',0,0),(36,34,'tpryan','terry@terrenceryan.com','http://www.terrenceryan.com/blog/','','2011-12-21 10:37:01','2011-12-21 10:37:01','Hey Lindsay, This post is like 6 years old.  I would imagine that it is very possible that this is no longer true.',0,'1','','',0,0),(37,34,'lindsay morris','lindsay@tsmworks.com','','','2011-12-21 10:27:37','2011-12-21 10:27:37','Doesn\'t look like that\'s right.  Each of my cluster nodes (xx1a, xx1b) reports its own name in the ActiveComputername, but only 1b is really active.  I would have expected xx1a to report xx1b as the activecomputername.',0,'1','','',0,0),(38,36,'marjo moore','marjo_moore@NOSPAM.yahoo.com','http://moremarjo.blogspot.com','','2005-12-01 08:25:40','2005-12-01 08:25:40','Such a perfectionist... :P\n\nIs there a certain validator that you use? I love Macromedia myself. Could not live without it-- but I certainly need some guidance, as I am only on my second website (and I only know a little bit of Java). Any tips would be welcome',0,'1','','',0,0),(39,36,'Ryan Stewart','ryan@ryanstewart.net','http://www.ryanstewart.net','','2005-12-03 12:00:14','2005-12-03 12:00:14','That\'s awesome Terry.  Hpoefully one of the things Ray will do is make it a little bit easier for people who use his blog software to use valid XHTML.  ColdFusion of course makes that nearly impossible though.  I wonder if that\'s something the CF team is working on.',0,'1','','',0,0),(40,36,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2005-12-01 18:34:40','2005-12-01 18:34:40','Well for validation in general I use the w3.org validator, which is linked into the Firefox developer\'s tool bar.\n\nHowever for testing the whole site, I use the WDG validator, which can crawl a site and validate up to 100 pages in the site.',0,'1','','',0,0),(41,37,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2005-12-05 23:41:07','2005-12-05 23:41:07','Wow.  I never expected a response from anyone at Macromedia/Adobe. I\'ll keep my eyes open in January. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(42,37,'John Dowdell','supportinfo@macromedia.com','http://weblogs.macromedia.com/jd','','2005-12-05 20:20:42','2005-12-05 20:20:42','I don\'t have hard info yet... if you\'ve been following the Macromedia-oriented weblogs, you\'ve seen how the businesses need to set up a \"clean room\" for any planning, in case political permission was not given and the businesses needed to compete separately. It will take awhile for internal briefings, then the holidays... I wouldn\'t realistically expect much in the way of explicit roadmaps until January.\n\nI pretty much agree with you, though, that the lightweight profile of FlashPaper for documents seems compelling. There are already profiles for archiving, exchange, and engineering... seems reasonable to me, but I\'ve got no inside info yet on this subject.\n\njd/mm',0,'1','','',0,0),(43,38,'Matt Thornton','mthornton@jimdavis2006.com','http://www.jimdavis2006.com','','2005-12-09 12:31:45','2005-12-09 12:31:45','Thanks for the post, Terry.\n\nI am doing a big live blogging push this weekend from the Florida Democartic Party State Conference.  Be sure to drop by and say hello.  Should be fun...',0,'1','','',0,0),(44,38,'Bob','bomalley@metroplanorlando.com','http://www.OBlog.blogs.com','','2005-12-09 13:36:23','2005-12-09 13:36:23','I\'m a Republican (just like the next Governor) but I admire what Congressman Davis and Matt Thornton have done with the website.  I think more elected officials should listen to their constituents and blogs are a good tool for that two-way communication to take place. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(45,38,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2005-12-09 14:49:36','2005-12-09 14:49:36','Wow, the website has cross-party appeal.  Granted, the Bob\'s not voting for Davis but in today\'s political climate, a compliment from the other side is a hard fought gain. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(46,38,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2006-10-14 00:39:42','2006-10-14 00:39:42','Well Bob is not voting for him becaue Bob is a Republican. I am not voting for him because I am not a resident of Florida.',0,'1','','',0,0),(47,38,'jean','laguerre@yahoo.com','','','2006-10-13 22:39:30','2006-10-13 22:39:30','why is he not going for davis',0,'1','','',0,0),(48,38,'judith','urbanpits@bellsouth.net','','','2006-10-29 21:41:55','2006-10-29 21:41:55','I\'m voting for Jim Davis because,frankly, I\'m tired of Jeb the magnificent\'s b.s. Florida is not very high on the educational monitor, our insurance rates are doubling even if you never had a claim, property taxes have doubled. We are cutting medicaid benefits for the poorest Floridians.I think ALL republicans should be voted out of office and the President and Mr.Foley should be in prison as Nixon should have been Foley for practicing pedophelia and the President for being stupid,selfish and self serving the rich instead of the majority of americans.\n ',0,'1','','',0,0),(49,38,'relocating to raleigh','currencyforex1242@gmail.com','http://www.relocationguide.biz/','','2010-01-20 07:56:00','2010-01-20 07:56:00','Is this true ?\n\n\nRegards',0,'1','','',0,0),(50,40,'Mark Neumann','mark.alan.neumann@gmail.com','http://www.myopicmindfulness.com','','2006-04-18 12:53:17','2006-04-18 12:53:17','Yep... We (at Implex) have hosted dataride from quite some time. :)',0,'1','','',0,0),(51,41,'Scott','smcnulty@gmail.com','http://blog.blankbaby.com','','2006-01-13 00:47:04','2006-01-13 00:47:04','And I thought being at Macworld was geeky.',0,'1','','',0,0),(52,41,'Scott Fegette','sfegette@adobe.com','http://weblogs.macromedia.com/sfegette/','','2006-01-13 13:55:38','2006-01-13 13:55:38','Cool- fun question.\nI\'m going with Tim Buntel- even with his voice gone, he\'s still one of the most entertaining personalities you\'ll ever meet (if you caught his MXDU 2005 keynote session, you\'ll know EXACTLY what I\'m talking about).\n\n(honestly, it\'s a very tight push for #2 between Nimer and Ben- both are a ton of fun to hang with as well...)',0,'1','','',0,0),(53,41,'Sean Corfield','seancorfield@gmail.com','http://corfield.org/','','2006-01-13 01:50:50','2006-01-13 01:50:50','Oh this will be a fun one...\n\nI think my vote would go to Tim as well - based on his MAX and CFUNITED keynotes...',0,'1','','',0,0),(54,41,'Martin Kristensen','mkristensen@gmail.com','','','2006-01-13 02:45:45','2006-01-13 02:45:45','Geeks like you should not drink',0,'1','','',0,0),(55,41,'Andy Allan','andy@creative-restraint.co.uk','http://www.creative-restraint.co.uk','','2006-01-13 04:23:56','2006-01-13 04:23:56','My vote goes for Tim as well. Saying that, after his last visit to Scotland, I don\'t think his liver could take it :)',0,'1','','',0,0),(56,41,'Gary Fenton','garygfx@gmail.com','','','2006-01-13 06:49:02','2006-01-13 06:49:02','I think Ben because he might make the least amount of mess to clean up! Hey, got to be practical!',0,'1','','',0,0),(57,41,'Dan','dan@alig.net','http://blog.alig.net/','','2006-01-13 07:00:51','2006-01-13 07:00:51','Damon.  \'Cause we could stay up all night talking about event gateways.  And no, I\'m not drinking at 7:00 AM....',0,'1','','',0,0),(58,41,'Hans','hans@hansomli.com','http://www.hansomli.com/','','2006-01-13 07:12:30','2006-01-13 07:12:30','<a href=\"http://tjordahl.blogspot.com/\" rel=\"nofollow\">Tom Jordahl</a>, though I wouldn\'t let him sleep until I had seen the <a href=\"http://groups.yahoo.com/group/flexcoders/message/27124\" rel=\"nofollow\">ColdFusion MX 7 and Flex2 integration</a> piece he\'s working on.',0,'1','','',0,0),(59,41,'Becky','bendy.straw@verizon.net','http://www.doesthisblogmakemybuttlookbig.com','','2006-01-13 10:12:53','2006-01-13 10:12:53','Viktor Schauberger.',0,'1','','',0,0),(60,41,'Janice','janice@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/janice/blog','','2006-01-13 12:01:42','2006-01-13 12:01:42','I bet Viktor Schauberger would be a really cagey houseguest.  I mean, after the Nazis caused him to have a nervous breakdown, I bet he became a lot less fun to be around...',0,'1','','',0,0),(61,41,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2006-01-14 13:26:10','2006-01-14 13:26:10','So looks like Tim Buntel is the leader by a head. Although there\'s a slight push for Ben Forta and Mike Nimer.',0,'1','','',0,0),(62,41,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2006-01-27 14:05:25','2006-01-27 14:05:25','I think that even for me, a \"ColdFusion sleep-over\" crosses some sort of limit for geekiness.\n\nUnless of course we could make \'smores. In which case, game on. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(63,41,'Rob Brooks-Bilson','rbils@yahoo.com','http://www.brooks-bilson.com/blogs/rob/','','2006-01-27 00:28:48','2006-01-27 00:28:48','Why narrow it down to just one?  How about a ColdFusion sleep-over!',0,'1','','',0,0),(64,42,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2006-01-17 16:33:07','2006-01-17 16:33:07','Actually it was the script tags themselves.  Pretty much all tags have to be lowercase. Additionally, it requires a type for script.  I have what I had done at home, I can email it to you later. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(65,42,'Gary Fenton','garygfx@gmail.com','','','2006-01-17 16:30:49','2006-01-17 16:30:49','What\'s wrong with the formatting of the javascript? Surely it\'s the same format for XHTML? Whatever goes inbetween the SCRIPT tags is governed by the ECMA JS standard. If you can give me examples of what it should be then I can try to work on it. Thanks.',0,'1','','',0,0),(66,42,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2006-01-17 14:16:07','2006-01-17 14:16:07','It was a combination of that and the formatting of the Javascript.  However when I tried to correct them to make them web compliant, they stopped working in IE.  I think cross browser compatibility is more important than Webstandards compliance in this case.  So a Cacheless Webstandards Compliant Flashpaper Embedder is a Platonic Ideal for now.    ',0,'1','','',0,0),(67,42,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2006-01-16 23:29:02','2006-01-16 23:29:02','Gary: It\'s really cool code.  However I can\'t seem to make it webstandards compliant and work in IE at the same time.  So it\'s an alternative solution to the issue, depending on your needs.\n\nThat being said, it\'s very cool. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(68,42,'Gary Fenton','garygfx@gmail.com','http://www.hotfusion.co.uk/embedDocument/index.htm','','2006-01-17 13:43:23','2006-01-17 13:43:23','Thanks for the feedback. What bit isn\'t \"webstandards compliant\"? The iframe element?',0,'1','','',0,0),(69,42,'Gary Fenton','garygfx@gmail.com','http://www.hotfusion.co.uk/embedDocument/index.htm','','2006-01-14 20:28:42','2006-01-14 20:28:42','Here\'s a link to my new tag. I\'ve called it CF_EmbedDocument.  <a href=\"http://www.hotfusion.co.uk/embedDocument/index.htm\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.hotfusion.co.uk/embedDocument/index.htm</a> (or click on my name).<BR>\n\nI can\'t use a CFC because the tag is called once as a regular cfm page (which CFCs can\'t) and again as a custom tag.\n\nUnfortunately my website runs PHP, not CF so there\'s no live demo. You can house it here if you think it\'s worthy enough. Ideas for improvements welcomed.',0,'1','','',0,0),(70,42,'Gary Fenton','garygfx@gmail.com','','','2006-01-14 19:26:46','2006-01-14 19:26:46','I accepted my own challenge(!) and created a new custom tag (I couldn\'t think how to do it cleanly with a CFC) that embeds PDF and FlashPaper documents without creating any files. Also lets you embed multiple docs (mix PDF and Flash if you like) on the same page. I needed something like this for my current project. It doesn\'t use Satay - no need as I \"cheated\" and used an iframe and session vars glued together with a spot of JavaScript. I will post a url to the file when I\'ve uploaded. Feel free to critique! :-)',0,'1','','',0,0),(71,42,'Gary Fenton','garygfx@gmail.com','','','2006-01-14 06:52:15','2006-01-14 06:52:15','Thanks, I found this useful, also thanks for flagging up Satay. I don\'t mean to nit-pick but the CFC throws an error as it\'s missing a double quote here:<BR>\n&lt;cfif overwrite or not fileExists(#This.cachedirectory#/#arguments.filename#\")&gt;\n<BR>\nIf you set the overwrite arg to false it will also throw an error.\n\nUsing a cache directory for files is okay if your site doesn\'t have many Flashpaper files but what if it does? A load of files can quickly build up especially if each file is unique to every user. It would be nice if there was a way to embed Flashpaper but serve it from memory. Not sure how?',0,'1','','',0,0),(72,42,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2006-01-14 13:22:28','2006-01-14 13:22:28','Thanks, it\'s not nitpicking, they are legitimate issues.\n\nThe error with overwrite=\"FALSE\" has been fixed.  The code I use to display code with coloring caused the  missing quote.\n\nAs for the temp display of it, I\'m intrigued.  That does sound like a better way of doing it. I too am not sure how to, but I\'m going to think on it.   ',0,'1','','',0,0),(73,42,'Gary Fenton','garygfx@gmail.com','','','2006-01-18 19:15:12','2006-01-18 19:15:12','Oops, lower case, of course! I\'m so used to doing upper case for tags and lower for attributes - it makes it easier to read. Thanks.',0,'1','','',0,0),(74,42,'Childrens Upholstered Chairs','wilfully03126@gmail.com','http://www.greenbriardesignsnc.com','','2009-12-18 00:03:59','2009-12-18 00:03:59','Hi,\n\nI want to buy more memory for my notebook.',0,'1','','',0,0),(75,43,'Steve Glachan','bdo2001@gmail.com','','','2007-10-10 01:42:35','2007-10-10 01:42:35','The include is nice a neat way of doing this, especially if your generated newsletter email is long and complex. Wrapping a &lt;savecontent/&gt; around the email content can also be an alternative. Then below it you would just output the \'savecontent\' variable between cfmail tags.',0,'1','','',0,0),(76,45,'Ryan Stewart','ryan@ryanstewart.net','http://www.ryanstewart.net','','2006-01-25 23:27:00','2006-01-25 23:27:00','There appears to be some disagreement: (See link above)\nAside from the ranting nature, he does bring up some interesting points.  I\'m torn, I really like web standards (though BlogCFC makes it impossible to have a valid website) but I also really like flash.\n\nIt is a pickle.',0,'1','','',0,0),(77,45,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2006-01-25 23:58:06','2006-01-25 23:58:06','He\'s got some good points. Howver I think he misses the greater point. The point is that webstandards should mean simpler HTML code. Webstandards also mean that even if you didn\'t test it on a particular platform, there\'s a good chance it will still work.\n\nDon\'t get me wrong,  I love Flex, CFForm type=Flash, and Flash, but they don\'t have Flash for my Blackberry yet. However webstandards built pages still work fine. Until Flash Lite really penetrates the US market I think webstandards buys you more.  ',0,'1','','',0,0),(78,48,'cfJeff','jeff.mcnaughton@puc.state.oh.us','http://www.puco.ohio.gov/','','2006-02-16 16:53:50','2006-02-16 16:53:50','nice work.  I happened to run into this very problem the other day.',0,'1','','',0,0),(79,48,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2006-02-17 10:46:01','2006-02-17 10:46:01','That\'s exactly the way I do it.  You could also write the catch to exacly match the conditions that cause the error (something about Stub objects usually.)\n\nAs for this as an alternative to restartings:  Absolutely. It\'s the equivalent and reloading the webservice in the cfide/administrator console. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(80,48,'Rich Rein','richard.rein@pearson.com','','','2006-02-17 10:41:01','2006-02-17 10:41:01','So essentially, you would have the following:\n\n<cftry>\n   <!--- try to consume web service --->\n<cfcatch type=\"any\">\n   <cfset reset_webservice(wsdl_URL) />\n   <!--- try to consume web service again --->\n</cfcatch>\n</cftry>\n\nwhere your web service call would happen a maximum of two times before erroring out?',0,'1','','',0,0),(81,48,'Rich Rein','richard.rein@pearson.com','','','2006-02-17 10:42:43','2006-02-17 10:42:43','Oops, code was gone from my previous:\n\ncftry\n   call webservice\ncfcatch type=\"any\"\n   reset_webservice(wsdl_url)\n   call webservice again\n/cfcatch\n/cftry\n\nAlso, would this be useful for noticing a change in a local webservice and reloading it, rather than having to restart the CF service?',0,'1','','',0,0),(82,48,'Sean Corfield','seancorfield@gmail.com','http://corfield.org/','','2006-02-16 01:47:06','2006-02-16 01:47:06','Oops, that kinda messed up the formatting :)\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(83,48,'Sean Corfield','seancorfield@gmail.com','http://corfield.org/','','2006-02-16 01:44:17','2006-02-16 01:44:17','Don\'t forget that the above code is not thread-safe unless you add \'var\' declarations for both factory and RpcService:\n\ncfset var factory = createobject(\"java\", \"coldfusion.server. ServiceFactory\")\ncfset var RpcService = factory.XmlRpcService\ncfset RpcService. refreshWebService (arguments.wsdl)\n\n(you don\'t need \"#..#\" there)\n\nOf course you could do the whole thing in one line and be thread-safe like this:\n\ncfset createObject(\"java\", \"coldfusion.server. ServiceFactory\"). XmlRpcService. refreshWebService (arguments.wsdl)\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(84,48,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2006-02-16 15:18:32','2006-02-16 15:18:32','I added Sean\'s comments to the extended entry portion of the post. Sorry about that, Sean, I haven\'t hacked MovableType enough for it to show code properly in comments.',0,'1','','',0,0),(85,49,'mensch','mensch53@hotmail.com','','','2006-02-16 16:33:21','2006-02-16 16:33:21','Mark, Steele is not going to get very far in an admittidly liberal state walking around and comparing stem cell research to the holocaust http://www.dailykos.com/storyonly/2006/2/10/132125/876',0,'1','','',0,0),(86,49,'Mark','mark@mdprofinish.com','','','2006-02-16 16:14:32','2006-02-16 16:14:32','Nice site,  but I still hope he wins.  I like his record and I wish I could vote for him.  Here in Maryland, we are likely to have our first interesting senate race in decades with a conservative African American (Michael S. Steele, Maryland\'s Lt. Governor) running.  Even though Maryland is an exceedingly liberal state, I think he has a shot.',0,'1','','',0,0),(87,49,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2006-02-16 16:31:15','2006-02-16 16:31:15','John Phillip seems to like Santorum a bit.\n\nMark I do have to agree that the Maryland race is shaping up to be interesting. But I have to admit, I\'ve been more interested in their Senate primaries.',0,'1','','',0,0),(88,49,'john phillip','asdf@asdf.com','','','2006-02-16 16:14:20','2006-02-16 16:14:20','Never gonna happen\nNever gonna happen\nNever gonna happen\nNever gonna happen\nNever gonna happen',0,'1','','',0,0),(89,51,'Jeff Porten','civitan@jeffporten.com','http://www.jeffporten.com','','2006-02-21 12:21:11','2006-02-21 12:21:11','Let me know when this is available as a general release.  I have a fear of signing up as a Macromedia developer only to find that it\'s a Window-only download.',0,'1','','',0,0),(90,51,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2006-02-21 13:41:57','2006-02-21 13:41:57','Sure, Jeff. I will personally notify you when Adobe releases Flash Player 8.5.  Any other companies you want me to track for you.  Microsoft has a new version of Office in the works, you know.  ',0,'1','','',0,0),(91,51,'Garnet','gchaney@webmill.com','http://www.bobsgear.com/display/ts/Adobe+Flash','','2008-10-16 21:15:51','2008-10-16 21:15:51','What happened to your demo? I clicked on the .CFM link above, and I got just a blank screen. Hope you can get it working again.\n\nhttp://www.bobsgear.com/display/ts/Adobe+Flash',0,'1','','',0,0),(92,52,'Arul Prasad','arulprasad@gmail.com','http://arulprasad.blogspot.com','','2006-02-22 02:32:33','2006-02-22 02:32:33','Hey,\n\nI tried with \'AJAX\' and \'FLASH\'. Though sadly in both instances \'AJAX\' defeats \'FLASH\', the Flex version always shows the numbers much lesser than in the CFM version!',0,'1','','',0,0),(93,52,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2006-02-22 10:26:53','2006-02-22 10:26:53','It took me a little bit to realize why the different count. The Flex front end version displays the word count.  The HTML front end version displays a character count.  I will be changing this. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(94,54,'John Dowdell','supportinfo@macromedia.com','http://weblogs.macromedia.com/jd','','2006-03-27 22:52:15','2006-03-27 22:52:15','If you\'re asking why EMBED makes the W3C Validators cry, then that\'s because it\'s what the browsers support, and the spec countered it. Player doesn\'t care what label the browser uses to invoke it, just that it\'s invoked.\n\n(Browsermakers are switching over to schemes to invoke the proper plugin via OBJECT tag, whether W3C-style OBJECT or MS-style OBJECT, but they\'re not quite there yet.)\n\nDo what thou wilt... you want to use OBJECT instead of EMBED, go ahead. Just test your project carefully in a range of viewing environments first, please, I don\'t want you to get burned.',0,'1','','',0,0),(95,54,'John Dowdell','supportinfo@macromedia.com','http://weblogs.macromedia.com/jd','','2006-03-27 22:53:09','2006-03-27 22:53:09','whoops, that was a couple of pargraphs in there, guess linebreaks aren\'t always translated across blogging engines....',0,'1','','',0,0),(96,54,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2006-03-27 22:57:53','2006-03-27 22:57:53','Yeah parts of Movable type mystify me. It\'s set to honor line breaks.\n\nAs to your comment, I do embed using the object tag, when I have control over the embed.  Unless I\'m missing something, I have no control over how cfchart, or flash forms embed their content.',0,'1','','',0,0),(97,55,'Terence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2006-05-22 10:25:33','2006-05-22 10:25:33','Sean: First off, thanks for giving me the first practical explanation as to why CFC\'s are less preferable than custom tags for output.  I\'ve never heard that reason before, and while it doesn\'t apply to my environment, I can see why it would have an impact on yours. As for your results.  I can see I left the trusted cache off on my production instance.  I will re-run after tweaking that, and post my results in a day or so. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(98,55,'Sean Corfield','seancorfield@gmail.com','http://corfield.org/','','2006-05-20 19:23:04','2006-05-20 19:23:04','Er, that first piece isn\'t very clear:\n<br />\n... anything from 10-50% faster ... [than the custom tag invocation]\n<br />\nAnd then an error:\n<br />\nMy custom tag invocation tests typically ran in around 70 (dev [I meant prod of course]) to 200ms (dev). ',0,'1','','',0,0),(99,55,'Sean Corfield','seancorfield@gmail.com','http://corfield.org/','','2006-05-20 19:19:40','2006-05-20 19:19:40','Interesting. I ran your tests on my Mac and, in \"development\" mode, I saw the in-memory CFC invocation be anything from 10-50% faster on repeated runs. In \"production\" mode (i.e., with trusted cache enabled), the times were much closer between in-memory CFC invocation and custom tags. My in-memory CFC invocation tests typically ran in around 70 (prod) to 100ms (dev). My custom tag invocation tests typically ran in around 70 (dev) to 200ms (dev). Therefore I\'m suspicious of your custom tag timings on your systems since your production system is an order of magnitude slower than my laptop (whereas the in-memory CFC invocation is in the same ballpark).\n\nFWIW, the direct CFC invocation was way slower on my system than on yours, both with and without trusted cache.\n\nDefinitely an interesting observation tho\'!\n\nMy main argument for not using CFCs for output (and preferring either custom tags or simple CFML pages) is that you can\'t really have a graphic designer / web production person editing your CFCs, whereas they can easily edit custom tags and CFML pages in their regular WYSIWYG HTML editor. That may not be important in your environment but it\'s important in mine :)',0,'1','','',0,0),(100,55,'Terence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2006-05-19 17:46:04','2006-05-19 17:46:04','Joe: Encapsulation technique like CFC functions and custom tags are in general better for this type of operation because they allow for variable passing between the calling document and the encapsulated code while maintaining a separate set of scopes for the encapsulated code. Cfincluding a template will encapsulate it, but you can\'t pass in variables. (However you can set them before you call the included file.) For example, let say I had an encapsulated navigation bar, and I wanted it to behave differently on different pages. With cfinclude, I would have to set a variable somewhere before I called the included code to indicate which page it was on, or use the cgi.scope to determine it.  With other encapulation techniques like custom tags and CFC\'s you explicitly pass them.  Does that make all make sense? ',0,'1','','',0,0),(101,55,'Terence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2006-05-19 17:38:14','2006-05-19 17:38:14','Mensch: You were warned. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(102,55,'Terence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2006-05-19 17:39:24','2006-05-19 17:39:24','Mark: I\'ll try and give that a shot and get back to you.  ',0,'1','','',0,0),(103,55,'Terence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2006-05-19 17:42:32','2006-05-19 17:42:32','Ray: Obviously more goes into coding than performance. I wouldn\'t say otherwise. But, my curiosity was mainly about performance. Do you have a method for testing performance that you rely on?',0,'1','','',0,0),(104,55,'J.Cruz','jcruz@wharton.upenn.edu','http://www.phillygryphons.org','','2006-05-19 14:56:19','2006-05-19 14:56:19','Admittedly, it\'s been a long time since i\'ve done any serious Cold Fusion programming, so please excuse the question if it\'s simple.\n\nWhat\'s the trade-offs/difference between the CFC/custom tag method a cfinclude or reusable interface content?',0,'1','','',0,0),(105,55,'mensch','mensch53@hotmail.com','','','2006-05-19 12:47:15','2006-05-19 12:47:15','I made it to the word \"encaspulation\" before my vision got blurry and my head hit my keyboard ;)',0,'1','','',0,0),(106,55,'Mark Fuqua','mark@mdprofinish.com','http://www.mdprofinish.com','','2006-05-19 13:45:08','2006-05-19 13:45:08','I would love to see what would happen if the cfc and custom tag were more like a header include. Or some other part of your interface.cfc, rather than just h.  Would the ratios hold?',0,'1','','',0,0),(107,55,'Raymond Camden','ray@camdenfamily.com','http://ray.camdenfamily.com','','2006-05-19 13:53:32','2006-05-19 13:53:32','I\'m not a big fan of testing like this (although I used to do it a lot a few years ago) as I feel it doesn\'t take into account other factors that could potentially be far more important - like code maintainability and ease of updating. I just don\'t put much faith in the \"Run it a 1000 times and take an average\" method of testing speed.\n\nThat being said - it does make sense in that calling a custom tag will typically result in overhead from the scope creation (caller, variables, this) that a created CFC would be able to skip (it just creates arguments and the local scope for the CFC method execution).\n\nI\'m probably rambing a bit - but I\'d probably say use the method that works best for you and your team.',0,'1','','',0,0),(108,56,'jko','jannekort@yahoo.com','','','2006-10-23 05:19:36','2006-10-23 05:19:36','Hi!\n\ni was also exploring the same feature. At times it was possible to publish complete version of a post. Especially with msnspace. I tried with Blogger too and first it did post as complete but then later it published as a draft.',0,'1','','',0,0),(109,56,'wipkkqa','zhyvpf@ncksqx.com','http://onmgoqyawnbl.com/','','2011-02-07 07:40:17','2011-02-07 07:40:17','e6JB6F  <a href=\"http://jnyezkcrjsnl.com/\" rel=\"nofollow\">jnyezkcrjsnl</a>, [url=http://hosbgxmrdvsc.com/]hosbgxmrdvsc[/url], [link=http://ndmqnlygfmnn.com/]ndmqnlygfmnn[/link], http://vkuxqrzppmfs.com/',0,'1','','',0,0),(110,61,'Phillybits','philly_bits@yahoo.com','http://phillybits.blogspot.com','','2006-06-18 01:43:55','2006-06-18 01:43:55','Love the Sweeney Todd graphic at the top left corner. Classy!',0,'1','','',0,0),(111,61,'Terence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.nutopia.com/terry','','2006-06-18 02:04:54','2006-06-18 02:04:54','Is that what that is from?  I\'ve tried to find a source, and couldn\'t track from before the book \"Depraved and Insulting English.\"\n\nThanks you\'ve solved a mystery for me.\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(112,62,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2006-06-18 21:42:50','2006-06-18 21:42:50','Cool! Make sure you tell me if it works. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(113,62,'cfJeff','cfJeff@gmail.com','','','2006-06-18 17:26:24','2006-06-18 17:26:24','I knew I subscribed to this blog for a reason!  I can\'t wait to give this a try.',0,'1','','',0,0),(114,63,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2006-06-26 22:31:41','2006-06-26 22:31:41','Thanks.  I also have to say, it\'s pretty easy to learn. I\'ve never done MVC before, but I\'ve got a lot of my application working already.\n\nIt really rules, Joe.',0,'1','','',0,0),(115,63,'Joe Rinehart','joe.rinehart@gmail.com','http://clearsoftware.net','','2006-06-26 09:22:03','2006-06-26 09:22:03','Welcome to the dark side :)',0,'1','','',0,0),(116,65,'Paul','paul_99@sify.com','http://www.yahoo.com','','2006-07-18 03:42:07','2006-07-18 03:42:07','Glad to read such a nice piece of information.',0,'1','','',0,0),(117,65,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2006-12-06 22:51:56','2006-12-06 22:51:56','I haven\'t, but it\'s because I use ColdFusion to handle images. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(118,65,'Stephen','stephen@ripthebag.com','','','2006-12-06 22:21:17','2006-12-06 22:21:17','Did you have any luck posting pictures?',0,'1','','',0,0),(119,67,'Nick Kwiatkowski','quetwo@hostingplace.net','','','2006-07-05 18:11:32','2006-07-05 18:11:32','An easier way is to create a template, and use the CFSCHEDULE command to fire it off.',0,'1','','',0,0),(120,67,'barry.b','barry.beattie@gmail.com','','','2006-07-05 19:09:50','2006-07-05 19:09:50','I don\'t get the significance of the timeout and \"The process will take a minimum of 1 second\" (I do get the cfcatch/rethrow bit tho...)\n\nin essence it\'s the fact that a webservice is called that makes it asyncronous?\n\nthanx for the tip',0,'1','','',0,0),(121,67,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry/','','2006-07-05 22:11:26','2006-07-05 22:11:26','Barry: Imagine that you have a code section that takes 30 seconds.  By setting the timeout on the invoke to 1 second, the request will throw an error 1 second.  The try block ensures that the error will be caught, but the request will still run. Since the minimum timeout for a weservice call is 1 second that\'s the least time it will take for the error to be triggered.\n\nNick: My hosting provider restricts cfschedule and not cfinvoke.  So... for me this is a good alternative. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(122,67,'Michael Horne','mike@recantha.co.uk','http://www.recantha.co.uk','','2006-07-06 05:48:19','2006-07-06 05:48:19','Thanks for this - I was just getting irritated that our development server is MX7 and everything else is MX6.1...',0,'1','','',0,0),(123,67,'Rob Wilkerson','r.d.wilkerson@gmail.com','','','2006-07-06 08:25:58','2006-07-06 08:25:58','I\'ve used CFMX7\'s J2EE backbone to create async requests using Java\'s URLConnection class.  Works like a dream.',0,'1','','',0,0),(124,67,'Tony Petruzzi','tonyp@rolist.com','','','2006-07-06 08:44:07','2006-07-06 08:44:07','One of the biggest problems that I have seen since gateways were added into CF is that a lot of people have been using them for the wrong reasons and adding unnescessary load onto their CF servers. For instance:\n\nWhy would you use a gateway to process SQL queries or dump a large amount of data into a database? You can create jobs with SQL server (I don\'t know what the equivalent is in other databases) to do this. Not only is it supported nativly inside SQL Server, it\'s much much faster than anything CF can do.\n\nWhy would you use CF to send out thousands of emails through a gateway? Again, this is another task that could easily be offloaded to mass email program running on a different server.\n\nIt goes with that old saying that just because you can do something, doesn\'t mean you should. In my opinion CF should be used for one thing, processing web requests. There\'s no reason to add more load to your CF server by making do task that are outside of the norm when more efficient solutions already exist.',0,'1','','',0,0),(125,67,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry/','','2006-07-06 14:36:48','2006-07-06 14:36:48','Tony:  There are many valid reasons to use Asynchronous CFML connections, even for operations best handled by other processes. (If 95 percent of your app is written in ColdFusion, why make the app less maintainable by writing the mail section in something else.  Especially if the gain in productivity is not necessary.)  But additionally there are many good reasons to use them.  I use them in a blog package I wrote to rewrite all of the rss files for categories, authors, most recent, etc in response to a user request.  By making it an asynchronous process the user can initiate the change without having to wait for it. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(126,68,'pylorns','pylorns@wetwired.org','http://www.wetwired.org','','2006-07-20 09:20:10','2006-07-20 09:20:10','Yeah I\'m getting really tired of spamers even being able to comment, regaurdless if the comment ever gets published, its the fact that i have to delete it. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(127,69,'Isidro','ipimentel@pausd.org','','','2008-04-03 02:21:15','2008-04-03 02:21:15','Thank you for the post as it clarifies things for me.\n\nI am trying to build a page on our intranet that allows users to reset their AD passwords. On my post that I have found online there is reference to a secure connection between AD and  the CF server I am having a hard time doing this could you please provide guidance on creating this connection. Our intranet already has a SSL certificate Do I need to get an additional  SSL certificate for communication from the CF8 server to the AD server?\n\nAny help will be greatly appreciated.  ',0,'1','','',0,0),(128,69,'Dan','dan@dan.com','','','2008-10-27 12:27:16','2008-10-27 12:27:16','Thank you so much! Been struggling with this all morning and this solved it!',0,'1','','',0,0),(129,70,'Peter Tilbrook','peter@tilbrook.name','http://www.actcfug.com/','','2006-08-06 00:30:56','2006-08-06 00:30:56','Cool! Added to my web links library (now over 600!).',0,'1','','',0,0),(130,71,'Armand','gaspyy@gmail.com','http://blog.richnetapps.com','','2006-09-06 02:19:58','2006-09-06 02:19:58','Very insightful post. Too bad people tend to be so in love with their tools that they forget that there\'s no solution for all kinds of applications.\n\nI must admit I\'m a little sad seeing how Ajax is all in the news with things that could be done with Flash (or Flex) years ago.',0,'1','','',0,0),(131,71,'Fabio Terracini','fabio@augsp.com.br','http://www.cfgigolo.com','','2006-09-06 10:24:45','2006-09-06 10:24:45','Good point. I\'ve presented on this topic on our local AUG (AUG-SP):\n\nAdobe Flex and Ajax demystified\nhttp://www.augsp.com.br/UserFiles/File/enc06Jun06/flex_e_ajax_augsp_junho2006.swf\n\nIt\'s in portuguese, but the slides are pretty much illustrated.\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(132,71,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry/','','2006-09-06 12:22:22','2006-09-06 12:22:22','Whoa.  I\'m glad I don\'t speak Portuguese, or I\'d be guilty of plagarism. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(133,72,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2006-09-12 10:44:06','2006-09-12 10:44:06','That wasn\'t it for me. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(134,72,'Dave','dave@lifelikeweeds.com','http://www.lifelikeweeds.com','','2006-09-12 08:55:11','2006-09-12 08:55:11','The \"Getting Started with Apollo\" session was dropped from my schedule.',0,'1','','',0,0),(135,73,'Steve','steve@ellernet.com','http://www.ellernet.com','','2006-09-14 11:08:25','2006-09-14 11:08:25','i\'d love to help test your cigar application. Very interested to see what kind of web application this is.  :)',0,'1','','',0,0),(136,73,'Ryan Guill','ryanguill@gmail.com','http://www.ryanguill.com/blog/','','2006-09-14 08:15:18','2006-09-14 08:15:18','I would love to help in the name of progress...',0,'1','','',0,0),(137,73,'Jimbo','jim@jimbo.us','http://jimbo.us','','2006-09-14 07:49:34','2006-09-14 07:49:34','If you can use an Arturo Fuente 8-5-8 lover, I\'m in.',0,'1','','',0,0),(138,73,'Drama Queen','weshouldbegms@hotmail.com','http://pabaseball.blogspot.com','','2006-09-16 09:29:29','2006-09-16 09:29:29','I have a funny and thoughtful Phillies blog that I think you might enjoy.  Come check it out at http://pabaseball.blogspotcom\n\nHope to see you there!',0,'1','','',0,0),(139,73,'furiousBall','vank@furiousBall.com','http://furiousball.com','','2006-09-19 15:45:47','2006-09-19 15:45:47','I\'m a developer, not much of a cigar smoker, but I do enjoy one now and then. I\'d be happy to help.',0,'1','','',0,0),(140,73,'Campbell','campbell@xsive.co.nz','http://blog.xsive.co.nz','','2006-09-14 00:55:02','2006-09-14 00:55:02','Ill give you an hour of my time bro.....',0,'1','','',0,0),(141,73,'TJ Downes','koldfuzun@gmail.com','','','2006-09-14 01:32:20','2006-09-14 01:32:20','Count me in! I am a casual smoker these days, but Ill smoke as much as necessary in the interest of furthering technology!',0,'1','','',0,0),(142,73,'Toby Tremayne','toby@lyricist.com.au','http://www.lyricist.com.au','','2006-09-14 03:28:41','2006-09-14 03:28:41','Yeah I\'m up for it - I love a good cigar, preferably with a good whiskey :)',0,'1','','',0,0),(143,73,'Al Davidson','apdavidson@gmail.com','http://instantbadger.blogspot.com','','2006-09-14 05:05:33','2006-09-14 05:05:33','I can\'t stand cigars myself, but my g.f. Lisa - who works for a user-centric design consultancy - loves \'em to bits. She\'d probably be willing to help.',0,'1','','',0,0),(144,73,'Marcos Placona','marcos.placona@gmail.com','','','2006-09-14 05:14:04','2006-09-14 05:14:04','Yes, count me in. Love cigars!',0,'1','','',0,0),(145,73,'Frederick','frederickwilliams@hotmail.com','http://frederickwilliams.blogspot.com','','2007-03-07 19:43:02','2007-03-07 19:43:02','I love cigars and I\'d love to help. I\'m really interested in what type of project you\'re working on.',0,'1','','',0,0),(146,73,'Nicholas Wache','nicholaswache@yahoo.com','http://rubydeveloper.blogspot.com','','2007-03-26 19:25:31','2007-03-26 19:25:31','It\'s really interesting to what lenghts men will go to forget about marriage. Good luck with your application.',0,'1','','',0,0),(147,73,'Ian Unger','ungeri@misericordia.edu','','','2007-09-30 03:03:17','2007-09-30 03:03:17','Hey, I am a big cigar fan.  I would love to test cigars or rate cigars for your website. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(148,73,'Walt K.','bosstaz01@hotmail.com','','','2008-01-30 13:33:24','2008-01-30 13:33:24','I\'m Cigar Smoker For Over 40 Yrs. Glad To Help!!  I would love to test cigars or rate cigars for your website. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(149,73,'tony','mafiosot11B3@yahoo.com','','','2008-09-30 19:11:30','2008-09-30 19:11:30','Im a casual smoker but love cigars. im drfiantly interested. pleeeeaaassseeee let me test',0,'1','','',0,0),(150,74,'John Garcia','garcia@john.com','','','2006-10-13 23:26:17','2006-10-13 23:26:17','I had the same problem when my design centered the content on the page but also centered the CF debug data.\n\nMy solution wasn\'t as good as yours but I removed the style for centering the content in dev and added it back when it went back into production.\n\nI will try this one next time.',0,'1','','',0,0),(151,74,'Ed Salsberg','steelvalor@gmail.com','http://www.steelvalor.com','','2007-06-21 11:07:03','2007-06-21 11:07:03','I\'ve recently broken into css and encountered the same problem so for those who look after this =D\n\n.cfdebug,.cfdebuglge{text-align:left}\n\noh, Nice Blog, is the source available?',0,'1','','',0,0),(152,74,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-06-24 20:28:48','2007-06-24 20:28:48','The blog is written with MovableType.',0,'1','','',0,0),(153,75,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2006-10-16 12:13:50','2006-10-16 12:13:50','Thanks for the encouragement, Ted. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(154,75,'Ted Patrick','tpatrick@adobe.com','','','2006-10-16 12:05:48','2006-10-16 12:05:48','No worries. Presenting is great practice and you will do just fine. I am pretty interested to see what you all are working on with Flex/Coldfusion at Wharton and I am sure others will be as well.\n\nReal projects, real people, MAXUP!\n\nSee you there!\n\nTed Patrick ',0,'1','','',0,0),(155,76,'Scott','smcnulty@gmail.com','http://blog.blankbaby.com/','','2006-10-17 09:55:30','2006-10-17 09:55:30','I kid, Terry, I kid.  No guilt should be felt by anyone (other than the normal guilt that is associated with growing up Catholic).',0,'1','','',0,0),(156,76,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2006-10-16 21:24:56','2006-10-16 21:24:56','Dave: Sorry.\nAdrian: Yes I still have it on mine. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(157,76,'Adrian J. Moreno','amoreno@iKnowKungFoo.com','','','2006-10-16 17:49:31','2006-10-16 17:49:31','I logged in just now to check my schedule and \"The Big Framework and Methodology Debate\" is gone from my calendar. I can\'t even find it listed anymore. Do you still have it scheduled Terrence?',0,'1','','',0,0),(158,76,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2006-10-16 17:01:06','2006-10-16 17:01:06','John, ask me for tips about cigars?  You\'ll have trouble shutting me up.  I\'d be happy to make give you some pointers. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(159,76,'Dave Shuck','dshuck@gmail.com','http://www.daveshuck.com','','2006-10-16 17:27:12','2006-10-16 17:27:12','And so it begins... Next, the less fortunate of us get to endure the barrage of \"Max is awesome this year!\" live posts to everyone\'s blogs like CFUnited a couple of months back!  Only then I was one of the posters! <grrrr>\n\nEnjoy! :)',0,'1','','',0,0),(160,76,'John Dowdell','supportinfo@macromedia.com','http://weblogs.macromedia.com/jd','','2006-10-16 16:25:00','2006-10-16 16:25:00','One nice thing about Las Vegas is the ventilation systems... coming from San Francisco it\'s nice to be able to smoke indoors, among other people.\n\nIf we meet up, could you give me some tips about cigars, Terry? I usually smoke a pipe, but have been trying small cigars in social situations, and really don\'t know much yet. Thanks!\n\njd',0,'1','','',0,0),(161,76,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2006-10-16 15:48:56','2006-10-16 15:48:56','Scott, there\'s no need to try and make me feel more guilty that you aren\'t going. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(162,76,'Scott','smcnulty@gmail.com','http://blog.blankbaby.com','','2006-10-16 14:44:42','2006-10-16 14:44:42','What is this \'Max\' you keep talking about? ;)',0,'1','','',0,0),(163,81,'Ben Nadel','ben@bennadel.com','http://www.bennadel.com','','2006-10-25 08:13:50','2006-10-25 08:13:50','Yeah that is cool. Also, perhaps my favorite Java string method for use in ColdFusion is ReplaceAll() and ReplaceFirst(). These use regular expressions and are much faster than the CF equivalents.',0,'1','','',0,0),(164,81,'Brandon Harper','ieatspam@gmail.com','http://devnulled.com','','2006-10-26 00:34:15','2006-10-26 00:34:15','Yes, JAlpino is correct.  If you need to do much string manipulation, use StringBuffers.  Strings in Java are immutable objects, so at least one new object must be created when you \"change\" a String.',0,'1','','',0,0),(165,81,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2006-10-26 01:33:22','2006-10-26 01:33:22','I subtly diagree with you, Brandon.  I would say if you have to <strong>optimize</strong> string manipulation, use StringBuffers.',0,'1','','',0,0),(166,81,'Mark Mandel','mark@compoundtheory.com','http://www.compoundtheory.com','','2006-10-25 19:32:53','2006-10-25 19:32:53','I\'ve always liked the string method .startsWith() much easier to use.\n\nLet\'s not also forget -\n\nParsed Dates are java.util.Date\nArrays are java.util.Vector\nStructs are java.util.Hashmap\nQuery results are java.sql.ResultSet\n\nthere are lots and lots out there ;o)',0,'1','','',0,0),(167,81,'JAlpino','jalpino@gmail.com','http://www.jalpino.com','','2006-10-25 09:49:41','2006-10-25 09:49:41','Don\'t forget about StringBuffers, they perform very well especially when building large strings.',0,'1','','',0,0),(168,81,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2006-10-25 11:26:02','2006-10-25 11:26:02','I haven\'t compared this method to StringBuffers yet. So much to try, so little time. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(169,81,'funny jokes man','njanjayrp@msn.com','http://myfunnybreak.com','','2008-06-28 11:56:54','2008-06-28 11:56:54','Great! I only recently started using Cold Fusion, and was just doing some research on it. It\'s good to know that ReplaceAll(); will work.',0,'1','','',0,0),(170,85,'Ashwin Mathew','amathew@adobe.com','http://blogs.sanmathi.org/ashwin/','','2006-10-31 09:40:53','2006-10-31 09:40:53','Hey, go easy on us, Terrence! We can\'t talk about a lot of the new stuff we\'re doing for a variety of reasons. Some are irritatingly legal; others are more practical - features are still evolving, and we don\'t want to show them off publicly before they have some meat on their bones. That said, if there\'s anything you do want to know (apart from the release date, my lips are sealed on that one!) you know where to find me.',0,'1','','',0,0),(171,85,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2006-10-31 09:56:18','2006-10-31 09:56:18','Ashwin, I was being totally light-hearted here. In fairness, I\'m impressed with your spy-like tightlippedness.  And frankly, I\'m so eager to find out more because you have really done a great job with what you have let show.',0,'1','','',0,0),(172,85,'Mark Fuqua','mark@mdprofinish.com','','','2006-10-26 20:06:05','2006-10-26 20:06:05','Scorpio will be leaked slowly over time.  Best for last I\'m sure',0,'1','','',0,0),(173,85,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2006-10-26 20:16:05','2006-10-26 20:16:05','I get that... It doesn\'t mean that I like it. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(174,87,'Ben Forta','ben@forta.com','http://forta.com/','','2006-11-08 09:43:13','2006-11-08 09:43:13','And don\'t forget that as of CFMX7 you can use RESULT to rename many of those hard coded return structures.\n\n--- Ben',0,'1','','',0,0),(175,87,'Ben Nadel','ben@bennadel.com','http://www.bennadel.com','','2006-11-08 07:47:35','2006-11-08 07:47:35','Terrence,\n\nSorry, I think when I first read it, I didn\'t quite understand what you were saying. I see. I read it too fast.\n\nAny thoughts on FILE vs. CFFILE?\n\nExcellent post by the way.',0,'1','','',0,0),(176,87,'bethb','bethbowden@earthlink.net','','','2007-01-17 11:49:17','2007-01-17 11:49:17','Also, \"CFLOOP\" and \"CFSAVECONTENT\"',0,'1','','',0,0),(177,87,'Ben Nadel','ben@bennadel.com','http://www.bennadel.com','','2006-11-07 20:57:33','2006-11-07 20:57:33','I could be way off here, but I could swear that I remember trying to \"var\" scope the CFFILE results:\n\n&lt;cfset var CFFILE = \"\" /&gt;\n\nand it gave me some sort of error about dereferencing scalar objects as though they were structs with properties.\n\nOh, and that makes me thinkg of something else... doesn\'t ColdFusion create backwards compatable structures? I think for a CFFILE tag it creates both a CFFILE and a FILE structure. Do both need to be var\'d? Hmmmm.\n\nPerhaps the best thing to do would be to use the \"result\" attribute for any tag that can take it and var that.\n\nI haven\'t tested any of that though, so forgive me if I am misleading.',0,'1','','',0,0),(178,87,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2006-11-07 21:15:47','2006-11-07 21:15:47','I touched on this a bit in the post Ben, but I didn\'t make it very clear. Structs needs to be initialized as structs. So it should be : &lt;cfset cffile = StructNew() /&gt;.  That would prevent the error. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(179,87,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2006-11-08 11:03:07','2006-11-08 11:03:07','Ben Nadel: Can you give me an example of this file and cffile thing?  I can\'t seem to reproduce it.\n\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(180,88,'Barney','bboisvert@gmail.com','http://www.barneyb.com/','','2006-11-09 16:19:17','2006-11-09 16:19:17','This actually has nothing to do with the \'this\' scope, but rather just general thread safety issues.  You\'d run into the same problem if you used the \'variables\' scope.  The reason for not using the \'this\' scope is that it\'s publicly readable and writable outside the CFC, wheras the \'variables\' scope is not.\n\nWhen you use shared-scope objects, you must ensure that the only instance-level state is request-agnostic.  If that\'s impossible, you need to use a request-aware scope to house the data a la a java.lang.ThreadLocal.  Fortunately (or unfortunately) CF has that built-in with the request scope, which you can use from anywhere.  Just be aware of what you\'re doing and clearly document the dependancy.',0,'1','','',0,0),(181,88,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2006-11-09 16:52:33','2006-11-09 16:52:33','Well I chalk it up to the this scope as I had var scoped all of the other variables, and thought I had  made it thread safe.  The bigger point there might be \"There\'s more to thread safe CFC\'s then just the var scope.\"\n\nIn any case it was horribly architected all around.  ',0,'1','','',0,0),(182,88,'Tony Petruzzi','tonyp@rolist.com','http://rip747.wordpress.com','','2006-11-09 20:49:22','2006-11-09 20:49:22','this (pun intended) is why I can\'t stand applications that throw their CFC into the application scope. Everyone thinks that you get a performance gain by doing it, I have never seen it. Start using good old cfinvoke. I can almost bet that you could of kept your CFC the way it was, by using cfinvoke and it would of worked just fine.',0,'1','','',0,0),(183,88,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2006-11-10 10:29:46','2006-11-10 10:29:46','I actually stand by CFC\'s in the application scope. You just have to write them correctly.\n\nBut you are right about the cfinvoke for this particular CFC. That was the way it was *intended* to be used. However once you start sharing code, how you intend to use it, and how it is used aren\'t the same.  That\'s when proper coding can save you a bunch of headaches.  ',0,'1','','',0,0),(184,89,'Jeff Porten','civitan@jeffporten.com','http://www.jeffporten.com','','2006-11-30 19:10:03','2006-11-30 19:10:03','The situation gets even more confusing when a reader mistakenly presumes you\'re referring to chlorofluorocarbons.',0,'1','','',0,0),(185,89,'Adam Cameron','adam_junk@hotmail.com','','','2006-12-01 08:30:40','2006-12-01 08:30:40','Michael... whilst that\'s all very interesing... how does all that make it difficult to give the local scope a NAME?\n\n--\nAdam',0,'1','','',0,0),(186,89,'Michael Dinowitz','mdinowit@houseoffusion.com','http://www.houseoffusion.com/groups/CF-Talk','','2006-11-30 17:20:05','2006-11-30 17:20:05','It gets a little complicated under the hood as a UDFs \'local\' scope can be assigned variables in 4 different ways. The first are variables passed into the UDF that also have a CFARGUMENT tag. Variables passed into a UDF without a matching CFARGUMENT tag are NOT automatically part of the local scope. The second are the result of CFARGUMENT tags with default values. The third are CFARGUMENT tags without default values, but this is a special case. CFArgument tags without a default and without a passed value create a \'space holder\' for a local variable that can be filled within the UDF. The fourth are variables set with a var prefix inside the UDF.\n\nI cover this in depth in my \"From User-Defined Functions to ColdFusion Components\" chapter in the latest FAQ-U (small plug). :)',0,'1','','',0,0),(187,90,'Brian Deitte','brian@deitte.com','http://www.deitte.com','','2006-12-06 12:35:36','2006-12-06 12:35:36','If this comment shows up, then it worked for me.  :)\n\nI use Movable Type 3.3.  I changed some of the scorings (and enabled everything) for the built-in SpamLookup plugins.  I also installed AutoBan:\n\nhttp://blog.thought-mesh.net/solidwallofcode/mt_projects/autoban.php\n\nWith these settings, I only get a couple of spam messages that aren\'t junked each day.\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(188,90,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2006-12-06 13:10:53','2006-12-06 13:10:53','Unfortunately, I cannot use autoban. My webhost uses IIS instead of Apache. Good to know it\'s all working though.  We\'ll see what it does to my spam.',0,'1','','',0,0),(189,90,'Ryan Stewart','ryan@ryanstewart.net','http://blog.digitalbackcountry.com','','2006-12-07 03:32:29','2006-12-07 03:32:29','Dude. Wordpress and Akismet. I never have spam problems any more.',0,'1','','',0,0),(190,90,'Dmitry Yakhnov','dmitry@yakhnov.info','http://www.yakhnov.info/','','2006-12-07 21:46:32','2006-12-07 21:46:32','I am using text math operation instead of CAPTCHA, which quite easy to broke :)',0,'1','','',0,0),(191,90,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2006-12-08 15:57:49','2006-12-08 15:57:49','Ryan: I really don\'t want to change blogging software.  Like I said, if I did I would come over to BlogCFC.\n\nDmitry: That sounds very cool.  What blogging tool are you using?',0,'1','','',0,0),(192,91,'Dave','dave@lifelikeweeds.com','http://www.lifelikeweeds.com','','2006-12-18 09:12:01','2006-12-18 09:12:01','Thanks for #2 - glad you like the design. I\'m a big fan of mocking up before hitting html. I do a lot of free form sketching on paper to work through initial ideas. Then I move to a graphics app. Sometimes I pick a display font, or sometimes colors if I don\'t have any previous logo or other visual element to work with -- just something to set the tone on the screen. It helps me to lay out five, maybe seven column lines to guide the process. I find that helpful in establishing a balance, but also in finding subtle ways to break out of boxy design.',0,'1','','',0,0),(193,91,'Dan Wilson','sipacate@gmail.com','','','2006-12-17 11:03:27','2006-12-17 11:03:27','I often have a go at Open Source Web Design ( http://www.oswd.org/ ) for inspiration. Once I find something I like, I begin to customize and who knows what i\'ll end up with. I just don\'t like starting with a blank slate.\n\n\ndw\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(194,91,'Ben N