2:28','Guys I am using blogspot.com for blogging.\n\nI am unable to publish pics on my blog through\nword 2007.\n\nCan anybody tell me the required setting for using picassaweb in word 2007  ',0,'1','','',0,0),(219,97,'Mark Drew','mark.drew@gmail.com','http://www.markdrew.co.uk','','2007-01-26 09:44:42','2007-01-26 09:44:42','That is really odd, there are NO .bat files in the release.... what is Vista doing???',0,'1','','',0,0),(220,97,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-01-26 10:31:12','2007-01-26 10:31:12','Mark, I hardly think you\'re in a position to know what is and is not in CFeclipse....\n\nOh wait.\n\nI\'ll do a little more experimenting, and see if I can isolate what is happening.  ',0,'1','','',0,0),(221,97,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-01-26 10:48:32','2007-01-26 10:48:32','Here\'s the error message I get:\n\nUnable to complete action for feature \"CFEclipse\" due to errors.\n  Unable to create file \"/c:/Program Files/Adobe/Flex Builder 2/plugins/org.cfeclipse.cfml_1.3.0 dictionary/preprocess.bat\". [c:Program FilesAdobeFlex Builder 2pluginsorg.cfeclipse.cfml_1.3.0 dictionarypreprocess.bat (Access is denied)]\n\n\nSo it might be relavant that I\'m running CFEclipse as a stand alone build of Flex Builder.\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(222,97,'Mark Drew','mark.drew@gmail.com','http://www.markdrew.co.uk','','2007-01-26 13:35:19','2007-01-26 13:35:19','Aha... that is a leftover file from some conversions I think (or a pre-processor we were working on) talk about fascist OS!\n\nWill remove it before vista becomes (like all virus) prevolent.',0,'1','','',0,0),(223,97,'Mark Drew','mark.drew@gmail.com','http://www.markdrew.co.uk','','2007-01-31 13:14:52','2007-01-31 13:14:52','I thought I would let you know that this wont be an issue in the next release as it has been removed from the source code.\n\nThanks for pointing it out.',0,'1','','',0,0),(224,97,'Otel','romanticapart@hotmail.com','http://www.romanticapart.com','','2008-06-02 01:28:59','2008-06-02 01:28:59','very thanks.',0,'1','','',0,0),(225,97,'Free games','azbord@gmail.com','http://www.favplay.com','','2008-09-01 19:05:40','2008-09-01 19:05:40','Amazing work mate, you helped me a lot and save me a couple of days of hard work.\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(226,97,'earth4energy','jasontpopper@gmail.com','http://earth4energymanual.net','','2008-09-26 20:58:17','2008-09-26 20:58:17','great, interesting thanks',0,'1','','',0,0),(227,97,'north cyprus hotels','cypforum@hotmail.com','http://www.northerncyprusholidays.org','','2008-09-27 05:34:20','2008-09-27 05:34:20','I like very much the writings and pictures and explanations  in your adress so I look forward to see your next writings. I congratulate you.',0,'1','','',0,0),(228,98,'Kris Brixon','kris.brixon@gmail.com','','','2007-01-31 18:58:30','2007-01-31 18:58:30','Awesome, I did something recently similar for Oracle but without the stored procedures. I needed to make a prototype and creating a code generator was quicker than writing the CRUD functions. What language did you write this in? Writing a code generator in CF for CF is confusing.',0,'1','','',0,0),(229,98,'Rick Mason','Rick@Coldfusion.org','','','2007-01-31 21:25:36','2007-01-31 21:25:36','I think that it would help a lot of people.  There are lots of good reasons to used stored procedures and it would automate things for many with homegrown frameworks.',0,'1','','',0,0),(230,98,'Nathan Drury','rustyaxe@gmail.com','','','2007-01-31 22:08:43','2007-01-31 22:08:43','Sounds great.  Would be very useful for me.  I\'m interested in code generation so it would be interesting from a \"how did he do it\" perspective too.',0,'1','','',0,0),(231,98,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-02-01 09:12:40','2007-02-01 09:12:40','Great, well I\'ll clean up the code and make it available publicly then. Expect something next week. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(232,98,'Peter Bell','pbell@systemsforge.com','http://www.pbell.com','','2007-02-06 08:43:52','2007-02-06 08:43:52','Hi Terrence, Glad to see you\'re drinking the Kool-aid :-> Looks like a great project and I see it is up on RIA Forge at http://squidhead.riaforge.org/. Will definitely have to check this out!',0,'1','','',0,0),(233,98,'Peter Bell','pbell@systemsforge.com','http://www.pbell.com','','2007-02-06 08:49:17','2007-02-06 08:49:17','BTW, any tricks for how you put the flash demo together or did you just do it manually in flash?',0,'1','','',0,0),(234,98,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-02-06 09:24:22','2007-02-06 09:24:22','Thanks for the encouragement, Peter.\n\nActually, I made the demos with an Adobe product named Captivate (used to be RoboDemo). It\'s really a good product that makes doing that sort of thing, extremely easy. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(235,98,'Phillip Senn','psenn@alexlee.com','http://www.aacr9.com','','2007-02-13 11:08:31','2007-02-13 11:08:31','This is really great!  By the time a programmer starts copying/pasting the same subroutine (sproc) for the 3rd or 4th time, he starts to think about an application generator.\nI encourage you to take a look at Paul Nielsen\'s logging stored procedure that he\'s posted at www.sqlserverbible.com.\nIt looks at all the tables and builds triggers to log any changes.\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(236,98,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-02-14 12:01:43','2007-02-14 12:01:43','Thanks Phil, I\'ll check it out. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(237,100,'J.Cruz','jcruz@wharton.upenn.edu','http://guamaniac.wordpress.com','','2007-02-06 15:44:08','2007-02-06 15:44:08','Excellent write-up, Terry!  I especially like the color-coded comments with varying severity levels.  Reminds me of the National Terror Alert or some such.\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(238,100,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-02-06 15:59:11','2007-02-06 15:59:11','Thanks Joe. I learned it by watching you. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(239,100,'Rob Brooks- Bilson','rbils@amkor.com','http://www.brooks-bilson.com/blogs/rob/','','2007-02-06 15:59:13','2007-02-06 15:59:13','Terrence,\n\nOne other area you might consider is automated code reviews.  This isn\'t a replacement for human code reviews, but it can be a nice way to  complement them.\n\nFor ColdFusion, there\'s a tool called CodeCop by Steve Bryant that\'s worth a look.  It lets you create rules which the engine will apply against your code.  You could (fairly) easily create rules for most of your coding standards/guidelines and have the engine perform a first-pass code review.  Check it out here:\n\nhttp://www.bryantwebconsulting.com/products/codecop.cfm',0,'1','','',0,0),(240,100,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-02-07 00:45:42','2007-02-07 00:45:42','Thanks, Rob. I gave that product a while back.  I think he created it for a Ray Camden contest.  I tried in its first incarnation, and hadn\'t tried it again.\n\nI\'ll give it another shot. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(241,102,'mark','fennell@armc.org','','','2008-04-14 12:05:18','2008-04-14 12:05:18','So, do you have any quick and easy solutions of finding out if a user is already a member of a group? Thanks.\nmf',0,'1','','',0,0),(242,103,'charlie griefer','charlie@griefer.com','http://charlie.griefer.com','','2007-02-14 12:37:39','2007-02-14 12:37:39','it took me three attempts to make the switch from HS+ to Eclipse/CFE.\n\ni never used to work in \"projects\" and that was a big hurdle for me.  the rest was just getting used to the environment.  HS+ had become so much my \"comfort zone\" that i just couldn\'t make the break, and always seemed to end up going back to it.\n\nfinally, on my 3rd attempt to switch over, i just forced myself to do it, and now i can\'t look back.  biggest things i like (about eclipse in general) is the concept of the plugins.\n\nwith CFE, Aptana, and JSEclipse... i\'ve pretty much got my ideal IDE.',0,'1','','',0,0),(243,103,'john','jherr@johnherr.net','','','2007-03-15 17:12:19','2007-03-15 17:12:19','Have you found a way to use CFEclipse in association with Dreamweaver\'s check-in/check-out?\n\nI\'m using Aptana.',0,'1','','',0,0),(244,103,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-03-16 23:51:13','2007-03-16 23:51:13','Are you referring to vss integration?\n\nIf so there is a vss plugin for eclipse. If not can you explain the dreamweaver feature you are talking about in greater detail.',0,'1','','',0,0),(245,103,'john','herr@mail.fpg.unc.edu','','','2007-03-20 10:21:35','2007-03-20 10:21:35','Not really vss, but very similar.  Basically Dreamweaver\'s version works like this: when a user \"check\'s out\" a file, DW ftps a .LCK file (plaintext) with the user\'s name.  On \"check in\" that file is deleted.\n\nI think I\'m going to roll my own if I can\'t find anything -- it\'s just too easy.',0,'1','','',0,0),(246,103,'honda new jersey','gorav@gmail.com','http://www.planethondanj.com/','','2009-11-23 02:36:01','2009-11-23 02:36:01','Well this is very interesting indeed.Would love to read a little more of this. Great post. Thanks for the heads-upThis blog was very informative and knowledgeable',0,'1','','',0,0),(247,104,'Ryan Stewart','ryan@ryanstewart.net','http://blog.digitalbackcountry.com','','2007-02-15 15:34:20','2007-02-15 15:34:20','MySQL ;). I\'ve played with Squidhead on my MS SQL box at home, but I\'d love to be able to use it for our production environment. MS SQL is way too expensive. so we\'re using MySQL.\n\nAs long as you can do MySQL support at SOME time, I\'ll be a happy camper!',0,'1','','',0,0),(248,104,'Michael Wolfe','vws@visionary-art.com','','','2007-02-15 14:00:28','2007-02-15 14:00:28','Go for the MSSQL updates, and add in support for MySQL when you can.',0,'1','','',0,0),(249,105,'J.Cruz','jcruz@wharton.upenn.edu','http://guamaniac.wordpress.com','','2007-02-18 01:07:52','2007-02-18 01:07:52','This is a great perspective, Terry, and seems quite logical.  What to do, then, when all you are is \"weak spots\"?  :)',0,'1','','',0,0),(250,105,'Peter Boughton','cf_blog@bpsite.co.uk','http://blog.bpsite.net','','2007-02-18 08:03:58','2007-02-18 08:03:58','>> What to do, then, when all you are is \"weak spots\"?\n\nPick something. Learn it.',0,'1','','',0,0),(251,105,'Sammy Larbi','sam@codeodor.com','http://www.codeodor.com','','2007-02-18 09:41:38','2007-02-18 09:41:38','I like that you cleared that up using the 80-20 rule.  Almost certainly in the case of an ORM you will be more productive using it that writing your own stuff, and it will be useful for (likely more than) 80% of your cases.\n\nBut (not sure why this font is getting big, but I put a space in above and it seems to have gone away) I would caution not to just assume that \"my solution is better than theirs\" because that is your expertise.  That may be true - but your solution may still take longer and produce something better than \"good enough,\" in which case, you\'ve still wasted your time.\n\nTo me, Joel\'s article read more about not outsourcing your primary business function - not your primary talent.  So for instance, if you were selling data mining services, you might want to write your own applications for it.  But, if you can make use of Reactor (which, you may or may not be able to do), then you still might do that.  But, if you were selling ORM frameworks, you might not want to use Reactor to do it.  That\'s how I took it anyway.  I know the Excel example didn\'t focus too much on that - but they had other, internal reasons for not wanting to use others\' code, that I\'m not sure apply to this situation as well as they might to others.',0,'1','','',0,0),(252,105,'Sammy Larbi','sam@codeodor.com','http://www.codeodor.com','','2007-02-18 09:44:02','2007-02-18 09:44:02','In any case, the point of the framework is to assist you.  If you run into to points where you are fighting it to do what you want to do - then you should be able to drop out of it for a second and just do what you want to do.  That doesn\'t mean you would completely give up the framework, however.  You use it to build what it can, and ignore it for the things it can\'t.',0,'1','','',0,0),(253,105,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-02-18 22:42:40','2007-02-18 22:42:40','Sammy: I admit that I am extrapolating from Joel\'s piece, but I think that the logic is still sound.  Don\'t let someone else do what adds value to your customers.  I would also add, that someone who has a better way than a particular framework, could still be better off, if they automate their own \"framework\" instead of using someone else\'s. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(254,105,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-02-18 22:46:54','2007-02-18 22:46:54','Joe: Ironic that you would ask that, being as you\'re an expert in some pretty diverse areas of knowledge.  But I would say, at some point you\'re going to have to add value to the people paying your fees/paycheck. So if you\'re just weak spots, then get rid of one... fast. But I\'d argue that people that are all weak spots technically speaking, usually provide some other value to the people that pay them. In which case they should defer to technical experts for everything technical, and leverage their soft skills to add value.',0,'1','','',0,0),(255,105,'Craig M. Rosenblum','crosenblum@gmail.com','http://cfpurists.blogspot.com','','2007-04-06 17:08:20','2007-04-06 17:08:20','I have to say the same, I would love to be more efficient, and I personally haven\'t seen a framework that screams to me, yep this is the one for you.\n\nWhat bothers me the most about framework\'s is the proselytizing, everyone does, implying your a sucky programmer if you don\'t program with a certain framework or any framework.\n\nI think there are things we can learn from frameworks, but me, i am still waiting for the fish to come and bite me.\n\nAnd I do like Joel Spolsky, he has a lot of common sense, also like Jeff Atwood\'s Coding Horror.\n\nI mean, good architecture helps, unless the creation of that architecture gets in the way of you doing your job.\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(256,106,'Dave Konopka','dave@lifelikeweeds.com','http://www.lifelikeweeds.com/tech','','2007-02-21 08:59:48','2007-02-21 08:59:48','The only thing I don\'t like about this implementation is that the formatting of the code ends up locked in Function.cfc. For me, this is similar to the debate over custom tags versus CFC\'s for interface code.\n\nThe code ends up being a formatted document that developers will eventually read. I\'d be willing to trade performance to make that document format easier to change.\n\nI don\'t like having to edit string concatenations buried in a cfc function to change the layout of the code, or to change the format of something usually personalized like comment flower boxes.',0,'1','','',0,0),(257,106,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-02-21 09:49:42','2007-02-21 09:49:42','That\'s a good point, Dave, and that is why it does break down the less structured the resulting code is. I\'d argue that with functions, storedproc\'s, and cfc\'s there are a finite set of permutations because there are a finite set of attributes for the code structures. You may quibble over formatting or  order of calls, but I think that tradeoff is worth it.  With custom tags and cfml templates, one could argue that it isn\'t. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(258,106,'reolica','judy4121@qq.com','http://www.watchvisa.com','','2009-12-09 01:37:32','2009-12-09 01:37:32','Instead, replica watches will head up rolex watches north to Toronto breiting watches to be the everyday tag heuer watches shortstop ahead of another cartier watches middle infielder of the all-field, omega watches, no-hit variety, John McDonald.\nhttp://www.mybagsvip.com',0,'1','','',0,0),(259,106,'reolica handbags','judy4121@qq.com','http://www.mybagsvip.com','','2009-12-09 01:40:35','2009-12-09 01:40:35','His decision to replica handbags sign elsewhere, though, limits the wholesale handbags Red Soxs search for a shortstop. The free agent market at the position is louis vuitton handbags extremely weak, and, barring a trade, the prospects for a replacement are pretty bleak',0,'1','','',0,0),(260,107,'Kelly Murphy','kmurphy@vtforge.com','','','2008-08-07 11:47:08','2008-08-07 11:47:08','An answer to the N question (in case you haven\'t gotten it yet).\n\nIf you are not using the listGroups attribute, leave it at its default which is \"no\". The user will not authenticate if the number of characters returned by listGroups is > 469.\n\nI found this at http://livedocs.adobe.com/coldfusion/7/htmldocs/wwhelp/wwhimpl/common/html/wwhelp.htm?context=ColdFusion_Documentation&file=00000301.htm\n\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(261,107,'Daniel Scott','daniel.scott@biomet.com','','','2009-11-10 09:45:07','2009-11-10 09:45:07','Can you post the source for the secure LDAP CFC that you created?  I\'d like to see it.',0,'1','','',0,0),(262,108,'Janice','janice@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/janice/blog/','','2007-02-27 22:13:57','2007-02-27 22:13:57','Don\'t worry.  All traces of it have been removed from the script I was working on.  Delete all your copies and never speak of this again.  It will be like it never happened. :)',0,'1','','',0,0),(263,108,'Jeff Porten','civitan@jeffporten.com','http://www.jeffporten.com','','2007-02-28 16:45:52','2007-02-28 16:45:52','I hope that at least she fixed your abyssmal punctuation.',0,'1','','',0,0),(264,109,'Peter Bell','pbell@systemsforge.com','http://www.pbell.com','','2007-03-01 01:43:02','2007-03-01 01:43:02','I use package protection sometimes - the trick is in your directory structuring. When I first wrote LightBase, I also put DAOs together, Service classes together and so on.\n\nThen I thought about package protection and realized that you want to do things like make UserDAO only available to UserService to enforce service methods as API. As such, you put UserDAO, User and UserService into model.User. Same for model.product and so on.\n\nThat is working out REALLY well for me, so I\'ve found that package protection was not only useful, but also helped me to put my files together in what I now find to be a better structure with all of the class files for a give business object in the same directory.',0,'1','','',0,0),(265,110,'Danlance','danlance@gmail.com','http://www.danlance.co.uk/index.cfm/imified','','2007-03-29 19:57:31','2007-03-29 19:57:31','Did you have any luck with inserting line breaks?  I could not work out how to do that - but that may be something to do with BlogCFC rather than imified...',0,'1','','',0,0),(266,110,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-03-29 21:09:55','2007-03-29 21:09:55','Truthfully I gave up on it.  I didn\'t use enough services to keep using Imified.',0,'1','','',0,0),(267,112,'Mike Kollen','mike@nospam.com','','','2007-03-08 01:28:43','2007-03-08 01:28:43','Just making an educated guess, but I would be willing to bet that \"8\" stands for Scorpio 8, and not the month number.  It will be released in 2007, though.',0,'1','','',0,0),(268,112,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-03-08 01:42:51','2007-03-08 01:42:51','I\'d buy that, except that other versions of the  wallpaper display an 8 and the 2007.  This one has an 8, AND the line 8 : 2007.',0,'1','','',0,0),(269,112,'Dale Fraser','dale@fraser.id.au','http://dale.fraser.id.au/','','2007-03-08 02:16:40','2007-03-08 02:16:40','I think I would have to agree that the 8 is version 8 and that 2007 is the year it was released.\n\nI actually think you might see it before August given it\'s currrent status.',0,'1','','',0,0),(270,112,'Peter Tilbrook','peter@tilbrook.name','http://www.actcfug.com/','','2007-03-08 02:26:11','2007-03-08 02:26:11','Could be (August is the 8th month).\n\nI hope it is released well before then though.',0,'1','','',0,0),(271,112,'Ashwin','amathew@adobe.com','http://blogs.sanmathi.org/ashwin','','2007-03-08 04:26:42','2007-03-08 04:26:42','8=infinity, sideways. Go figure!\nYep, definitely screwing with you... ;)',0,'1','','',0,0),(272,112,'dc','david.collie@gmail.com','','','2007-03-08 07:51:59','2007-03-08 07:51:59','All I know is that &lt;8:2007/&gt; would never validate ;)',0,'1','','',0,0),(273,112,'Jacob Munson','yacoubean@gmail.com','http://techfeed.net/blog/','','2007-03-08 14:41:57','2007-03-08 14:41:57','Adobe has said that Scorpio is scheduled to be released this summer.  I\'d be willing to bet money that it will be announced at CFUnited at the end of June.',0,'1','','',0,0),(274,112,'Cutter','no.junk@cutterscrossing.com','http://blog.cutterscrossing.com','','2007-03-08 15:06:57','2007-03-08 15:06:57','I\'m thinking CFUnited keynote',0,'1','','',0,0),(275,112,'Damon Cooper','dcooper@adobe.com','http://www.dcooper.org','','2007-03-08 16:18:29','2007-03-08 16:18:29','Summer = June 21-September 23, for the record :)\n\nDamon',0,'1','','',0,0),(276,112,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-03-08 16:48:55','2007-03-08 16:48:55','@Jacob I agree that you they could announce its release date then.  But I haven\'t even seen a public beta of it yet. I feel like June would be really cutting it close.',0,'1','','',0,0),(277,112,'mark','markfoolr@aol.com','','','2007-09-08 23:47:50','2007-09-08 23:47:50','August had pass.Scorpio is ok?',0,'1','','',0,0),(278,112,'warehouse','info@afasfdasdfa.com','http://www.simplestorage.com.hk/en/warehouse-about.html','','2007-09-14 22:25:23','2007-09-14 22:25:23','But I haven\'t even seen a public beta of it yet. I feel like June would be really cutting it close. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(279,114,'Robby Dhillon','djrobby@gmail.com','http://rdx-solutions.com','','2007-03-27 23:47:37','2007-03-27 23:47:37','You know I have been on this boat since day one. I am yet to see the kind of execution times produced by Stored Procedures using other methods.  Simply, lightening fast!!! Good work Terry, keep it up :)',0,'1','','',0,0),(280,114,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-03-28 01:29:26','2007-03-28 01:29:26','I did not know that Robby, but I\'m glad to know it now.\n\nTo be fair I feel like I need to point out that queries with cfqueryparam often execute as fast as stored procs, and with caching you can get better performance still.\n\nBut I still prefer stored procedures. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(281,115,'kola','kolasmail@gmail.com','http://www.coolskool.blog-city.com','','2007-04-02 10:08:13','2007-04-02 10:08:13','Hey Glad you\'re liking Jupiter - it has been a while since I played with it and by the sounds of it, it seems like it has come some way - and worth another look.\n\nKola',0,'1','','',0,0),(282,115,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-04-03 01:35:24','2007-04-03 01:35:24','Yeah, Kola, it\'s sped up my code review process (at least the evaluation side of things) immensely. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(283,115,'Thomas','ranking@ranking-charts.at','','','2007-09-12 05:43:36','2007-09-12 05:43:36','hi , where can i get the jupiter tool? thank your very much mades',0,'1','','',0,0),(284,115,'jk','jk@hvkamlowski.de','','','2007-09-13 14:29:12','2007-09-13 14:29:12','Thanks for the article - great to know it!',0,'1','','',0,0),(285,115,'Maca','marc@fitness-am.de','','','2007-09-14 00:22:48','2007-09-14 00:22:48','nice tool! ',0,'1','','',0,0),(286,115,'Nils','webmaster@tarif-angebote.de','http://tarif-angebote.de','','2007-10-16 10:29:35','2007-10-16 10:29:35','I discovered Jupiter a few months ago.. It really is a gem. Used it in the development of a recent big community project and it helped a lot indeed.\nSo.. kudos to the developers!',0,'1','','',0,0),(287,115,'David Deutsch','daviddeutschster@gmail.com','http://daviddeutsch.de','','2008-05-08 05:03:33','2008-05-08 05:03:33','Interesting post, I guess it\'s a good idea to subscribe to your RSS Feed cause I searched for sth like this a few months ago (without success).\n\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(288,115,'Jochen Jolli','webbfan@freenet.de','http://www.erlebnisgeschenke4u.de','','2008-05-13 08:13:06','2008-05-13 08:13:06','Great post, I subscribed to your feed as well, keep em coming!',0,'1','','',0,0),(289,115,'Friseur','pizzadude81@gmail.com','http://www.rolfundbernd.de','','2008-05-27 14:31:40','2008-05-27 14:31:40','Thanks for the article, very nice read...',0,'1','','',0,0),(290,116,'Gary Fenton','garygfx@gmail.com','','','2007-03-29 19:33:54','2007-03-29 19:33:54','Indeed, what is the big deal? In the days of CF5 and earlier it may have been a problem as far as adding a few Kb to the size of each page downloaded to browsers. But today we have two things that weren\'t practical back then - broadband and gzip.\n\nA year ago I activated HTTP compression on one of my client\'s sites and saw bandwidth consumption shrink dramatically, and anyone left using lowband would notice much faster page downloads - even with a hundred line of lines of white space.\n\nEvery browser supports compression and there are very few good reasons not to use it.\n\nThe only issues I\'ve encountered on a technical level because of white space are CF XML generated pages which cause some web services to complain and some doctype declariations that aren\'t at the top of the page which have messed up a browser\'s use of CSS.',0,'1','','',0,0),(291,116,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-03-29 21:35:04','2007-03-29 21:35:04','Gary I have to disagree.  The idea that broadband means we don\'t have to worry about whitespace is, in my humble opinion, a fallacy. My big argument against this mobile consumers.  Yes speeds are increasing, but they aren\'t there yet.\n\nAdditionally, just because you are on broadband doesn;t mean that big pages don\'t cause any problem at all. I\'ve had whitespace issues dealing with work servers from my Comcast broadand server, which has a special connection to my employer\'s network.\n\nLong and short of it.  Do the right thing, get rid of the whitespace. It\'s not terribly hard to do, and it reaps benefits down the road.',0,'1','','',0,0),(292,116,'Joe Fitzgerald','joef@netcessities.com','','','2007-03-29 23:50:46','2007-03-29 23:50:46','I\'m not entirely sure this issue has a huge impact on most applications or their users; however, I also agree it is a good practice to address it to one extent or another.\n\nIn most well-designed web applications this issue should be nearly non-existent anyway with only a single minor change...  How?  Well, if you are taking an MVC approach, simply \'reset\' the page output just prior to first actual view/output area.\n\nSpecifically, in the application I develop, everything I am going to output is captured to variables prior to display.  The actual code that ends up dumping the variables to the browser simply issues a cfcontent reset=\"true\" /&gt; command prior and viola, virtually no unintended whitespace.',0,'1','','',0,0),(293,116,'Kelvin Luck','kelvin@kelvinluck.com','http://www.kelvinluck.com/','','2007-03-30 09:06:29','2007-03-30 09:06:29','One important point that you don\'t mention is that any whitespace before the DOCTYPE will throw IE into quirksmode regardless of which DOCTYPE you declare. Which can have pretty serious consequences on your layout (CSS based layouts are most effected)',0,'1','','',0,0),(294,117,'Jance','janice@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/janice/blog/','','2007-04-04 17:05:17','2007-04-04 17:05:17','You neglected to mention the article your beautiful wife sent you that pointed out how an improperly used try/catch is a security breach waiting to happen, ala this week\'s animated cursor boondoggle:\n\n<a href=\"http://msmvps.com/blogs/alunj/archive/2007/04/02/don-t-catch-exceptions.aspx\" rel=\"nofollow\">Tales from the Crypto: Don\'t catch exceptions</a>\n\nAn improperly used try/catch causes errors to fail silently, which just gives a malicious user the opportunity to try and break your program repeatedly without consequence.  It\'s saying \"Oh, did your buffer overflow fail?  Here try again, I don\'t mind.\"\n\nThat\'s great if you know you\'re perfect, and your code is infalible.  However, if that\'s the case, you shouldn\'t need the try/catch at all in the first place!\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(295,117,'Janice','janice@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/janice/blog/','','2007-04-04 17:06:41','2007-04-04 17:06:41','Hey, you stripped out my URL.  The article is at:\n http://msmvps.com/blogs/alunj/archive/2007/04/02/don-t-catch-exceptions.aspx',0,'1','','',0,0),(296,117,'Jay Greer','gr33r@hotmail.com','','','2007-04-05 13:06:25','2007-04-05 13:06:25','The docs give a good overview of all this and support your position:\n\nhttp://livedocs.adobe.com/coldfusion/7/htmldocs/wwhelp/wwhimpl/js/html/wwhelp.htm?href=part_cfm.htm',0,'1','','',0,0),(297,117,'Alun Jones','alun@wftpd.com','http://msmvps.com/blogs/alunj','','2007-04-27 12:18:12','2007-04-27 12:18:12','I like this article.\nI particularly like the one line:\n\"In a nutshell, the <cftry> and <cfcatch> model in ColdFusion is for handling expected errors, as opposed to handling unexpected errors.\"\nThis explains the crux of my objection to exception-based programming - that it is poorly used by developers, who see it as their job to somehow manage every exception that comes in.\nInstead, they should be taught that they should handle only those things that they can correctly recover from at all times.\nI take exception, if you\'ll pardon the pun, at the use of \"exception\" to describe part of the normal operation of an application - but more at the expectation by a generation of developers that exceptions are the rule, and that they \"gotta catch \'em all\".',0,'1','','',0,0),(298,117,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-04-30 17:02:40','2007-04-30 17:02:40','Thanks, Alun.  As you can see Janice likes your blog.',0,'1','','',0,0),(299,117,'fliessurf','3@verifieds.biz','http://www.es5.com','','2011-05-24 15:44:22','2011-05-24 15:44:22','<a href=http://es5.com rel=\"nofollow\"><img>http://www.blackhatworld.com/images/clip_image002.gif</img></a>\n\nGood Afternoon <a href=http://www.blackhatworld.com rel=\"nofollow\"><img>http://es5.com/images/smile.gif</img></a>\n\nWe are doing research online <a href=http://www.es5.com/blackhat-seo/ rel=\"nofollow\"><b> WhiteHat SEO</b></a> traffic software  to enlarge our SEO rankings.  I\'d be thankful for any and all form of SEO and Web Site promotion\n\n If you know anybody that will to support quality traffic and with <a href=http://es5.com rel=\"nofollow\"><b>Whitehat</a></b> Methods.  I want to learn how to promote and exploit of our websites & products.',0,'1','','',0,0),(300,118,'Dan Wilson','sipacate@gmail.com','http://www.nodans.com','','2007-04-11 15:51:12','2007-04-11 15:51:12','Cool!  See you there.\n\ndw',0,'1','','',0,0),(301,119,'Pete','bulk@subnova.net','','','2007-04-12 07:55:36','2007-04-12 07:55:36','It\'s always worth exporting your SSL certificates _before_ something bad happens. I\'ve been in a situation where \"Mark private key as exportable\" was not checked when one of our production certificates was installed, making it \"stuck\" on the server it was currently on.  It took a call to Verisign, two days, and several hundred dollars to get a new cert issued that we could properly export.',0,'1','','',0,0),(302,119,'Dan Wilson','sipacate@gmail.com','http://www.nodans.com','','2007-04-12 09:40:13','2007-04-12 09:40:13','On Apache, simply copy the httpd.conf file.\n\nOne simple text file CONTROLS the horizontal and the vertical.\n\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(303,119,'Fernando Lopez','lopezf@gmail.com','http://grtfercho.blogspot.com','','2007-04-12 10:30:12','2007-04-12 10:30:12','I\'ve been really interested in your previous posts and this one confirms one of the ideas I had.\nIt took a while to get Eclipse working the way I wanted. Now that I have things the way I like   I\'m thinking of \'backing up\' my whole environment.\nBy \'Backing up\' what I really mean is moving all the config files to CVS, that way if something changes and we have to revert to the old files we can do that without any problems, plus we can have a history of all the changes. I\'m trying to push the idea of doing the same with all neo-query files for Dev/Test/Prod here where I work.\n\nFor my localhost environment I\'m actually going to move all the CFIDE files up to CVS. I had a \"Pimp My ride\" episode with my localhost CF Admin and it looks different than the standard CF Admin panel.\n\nThe three articles are a great read!!.\n\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(304,119,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-04-12 21:53:52','2007-04-12 21:53:52','@Pete, thanks for the backup about the SSL certs.\n@Dan, thanks for the Apache information\n@Fernando, thanks for the compliment and I\'m glad I could help. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(305,119,'Hidden','azbord@gmail.com','http://www.hiddenobjectgames.us','','2008-06-29 20:53:30','2008-06-29 20:53:30','I introduced ColdFusion to my IT shop three years ago and it has worked out great. We are a large public company and my team is the most productive team in IT. ColdFusion rocks!',0,'1','','',0,0),(306,119,'Alen','martyr@gmail.com','','','2009-12-17 04:37:23','2009-12-17 04:37:23','http://www.twincling.org/node/742',0,'1','','',0,0),(307,120,'Jeff Porten','civitan@jeffporten.com','http://www.jeffporten.com','','2007-04-17 21:52:28','2007-04-17 21:52:28','Hoth?  As in \"ice planet of\"?  First technical term that I\'ve understood in your blog in months.',0,'1','','',0,0),(308,120,'Michael Long','hmlong@gmail.com','http://cfinternals.typepad.com/blog/','','2007-04-18 02:58:42','2007-04-18 02:58:42','Yeah, you can program a workaround, but it would be nice if they fixed the problem. I\'ve had this issue for years, and basically solved it in the same fashion.\n\nIt\'s like the CFApplication bug where the tag blows up when only one of the cfid/cftoken cookie pairs is present. Been there for I don\'t know how many versions, and I fully expect it to be there when Scorpio ships.',0,'1','','',0,0),(309,120,'Tom','ke4pym@gmail.com','','','2007-04-18 14:40:13','2007-04-18 14:40:13','From time to time the mail spooler internal service will crash out.  The only way to fix it is to restart CF.\n\nI had one of our VB dev\'s write a little file checker utility.  I plug in all my UNC paths and set a timer.  If it checks the path and finds files so many times in so many minutes it will pop a little alert on my screen.  It also checks the undelivr folder for files as well.',0,'1','','',0,0),(310,120,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-04-18 15:11:23','2007-04-18 15:11:23','@Jeff - We are nothing if not geeks here.\n\n@Michael - From what I\'ve seen, its very hard to troubleshoot. It seems to happen when our mail servers have problems.  The connection breaks and does not get picked back up.\n\n@Tom - Wow, same principle. We do a similar thing for undelvr as well. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(311,121,'Seun Ojo','xterzone@yahoo.com','','','2007-04-20 07:07:35','2007-04-20 07:07:35','nice one dere...\n\nIm a CF developer n think im guilty about not making CF>>CF n SQL>>SQL.\n\nThough im an Advanced T-Sql programmer...but U n I know CF makes life/things easier...so usually if ur under pressure to deliver, u r just tempted to go it the easier way (the CF way../)',0,'1','','',0,0),(312,121,'Sean Corfield','seancorfield@gmail.com','http://corfield.org','','2007-04-21 14:34:54','2007-04-21 14:34:54','On 4. access=\"private\" in CF is more like \"protected\" in Java etc - it means only accessible by that CFC *and any CFC that extends that CFC*.\n\nAlso note that even within that CFC, you cannot say otherObj.somePrivateMethod() even if you can say variables.somePrivateMethod() - using another object means the calls are external to that object and therefore restricted to non-private access. This catches quite a few people out, in my experience.',0,'1','','',0,0),(313,121,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-04-23 11:06:34','2007-04-23 11:06:34','@Seun in fairness, I did say my scenario described what was usually the case.\n\n@Sean, as always you are correct.',0,'1','','',0,0),(314,122,'Scott','smcnulty@gmail.com','http://blog.blankbaby.com','','2007-04-20 01:06:13','2007-04-20 01:06:13','You may find this of interest:\n\nhttp://twitter.pbwiki.com/Cats',0,'1','','',0,0),(315,122,'roz','rosalyn@stellargirl.com','http://www.stellargirl.com','','2007-04-20 07:22:08','2007-04-20 07:22:08','i was totally thinking the same exact thing!',0,'1','','',0,0),(316,123,'Adrock','adrocknaphobia@gmail.com','http://www.adrocknaphobia.com','','2007-04-25 16:57:08','2007-04-25 16:57:08','Lol. From your title, I assumed this was a New Atlanta blog. :-)\n\nFYI. People who attend the Scorpio User Group tour events may be offered the opportunity to join the private beta.\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(317,123,'J.Cruz','jcruz@wharton.upenn.edu','http://guamaniac.wordpress.com','','2007-04-25 20:37:53','2007-04-25 20:37:53','Is it safe to assume there is compatibility with Exchange 2007 in Scorpio??',0,'1','','',0,0),(318,123,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-04-25 22:06:16','2007-04-25 22:06:16','Not knowing the internals of how the CF team are communicating with Exchange, I have to say \'I don\'t know.\'\n\nWhat little tidbit I was able to get out of a tired CF engineer at Max, points me to Webdav which is deemphasized but not deprecated in Exchange 2007.\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(319,123,'Dan Sorensen','dan.sorensen@esd112.org','','','2007-04-26 12:32:21','2007-04-26 12:32:21','My understanding from the presentation at the Seattle User Group is that Adobe is using a Webdav wrapper to implement communication between Exchange and Scorpio and it will be compatible with both 2003 & 2007. However, it was clearly stated in the meeting that \"Things in Scorpio are still subject to change\".',0,'1','','',0,0),(320,123,'Carlos','cjuarez@vproinc.com','','','2008-07-23 13:13:45','2008-07-23 13:13:45','Is there way to get the \"modified date\" of a contact in exchange using the new tags? ',0,'1','','',0,0),(321,125,'Dave Konopka','dave@lifelikeweeds.com','http://www.lifelikeweeds.com/tech','','2007-05-02 12:17:51','2007-05-02 12:17:51','Did I just contribute to an open-source project? My last shreds of Microsoft street-cred have officially been wiped out ;)',0,'1','','',0,0),(322,125,'John Hodorowicz','jjhodoro@cipm.info','','','2007-05-02 15:41:13','2007-05-02 15:41:13','It will be interesting to see the new features in action. I\'m not sure how the created business will work, but the way I understood it was that it was up to the developer to create their own business logic. But, if its less work for me then I\'m a supporter. I\'m using Squidhead w/ Coldbox and it works great.\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(323,125,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-05-02 15:59:16','2007-05-02 15:59:16','Good to hear it John. All of the business stuff will be totally optional.  I\'m still trying to figure out how to implement it.  Cool to hear that your using it with Coldbox, as I hear such great things about it.  ',0,'1','','',0,0),(324,127,'charlie griefer','charlie@griefer.com','http://charlie.griefer.com','','2007-05-04 18:13:51','2007-05-04 18:13:51','re: differences between Reactor and Transfer:\n\nhttp://corfield.org/blog/index.cfm/do/blog.entry/entry/Comparing_Transfer_and_Reactor',0,'1','','',0,0),(325,127,'Mark Mandel','mark@compoundtheory.com','http://www.compoundtheory.com','','2007-05-05 00:16:45','2007-05-05 00:16:45','Wander over and ask away.. I\'m quite happy to answer questions.\n\n:oD',0,'1','','',0,0),(326,127,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-05-05 00:39:05','2007-05-05 00:39:05','@charlie: Thanks.\n\n@Mark: I\'ll take you up on that... and try not to be an ass about it.',0,'1','','',0,0),(327,127,'Adrock','adrocknaphobia@gmail.com','http://www.adrocknaphobia.com','','2007-05-05 17:58:25','2007-05-05 17:58:25','Ahem... I said it can \'pretty much\' do everything Outlook can. Out of office.... good feature idea... ;-)',0,'1','','',0,0),(328,127,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-05-05 18:06:31','2007-05-05 18:06:31','@adrock Just keeping you honest dude. And have to do something so that when I rave about Cfexchange people don\'t think I\'m an Adobe apologist.... that\'s your job.',0,'1','','',0,0),(329,128,'Matt Woodward','matt@mattwoodward.com','http://mattwoodward.com/blog','','2007-05-05 23:33:12','2007-05-05 23:33:12','Minor comment about my presentation--you want to increase cohesion but *decrease* coupling. :-)',0,'1','','',0,0),(330,128,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-05-06 00:09:44','2007-05-06 00:09:44','@Matt - Right you are.  Sorry about that. Cohesion = GOOD;  Coupling BAD.\n\nThat\'s what happens when you blog during the sessions.',0,'1','','',0,0),(331,128,'Sean Corfield','seancorfield@gmail.com','http://corfield.org','','2007-05-06 00:12:16','2007-05-06 00:12:16','Glad to hear you\'re considering giving Fusebox a go! Feel free to ping me (or anyone else on Team Fusebox) for assistance!\n\nI was also going to point out the *decrease* coupling thing but Matt beat me to it!',0,'1','','',0,0),(332,128,'Mike Henke','henke.mike@gmail.com','http://www.venteinc.com','','2007-05-06 09:02:51','2007-05-06 09:02:51','Another simple tip from Kelly\'s session was to turn OFF debug on production.  Having it on but not utilizing it still affects performance.',0,'1','','',0,0),(333,129,'Nathan Mische','nmische@gmail.com','http://www.mischefamily.com/nathan','','2007-05-07 11:22:50','2007-05-07 11:22:50','I saw both of Chris Scott\'s presentations on Sunday and some of the stuff he was doing with ColdSpring blew my mind. While he was using the RemoteProxy stuff with Flex, I can see how it  would equally useful for AJAX development.  ',0,'1','','',0,0),(334,130,'Randy','programmer@cfedge.com','','','2007-05-08 08:14:11','2007-05-08 08:14:11','Hello,\n\nI copied and pasted your list.  It is exactly what I have been thinking for quite some time.    I wasn\'t able to attend the conference unfortunately.\n\nI am curious as to why you do not have Coldspring under the real frameworks?  I have not done enough research yet, but I thought Coldspring would be listed under the real frameworks?\n\nThanks!\n\nRandy\n\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(335,130,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-05-08 10:14:23','2007-05-08 10:14:23','@Randy - Sorry for the confusion. It wasn\'t meant as an insult to ColdSpring.  Coldspring is a framework, but it exists at a separate layer independent of the interface framework. In fact ModelGlue includes it. So I should have further clarified that I mean I should use a real interface framework. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(336,130,'Dan Wilson','sipacate@gmail.com','http://www.nodans.com','','2007-05-08 10:24:09','2007-05-08 10:24:09','Terrance,\n\nIt was good to meet you at cf.objective(). I am always glad to put names with faces.\n\n\nDan Wilson',0,'1','','',0,0),(337,130,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-05-08 10:33:28','2007-05-08 10:33:28','@Dan right back at you.',0,'1','','',0,0),(338,130,'Randy','programmer@cfedge.com','','','2007-05-08 14:20:58','2007-05-08 14:20:58','No worries, I didn\'t know the difference between the two so I was curious :-)\n\nModel Glue includes the Coldspring Framework?\n\n-Randy',0,'1','','',0,0),(339,130,'nick','mail@nicksollecito.com','http://nicksollecito.com','','2007-05-08 22:43:57','2007-05-08 22:43:57','Couldn\'t agree with you more... this was my first CF conference and a great opportunity to meet other developers, if nothing else. Thanks for letting me tag along with you and Dave.',0,'1','','',0,0),(340,130,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-05-09 08:34:05','2007-05-09 08:34:05','@Nick, who was tagging along? We all had a great time together.',0,'1','','',0,0),(341,130,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-05-09 10:47:23','2007-05-09 10:47:23','@Randy: Now that I think of it, I\'m not sure if it actually includes it.  I know that it has hooks for coldspring and reactor that make some cool scaffolding stuff happen. But I know the \"unity\" in ModelGlue 2 was about combining all three into one uber framework. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(342,130,'DK','DanaKowalski@gmail.com','http://danakowalski.com','','2007-05-09 11:48:52','2007-05-09 11:48:52','Terrence,\n there is a really good mg:u presentation by Stephen \'cutter\' Blades to the nashville CFUG. When I first started with Unity I read all of Dan\'s tutorials then watched this presso. Things really started clicking at that point on a better way to do things. I think I\'m in the same boat as you :)\n\nAnyhow nashville cfug site:\nhttp://www.ncfug.com/\n\nDirect Presso Link:\nhttp://mmusergroup.adobe.acrobat.com/p45277812/',0,'1','','',0,0),(343,130,'Sean Corfield','seancorfield@gmail.com','http://corfield.org','','2007-05-09 22:31:24','2007-05-09 22:31:24','The imaginary Sean Corfield enjoyed meeting you. The real Sean Corfield isn\'t available for comment right now... Hard to talk with a gag in your mouth, isn\'t it?... Oh, stop squirming, those ropes aren\'t coming undone any time soon. And now, back to my cunning master plan...',0,'1','','',0,0),(344,130,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-05-09 23:01:08','2007-05-09 23:01:08','I KNEW IT!',0,'1','','',0,0),(345,130,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-05-11 00:20:19','2007-05-11 00:20:19','@DK.  Thanks for the links.',0,'1','','',0,0),(346,132,'Nathan Mische','nmische@gmail.com','http://www.mischefamily.com/nathan','','2007-05-16 08:58:19','2007-05-16 08:58:19','I really wanted to make last night\'s meeting; it sounds like I missed a good one. Thanks for the write up.',0,'1','','',0,0),(347,132,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-05-16 09:23:53','2007-05-16 09:23:53','No problem, Nathan.  ',0,'1','','',0,0),(348,132,'Dan Wilson','sipacate@gmail.com','http://www.nodans.com','','2007-05-16 10:17:23','2007-05-16 10:17:23','I haven\'t heard of onMissingMethod before. This seems like a VERY useful function.\n\n\nWhere did you hear of it?',0,'1','','',0,0),(349,132,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-05-17 11:06:17','2007-05-17 11:06:17','@Dan they mentioned it at the CFUG thing the other night. It makes the requested method and arguments available to the onMissingMEthod.\n\nThe biggest use of this to come out is no longer having to make your own singular getters and setters. But I\'m sure there are others.',0,'1','','',0,0),(350,133,'Hidden','azbord@gmail.com','http://www.hiddenobjectgames.us','','2008-06-29 20:50:40','2008-06-29 20:50:40','Thanks!',0,'1','','',0,0),(351,134,'Sean Corfield','seancorfield@gmail.com','http://corfield.org','','2007-05-25 02:59:24','2007-05-25 02:59:24','cfcUnit does NOT require Mach II!!\n\ncfcUnit has ant integration, can be run by the CFUnit plugin for CFEclipse and the ASFusion folks created a Flex front end for it (which they could not do for CFUnit due to the poor architecture of the latter).\n\ncfcUnit also has an HTML \"runner\" application. That happens to be a Mach II application but uses a built-in version of the framework so you don\'t need to download or install anything other than Mach II.\n\nAdobe use cfcUnit extensively as do several other companies I\'ve been dealing with lately. Having Squidhead generate cfcUnit test stubs would be far more valuable.',0,'1','','',0,0),(352,134,'Sean Corfield','seancorfield@gmail.com','http://corfield.org','','2007-05-25 03:00:38','2007-05-25 03:00:38','Argh! Typo:\n\nYou don\'t need to \"download or install anything other than cfcUnit.\" Sorry. See what happens when you get me frustrated?',0,'1','','',0,0),(353,134,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-05-25 09:08:49','2007-05-25 09:08:49','Sorry Sean, I didn\'t mean to make you angry. I was thrown off by the documentation on CFCUnit\'s site, on page: http://www.cfcunit.org/cfcunit/docs.cfm that states: \"Before you install cfcUnit, you must be running CFMX 6.1 and the Mach-II (1.0.9) application framework.\"\n\nThat being said. I\'ll take another look at CFCUnit. But I\'m curious, not challenging, why CFCUnit?  CFunit has Ant integration. CFUnit has an html runner and a front end.  Is it the difference in architecture that you alluded to?  Does CFCunit have better tests? (Which would definitely motivate me.)',0,'1','','',0,0),(354,134,'Robert Blackburn','skorpiun@gmail.com','http://www.rbdev.net','','2007-05-25 10:23:55','2007-05-25 10:23:55','Hi Terrence,\nI noted a while back on my blog some of the differences I found between CFUnit and cfcUnit:\nhttp://www.rbdev.net/devblog/index.php?entry=entry051116-030332\n\nSince then I have also added a mock object CFC to the CFUnit framework - which I personally think is a very handy tool.\n\nIn the end, I think both frameworks are very good. And I think the important think is just that you unit test at all, which framework you unit test with is secondary.',0,'1','','',0,0),(355,134,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-05-25 10:58:25','2007-05-25 10:58:25','Thanks Robert, that did shed some light on things.',0,'1','','',0,0),(356,134,'Nathan Mische','nmische@gmail.com','http://www.mischefamily.com/nathan','','2007-05-25 13:58:56','2007-05-25 13:58:56','I started to work on <a href=\"http://www.mischefamily.com/nathan/index.cfm/2006/11/16/Auto-Generating-Unit-Tests-With-cfcGenerator\" rel=\"nofollow\">auto generated unit tests with Brian Rinaldi\'s cfcGenerator</a> a while ago. I only got around to generating tests for Beans and DAOs as I couldn\'t figure out how to best populate the database to test gateways. One thing I\'d be curious to know, do you test against a production database? What I ended up doing was having a blank scratch database, then I created and droped necessary tables in my setUp and tearDown methods. Looking back I don\'t know if that was a good idea or not. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(357,134,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-05-25 14:48:45','2007-05-25 14:48:45','I\'m only doing (and recommending) unit tests against development databases. I actually do all of the database stuff within an cftranaction that is rolled back.  So the database is none the wiser. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(358,136,'J.Cruz','jcruz@wharton.upenn.edu','http://guamaniac.wordpress.com','','2007-05-31 19:21:53','2007-05-31 19:21:53','Great post, Terry!  Makes me wish I were a developer again...but you know...someone\'s gotta run those pesky infrstructure services...and you know?  Now I have PowerShell!',0,'1','','',0,0),(359,136,'B.Parnell','b.parnell@abertay.ac.uk','','','2008-03-07 11:40:13','2008-03-07 11:40:13','Well CF8 is out, and they still do not have a sensible sandbox model for the standard edition!  Since to administer coldfusion you have to be running coldfusion server, if you are security concious and want to disable some of the more nefarious cftags there is still the potential to break the cf administration site.  why o why did they design a security model for a standard edition that does not exclude the administration applications from its scope?  Well maybe they will clear this up in the next version!\n\nApart from that it looks not to bad so far, lets hope that the programatic administration has been improved.....  that is what I am testing next.....\n\nl8tr....\nB.',0,'1','','',0,0),(360,138,'kola','kolasmail@gmail.com','http://www.coolskool.blog-city.com','','2007-06-17 04:54:30','2007-06-17 04:54:30','I Love this task - in particular I find it very  useful for testing - as it allows me blow away data in test tables and recreate the data before running some unit tests!',0,'1','','',0,0),(361,138,'Jaime Metcher','jmetcher@gmail.com','','','2007-07-12 19:53:08','2007-07-12 19:53:08','In this context it\'s worth a look at dbunit and associated ant task.',0,'1','','',0,0),(362,138,'Mike Henke','henke.mike@gmail.com','http://www.henke.ws','','2007-07-25 16:54:11','2007-07-25 16:54:11','Lets say I want to do an insert, how would I pull back the new id in an echo message?  Great post!',0,'1','','',0,0),(363,138,'Mike','henke.mike@google.com','http://www.henke.ws','','2007-07-26 21:53:35','2007-07-26 21:53:35','Figured out my question.  See http://henke.ws/machblog/index.cfm?event=showEntry&entryId=055A6924-188B-4E84-1534BBFD052A04CA',0,'1','','',0,0),(364,138,'Phillip Gagnon','phill.gagnon@gmail.com','http://www.phillipgagnon.com','','2007-10-16 19:24:36','2007-10-16 19:24:36','Awesome post! FYI- That driver also works with MS2000. Just a heads up!\n\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(365,138,'Lars','lars.engel@gmail.com','','','2008-11-05 07:06:10','2008-11-05 07:06:10','How does your connection url look like for a MSSQL2000 server? I always get an error \"Server has to be MS SQL Server 2000 or later\" though I am using a MSSQL 2000.\n\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(366,138,'Lars','lars.engel@gmail.com','','','2008-11-05 07:06:36','2008-11-05 07:06:36','How does your connection url look like for a MSSQL2000 server? I always get an error \"Server has to be MS SQL Server 2000 or later\" though I am using a MSSQL 2000.\n\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(367,139,'Ashwin','amathew@adobe.com','http://blogs.sanmathi.org/ashwin/','','2007-06-25 01:01:35','2007-06-25 01:01:35','The fact that the OutOfMemoryError is thrown from the MonitoringServletFilter does not mean that monitoring is the root cause. The MonitoringServletFilter is the \"perimeter\" of the monitoring system - when exceptions are thrown from within CF, they\'re caught there, logged by monitoring, and rethrown. I would suggest you trace down the logs some more, and you\'ll probably find an entry beneath the one for this exception indicating the root cause exception. And do keep in mind that OutOfMemoryErrors occur when, well, the JVM is out of memory - is there any possibility that your application is creating objects, and not throwing them away, eating all the JVM memory? Also, as we\'ve noted before, do not run production systems with Memory Tracking on - that can quickly bring a  server to its knees. If neither of these is a potential root cause, do drop me a mail with more details, and we\'ll look into it ASAP.',0,'1','','',0,0),(368,139,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-06-25 02:21:35','2007-06-25 02:21:35','Actually, Ashwin, creating many, many objects and holding them over the course of one request was EXACTLY what I was doing. But with profiling and memory monitoring turned off, I was giving myself more rope?\n\nIn any case, my goal here wasn\'t to snipe at CF monitoring.  It was to point out what it looks like if you\'re doing something crazy that pushes monitoring to the point where it breaks. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(369,139,'Ashwin','amathew@adobe.com','http://blogs.sanmathi.org/ashwin/','','2007-06-25 02:35:45','2007-06-25 02:35:45','Yep, definitely plenty of rope there! ;) Going by our testing, profiling is safe to use in production, but as I noted, memory tracking could kill a server, especially if it\'s creating too many objects. Try your test with memory tracking turned off, and let us know what happens. I didn\'t at all mean to suggest that you were sniping at CF monitoring - just providing the background so you know why the stacktrace for the error looks the way it does.',0,'1','','',0,0),(370,139,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-06-25 02:44:15','2007-06-25 02:44:15','I definitely tried it with memory tracking turned off, and profiling turned on. It still crashed.\n\nWhat can I say?  I was doing weird stuff.',0,'1','','',0,0),(371,139,'Mike Faulkner','m.faulkner@premiervoice.net','','','2008-01-04 19:20:34','2008-01-04 19:20:34','How exactly do you turn off memory tracking and profiling, I have this exact problem on a clustered pair of 2x Servers with 8GB of RAM each :( ',0,'1','','',0,0),(372,139,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2008-01-07 10:18:00','2008-01-07 10:18:00','In the CF administrator:\nGo to Server Monitoring\nLaunch Server Monitor\nUp at the top there should be 3 options that say Stop Monitoring, Stop Profiling, Stop Memory Tracking.\nTurn them off.\n\nHowever, these are turned off by default and  if you have never turned them on this error could be caused by something else per Ashwin\'s comment earlier in this thread.',0,'1','','',0,0),(373,139,'Rebecca Younes','rjy7@cornell.edu','http://www.ilr.cornell.edu','','2008-01-08 10:16:25','2008-01-08 10:16:25','Thanks for posting this. I have now found warnings to this effect buried in the user documentation, but it seems to me incumbent on Adobe to post this warning in big red letters on the Server Monitor screen so it\'s clear to everyone that it should not be kept running on a production server. At CFUnited in June, there were a lot of Adobe people generating excitement about the Server Monitor, but no mention of its dangers. Of what use, exactly, is the Server Monitor if it can\'t run on production? This is a blow to my confidence in Adobe products.',0,'1','','',0,0),(374,139,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2008-01-14 11:58:17','2008-01-14 11:58:17','Well there are a lot of things you can do in the CFadministrator to really screw up the server. None of them get the same treatment. I think that Adobe acts responsibly here in that they don\'t install CF with the monitoring running.\n\nI do think mention of these dangers should be included in future documentation, and guides to setting up ColdFusion, but in reality the load burden of monitoring only comes up on heavily trafficked sites or in the case I discuss above, very complex sites. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(375,139,'Rob Commarota','robcom99@yahoo.com','','','2008-05-20 11:29:06','2008-05-20 11:29:06','We had a similar problem with Fusebox applications on our servers.  We finally did several thread dumps and determined that there were locking issues.  Turning off all server monitoring functions cleared the problems instantly.',0,'1','','',0,0),(376,139,'Ryan Duckworth','rduckworth@uhlig.com','','','2008-08-28 18:17:27','2008-08-28 18:17:27','If you have an object that has a lot of objects created in its variables scope, you may want to try this.\n\nAfter you are done with that object, clean up so it can be garbage collected such as:\n\nstructDelete( variables, \"objOrder\" );\n\nThis combined with turning off the monitoring as listed above solved our problem.',0,'1','','',0,0),(377,140,'JohnEric','john.enters@gmail.com','','','2007-06-27 13:40:57','2007-06-27 13:40:57','I always do a search on \'orphaned users\' in SQL Server Books Online',0,'1','','',0,0),(378,140,'J.Cruz','jcruz@wharton.upenn.edu','http://guamaniac.wordpress.com','','2007-07-13 23:44:57','2007-07-13 23:44:57','Another option i just read about was if you create a user with a known SID (i believe it\'s an option of the CREATE LOGIN or sp_add_login procedures in SQL 2005 and SQL 2000 respectively).\n\nThat way you can re-create the login on the new SQL Server with the right SID and SQL will automatically associate the Login with the DB user.\n\nNot as useful in a DR scenario; the sp_change_users_login procedure is still your best bet.',0,'1','','',0,0),(379,141,'Peter Bell','pbell@systemsforge.com','http://www.pbell.com','','2007-07-02 12:57:45','2007-07-02 12:57:45','Congrats on the new gig. \"DSL to automate page construction\" - very cool - have fun!\n\nGood luck with the Perl though - it can be a little impenetrable at times.\n\nVery best wishes for the new position.\nPeter',0,'1','','',0,0),(380,141,'Jeff Porten','civitan@jeffporten.com','http://www.jeffporten.com','','2007-07-02 17:03:52','2007-07-02 17:03:52','What he said.  I\'m impressed.',0,'1','','',0,0),(381,141,'nicholas','mail@nicksollecito.com','http://nicksollecito.com','','2007-07-02 23:31:30','2007-07-02 23:31:30','Congrats on the new position! I\'m sure you\'ll do well...\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(382,141,'Ashwin','amathew@adobe.com','http://blogs.sanmathi.org/ashwin','','2007-07-03 11:48:07','2007-07-03 11:48:07','Congratulations, and good luck with the new position! Now if only I were going to Wharton instead of Berkeley, I\'d know who to talk to about a campus job... ;)',0,'1','','',0,0),(386,142,'Ashwin','amathew@adobe.com','http://blogs.sanmathi.org/ashwin','','2007-07-12 02:10:06','2007-07-12 02:10:06','Here\'s an idea, based on what we do in the CF team - add a script to your source code control system so that diffs of all checkins are automatically mailed out to the entire development team. That way, everyone gets to see everyone\'s checkins - very egalitarian, and good in more ways than one, since folks who are familiar with the modified code may stick their heads up and shout if they see something wrong, even if they haven\'t been formally asked for a review.',0,'1','','',0,0),(387,142,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-07-12 10:50:26','2007-07-12 10:50:26','That\'s actually a very cool idea indeed.  I have a feeling that it would be much easier if we get everyone over to SVN.\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(388,143,'Nathan Mische','nmische@gmail.com','http://www.mischefamily.com/nathan','','2007-08-15 08:43:34','2007-08-15 08:43:34','I\'ve found cfhtmlhead to be invaluable for this purpose. I glad to see this post about it because I\'m always surprised how many CF developers I run into who don\'t know about this tag.\n\nOn thing to keep in mind when injecting JavaScript into the page is that it is very possible the page already has an onload function defined. One way to make sure the old onload event as well as your new event get fired is to use an anonymous function like so:\n\nwindow.onload = (function (old) {\n  return function () {\n    if (typeof old == \'function\') old();\n    if(document.getElementById(\"username\"));	    document.getElementById(\"username\").focus();\n  };\n})(window.onload);\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(389,143,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-08-15 09:10:48','2007-08-15 09:10:48','That\'s an awesome tip, Nathan. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(390,144,'Todd Rafferty','webRat@gmail.com','','','2007-08-16 12:55:23','2007-08-16 12:55:23','Yeah, as soon as we got CF8 in-house, that\'s the first thing I did was add the mappings and custom tags to the Application.cfc - at my work, we don\'t use a global custom tag directory at all due to the shear amount of sites on one box, so having this back now is godsend for us.',0,'1','','',0,0),(391,145,'Richard Davies','Richard@richarddavies.us','http://www.richarddavies.us','','2007-08-20 14:02:13','2007-08-20 14:02:13','Wow! This is very good to know. Fortunately, it looks like a bug report has been filed:\nhttp://livedocs.adobe.com/coldfusion/6/CFML_Reference/Tags-pt19.htm',0,'1','','',0,0),(392,145,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-08-21 01:52:22','2007-08-21 01:52:22','I\'m not holding my breath. ;)',0,'1','','',0,0),(393,145,'Kevin Penny','kpenny@jobs2web.com','http://www.jobs2web.com','','2008-09-19 01:43:49','2008-09-19 01:43:49','Well, in the 8.01 release of coldfusion, this bug is logged as fixed in the release notes - however we\'re running 8.01 servers and still see the comment in the headers.\n\nAhh Adobe - you know if cf was open, we\'d have fixed this by now ;)',0,'1','','',0,0),(394,146,'John','jjhodoro@cipm.info','','','2007-08-27 11:25:46','2007-08-27 11:25:46','We don\'t have a timeline to upgrade to CF8, so I\'ll be happy as long as the final app runs on CF7.\n\nI\'ve never used the created business objects; mainly because I have been using a version before they were generated.',0,'1','','',0,0),(395,146,'jeff','jeffglad@gmail.com','','','2007-08-28 15:35:34','2007-08-28 15:35:34','I probbably won\'t be upgrading to CF8, but I hope you decide to support Railo 2.0 fully!\n.',0,'1','','',0,0),(396,146,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-08-30 10:38:42','2007-08-30 10:38:42','@Jeff, it seems unlikely that I will support running Squidhead on Railto.  But I can promise to make every effort that the actual generated application will run on Railto. That way, like in shops that are still on CF7, you can run Squidhead on the free developers\'s version of CF8, but run the app on any version of CF.\n\n ',0,'1','','',0,0),(397,146,'dt','dtaaaarrrgghh@hotmail.com','','','2007-08-31 11:07:20','2007-08-31 11:07:20','This is a great tool. It can run on a PC with cf8 in developer mode.  So it doesn\'t really matter to me what the minimal reqs are. What would be useful though would be that if the generated code works under 6.1, 7 and 8.  ',0,'1','','',0,0),(398,146,'dt','dtaaaarrrgghh@hotmail.com','','','2007-08-31 11:09:23','2007-08-31 11:09:23','Just the datalayer it creates.  Not the application generation stuff...I should add.',0,'1','','',0,0),(399,147,'Steven Erat','talkingtree@gmail.com','http://www.talkingtree.com/blog/','','2007-08-27 14:44:31','2007-08-27 14:44:31','This is where the CFMODULE tag is useful to disambiguate the exact location of the CFML custom tag.',0,'1','','',0,0),(400,147,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-08-27 16:11:09','2007-08-27 16:11:09','That makes a lot of sense, Steven. I renamed, and moved on.  But if I\'m ever in the situation where I can\'t I now know what to do.',0,'1','','',0,0),(401,147,'Alexei','alexei@superdownloads.com.br','','','2007-08-28 10:15:44','2007-08-28 10:15:44','thats why CF looks for custom tags in the caller dir by default before looking for them in the specified custom tags dir.\n\nthats a stupid cf behavior. if it uses a default dir for customs, it oughta use it first.',0,'1','','',0,0),(402,148,'barry.b','barry.beattie@gmail.com','','','2007-08-31 01:58:07','2007-08-31 01:58:07','I started out with claiming you were \"flamin\' bonkers, mate!\" but I\'m having a change of heart.\n\nwhat you\'re getting at is more than using HTML or Flash (Flex) as SaaS (software as a service).\n\nyou\'re talking about distributing the AIR runtime and apps.\n\nyou\'re actually getting pretty close to Microsoft\'s \"no touch delployment\" of apps from a couple of years ago.\n\nI\'m warming to the idea!\n\n\n\n\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(403,148,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-08-31 02:13:59','2007-08-31 02:13:59','I may still be nuts. But I\'m glad to see you out here in nutville with me.',0,'1','','',0,0),(404,148,'barry.b','barry.beattie@gmail.com','','','2007-08-31 02:48:46','2007-08-31 02:48:46','part of my argument is that Adobe has one \"web server\" - ColdFusion - and doesn\'t need any other front-facing server technology - CF can (should) cover it all.\n\nThank heaven that Flex 1.5 compiling server died a death and Livecycle is busy with PDF stuff.\n\nAs Tim Buntel recently said, Adobe are positioning CF to be a \"glue\" tool. well, time to up the ante and \"glue\" the server to the client in more meaningful ways (ie: distribution) than passing XML or remoting packets....**\n\nis it too early to start up CFWishlist again?\n\neh, just my 2 buttons worth.\nb\n\n\n(** jd/Adobe and I had an argument over this. .. my point was that while CF can provide remote data to AIR, so can a ton of other technologies - some of em $Free)\n\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(405,148,'Hemant','hkhandel@adobe.com','','','2007-08-31 07:01:05','2007-08-31 07:01:05','Nice posting Terrence. It will be difficult for all traditional apps to become AIR apps automatically. AIR requires apps to be packaged as part .air file. Also there is no concept of back/forward button as in a browser when you are viewing apps in AIR.\n\nInteresting thought for next release :)\n\nHemant',0,'1','','',0,0),(406,148,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-08-31 12:20:14','2007-08-31 12:20:14','Thanks Hemant, always nice the get attention from the engineers.  I should make the point though that i don\'t think you should be able to publish ANY CF application as AIR.  Just that ColdFusion should be able to create AIR applications. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(407,148,'barry.b','barry.beattie@gmail.com','','','2007-09-05 00:05:15','2007-09-05 00:05:15','and just to push the idea along a bit further, especially with CF8.... the new \"CFMXML\" tag... ',0,'1','','',0,0),(408,148,'Elias Perez','eliasjp@msn.com','','','2007-11-12 16:53:03','2007-11-12 16:53:03','I loveee the idea of CF + AIR.\n\nGuys We Need this!!!\n\nI believe that to implement AIR with coldfusion we might need to follow a framework in order to make this possible for both worlds Desktop and Web. Having a development framework in place is not only going to probably help us with the integration of AIR we will be able probably to develop faster and more stable applications.',0,'1','','',0,0),(409,148,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-11-14 01:49:23','2007-11-14 01:49:23','@Elias, you should check out cfair.riaforge.com then. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(410,150,'Bob Forex','ewhs59a@gmail.com','http://www.talkgold.com/forum','','2007-09-10 14:47:26','2007-09-10 14:47:26','David is a great guy, I know him personally.\n\nBob',0,'1','','',0,0),(411,151,'beth','bethbowden@gmail.com','','','2007-09-10 06:58:31','2007-09-10 06:58:31','Nice post. Thx.',0,'1','','',0,0),(412,151,'Nathan Mische','nmische@gmail.com','http://www.mischefamily.com/nathan','','2007-09-10 09:10:46','2007-09-10 09:10:46','Great presentation. I missed this meeting so thanks for posting it. One thing I didn\'t see mentioned is when you do code reviews. Do you do them at the beginning, middle or end of a project? Also, do you do multiple reviews for the same application? There seems to be some compelling benefits to formal code reviews, but also some obvious costs, so I\'m just trying to get an idea of how to best use them... ',0,'1','','',0,0),(413,151,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-09-10 12:39:55','2007-09-10 12:39:55','@Nathan My comments went a little long, so I answered your question in my next entry: <a href=\"http://www.numtopia.com/terry/blog/archives/2007/09/formal_code_reviews_when_and_how_often.cfm\" title=\"Formal Code Reviews: When and How Often?\" rel=\"nofollow\">Formal Code Reviews: When and How Often?</a>',0,'1','','',0,0),(414,152,'bethb','bethbowden@gmail.com','','','2007-09-11 07:14:50','2007-09-11 07:14:50','Like so many things, it depends on the situation. If you have new staff or have just implemented new standards, more frequent reviews help transfer knowledge and ensure that the team is on the same page.  Since they are time-intensive, we have at most one a week.',0,'1','','',0,0),(415,153,'Scott Smith','ssmith1000@hotmail.com','','','2008-03-31 08:36:51','2008-03-31 08:36:51','I am running Vista Business with the latest Windows updates installed, and I am unable to install ColdFuison 8 on the machine. When I launch the Coldfusion-8-win.exe, I incur a fatal application error: \"java.lang.NoClassDefFoundError: Could not initialize class javax.swing.UIManager\"',0,'1','','',0,0),(416,154,'Todd Rafferty','webRat@gmail.com','','','2007-09-11 14:14:09','2007-09-11 14:14:09','Adobe has got to get more xhtml-conscience peeps into the CF Beta/Alpha.  I think this is one of the issues.  We\'re all so focused on new features and such, we forget about the standards.',0,'1','','',0,0),(417,154,'Jim','priest@thecrumb.com','https://www.thecrumb.com','','2007-09-11 14:53:32','2007-09-11 14:53:32','I agree - all these \'features\' aren\'t going to do me a bit of good if they don\'t generate valid, compliant code. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(418,154,'Justin Carter','justin.w.carter@gmail.com','http://www.madfellas.com/blog','','2007-09-11 20:08:31','2007-09-11 20:08:31','In regards to passing validation, Adobe also need to keep in mind HTML 4.01 and, in the future, HTML5. I haven\'t played with validating any of the generated code yet, but if Adobe went down the path of only generating valid XHTML it could be a bad thing (even though the parsing of HTML is a lot more forgiving).',0,'1','','',0,0),(419,154,'Rob Huddleston','rob@filmstosee.com','','','2007-09-11 20:29:50','2007-09-11 20:29:50','I\'ve been arguing about this for years, going all the way back to the fact that paragraphFormat() still adds a single closing &lt;P&gt; tag. The auto server-side form validation adds an unclosed input tag. Now,  cfimage provides no way to add alt text. And so on and so on. It\'s always seemed to me that these shouldn\'t require major rewriting of things, but when I have raised these issues with folks at Adobe, the response has always been \"do you want us fixing things like this, or adding new features?\" We need to get the message out that yes, we want these fixed!\nAnd Justin - I would argue that adding XHTML support would not in any way mess up HTML 4.01 pages, since technically, XHTML is valid HTML (but not the other way around), and potentially having to support a theoretical future version of HTML isn\'t a valid reason to not support a current version of XHTML. However, if that is a real issue, then maybe we need to have something like a cfdoctype element that lets us control these types of things. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(420,154,'Justin Carter','justin.w.carter@gmail.com','http://www.madfellas.com/blog','','2007-09-11 22:04:43','2007-09-11 22:04:43','@Rob: That\'s what I was throwing out there; we might want to have better control over the output in the future, especially if HTML5 and XHTML2 are butting heads :P XHTML1 should be covered since HTML5 will be backwards compatible.\n\nFor now though I hope Adobe can fix validation issues fairly quickly, since the last thing we\'d want is for some tags to become unusable in certain situations. Good post Terrence :)',0,'1','','',0,0),(421,154,'Hemant Khandelwal','hkhandel@adobe.com','','','2007-09-12 01:53:34','2007-09-12 01:53:34','@Rob,\n\nWe are working on the issue to add alt text with cfimage. We maybe posting a patch for this, but no promises.\n\n@Terrence\n\nI saw your wishlist posting and have logged a bug for the same. We will try to resolve it for  the next release.\n\nPlease let us know any feedback/specific issues using\n\nhttp://www.adobe.com/cfusion/mmform/index.cfm?name=wishform\n\nso that we can review and track the issues.\n\nThanks,\nHemant',0,'1','','',0,0),(422,154,'Ben Nadel','ben@bennadel.com','http://www.bennadel.com','','2007-09-12 08:22:48','2007-09-12 08:22:48','@Terrence,\n\nI am curious as to what went wrong with the OnRequest and the CFSaveContent. Other than not being able to flush any of the content to the browser until the whole page has rendered, it should have worked. What CFMenu actually writing to the primary content buffer from within the CFSaveContent tag?',0,'1','','',0,0),(423,154,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-09-12 09:18:30','2007-09-12 09:18:30','@Hemant Thanks, the only issue I have with the wish form is that lack of feedback from it. I don\'t know if my replies go to the either or are being seen by someone. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(424,154,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-09-12 09:21:32','2007-09-12 09:21:32','@Ben, somehow cfmenu is writing the javascript includes to the buffer independent of the way the rest of the content is created.  If you wrap the call in a cfsavecontent, but don\'t output it, it still adds that stuff to the html head. (Dumping the source of the ensuing blank page will reveal that. )',0,'1','','',0,0),(425,154,'John Hodorowicz','jjhodoro@cipm.info','','','2007-09-12 10:38:03','2007-09-12 10:38:03','This is one of the main reasons I refuse to use Spry.',0,'1','','',0,0),(426,154,'Richard Davies','Richard@richarddavies.us','http://www.richarddavies.us','','2007-09-12 12:29:20','2007-09-12 12:29:20','I\'m glad to see that there are other CF developers out there as concerned as I am with the lack of XHTML validation in code generated by ColdFusion. I recently posted a similar rant on my web site at http://www.richarddavies.us/archives/2007/08/coldfusion_is_the_next_frontpage.php\n\nIf enough of us start complaining about this, hopefully Adobe will do something about it!\n\nBTW, I really liked the suggestion of using savecontent to fix some of the invalid code.\n\nAnd regarding the \"invalid\" HTML in the JavaScript string. You are correct that it should not be flagged as invalid because technically it\'s just a string. But you\'re wrong in assuming that the validator is flawed. JavaScript code blocks should be nested inside CDATA tags (i.e. \"// <![CDATA[\" and \"// ]]>\") to tell the validator not to parse the contents of the script tags.',0,'1','','',0,0),(427,154,'Richard Davies','Richard@richarddavies.us','http://www.richarddavies.us','','2007-09-13 12:08:31','2007-09-13 12:08:31','Terrence,\nI posted a comment yesterday, but it appears your spam filter flagged it as junk (possibly because I included a link).',0,'1','','',0,0),(428,154,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-09-13 12:25:56','2007-09-13 12:25:56','@Richard, I\'ve restored your comment, and I\'m glad I did.  That\'s some good information.  I can\'t take credit for the cfsavecontent idea though, I stole that from Ben Nadel.\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(429,154,'gimmgyut','power@gmail.com','http://all-your-mp3.com/by_letter-d-1/','','2008-02-24 20:53:55','2008-02-24 20:53:55','I am curious as to what went wrong with the OnRequest and the CFSaveContent. Other than not being able to flush any of the content to the browser until the whole page has rendered, it should have worked. What CFMenu actually writing to the primary content buffer from within the CFSaveContent tag?',0,'1','','',0,0),(430,154,'Jeff','jjs6791@gmail.com','','','2008-08-15 19:56:14','2008-08-15 19:56:14','Thanks for posting this.  Has anyone figured out how to make it compliant?  ',0,'1','','',0,0),(431,154,'Miles Jordan','miles.jordan@aad.gov.au','','','2008-09-15 03:52:29','2008-09-15 03:52:29','A worthy topic. I see that CF 8,0,1 adds the alt attribute. So there\'s one problem fixed.\n\nThe other issue still stands. And I am so disappointed in Adobe for not fixing such a simple and important issue. One year on, it still exists!\n\nGood post, Terrence. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(432,154,'Computer Services Baltimore','wilfully03126@gmail.com','http://www.computerhandymanmd.com','','2009-11-19 06:52:01','2009-11-19 06:52:01','Where can i have more info on this ?\n\nRegards',0,'1','','',0,0),(433,155,'Todd Rafferty','webRat@gmail.com','','','2007-09-12 15:41:35','2007-09-12 15:41:35','Well, there ya go.  Now the boss will stay off my back.  *chuckles*',0,'1','','',0,0),(434,155,'Rupesh Kumar','rukumar@adobe.com','http://coldfused.blogspot.com','','2007-09-13 02:31:53','2007-09-13 02:31:53','This is actually very simple to do. All you need to do is to have one html file which will be the root content of the AIR application and the html will simply point to the URL you need. This file can look like\n\n&lt;html&gt;\n	&lt;frameset cols=\"100%\"&gt;\n	&lt;frame src=\"http://coldfused.blogspot.com\" frameborder=\"0\"&gt;\n&lt;/html&gt;\n\nOR\n\n&lt;html&gt;\n&lt;head&gt;\n	&lt;meta http-equiv=\'refresh\' content=\'0;url=http://http://coldfused.blogspot.com\'&gt;\n&lt;/head&gt;\n&lt;body&gt;&lt;/body&gt;&lt;/html&gt;',0,'1','','',0,0),(435,155,'Avi Flax','avif@arc90.com','http://arc90.com/','','2007-09-17 12:24:17','2007-09-17 12:24:17','Rupesh, you\'re absolutely correct - from a developer\'s point of view. But a\nregular end-user has no idea what to do with that - they wouldn\'t know how\nto invoke the AIR SDK, and wouldn\'t want to if they could. The idea behind\nAIRifier is just to automatate that process, so anyone can turn any website\ninto an AIR app in 10 seconds. The core idea though, as you\'ve pointed out,\nis very simple.',0,'1','','',0,0),(436,155,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-09-17 12:33:04','2007-09-17 12:33:04','It\'s also a good simple idea, one that the rest of us didn\'t come up with.',0,'1','','',0,0),(437,156,'Cozmo','Gerald.Guido@gmail.com','','','2007-09-14 11:17:11','2007-09-14 11:17:11','Never heard of you. You make internets or something?',0,'1','','',0,0),(438,156,'Jeff Porten','civitan@jeffporten.com','http://www.jeffporten.com','','2007-09-14 13:26:27','2007-09-14 13:26:27','I understand quasipopularity can be perfectly measured on a Heisenberg scale.',0,'1','','',0,0),(439,156,'Peter Bell','pbell@systemsforge.com','http://www.pbell.com','','2007-09-19 09:55:15','2007-09-19 09:55:15','Well, according to Merriam Webster:\n\nhttp://www.m-w.com/dictionary/quasi\n\nQuasi means:\n1 : having some resemblance usually by possession of certain attributes <a quasi corporation rel=\"nofollow\">\n\nSo a M2 afficianado might suggest it resembles a framework, but without the flexibility of distinguishing listeners from filters required for more complex apps.\n\nA Fuseboxer might suggest it resembles a framework but without the ease of use required for non-OO programmers to work with it.\n\nA Model-gluer on the other hand would no doubt suggest that it resembled a framework in that it allowed you to create quality apps quicker and more efficiently and it was only missing the b*llsh!t and cult like status of frameworks like RoR.\n\n:->\n\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(440,156,'Danny','detarmstrong@gmail.com','','','2007-09-19 15:44:26','2007-09-19 15:44:26','RoR b*llshit? That statement requires elucidation from Peter Bell.\nI\'ve worked on model-glue and RoR and found RoR to be simple, concise and capable (This makes no statement about mg). I lost XML configuration files and gained a console to run code in and gained a first-rate ORM (mg, I\'m talking to you). RoR\'s MVCness is lucidly designed and easy to follow.\nThe \'cult\' you speak of is really quite nice. They only ask that you sacrifice your allegiance to a specific technology. Furthermore, I think to wholly align yourself to a specific technology, cf or ruby or x, is to subordinate yourself to it.',0,'1','','',0,0),(441,158,'Jim','priest@thecrumb.com','https://www.thecrumb.com','','2007-09-19 12:10:56','2007-09-19 12:10:56','Yes - it would be nice to see this become an official tag!',0,'1','','',0,0),(442,159,'Sean Corfield','seancorfield@gmail.com','http://corfield.org','','2007-09-20 14:34:08','2007-09-20 14:34:08','I hope you enjoy my session on Tuesday!',0,'1','','',0,0),(443,159,'Dan Wilson','sipacate@gmail.com','http://www.nodans.com','','2007-09-20 15:50:20','2007-09-20 15:50:20','Great news man,\n\nI\'ve also just recently found out I have the ability to attend Max. I just gotta find a ticket....\n\nHope to see you there!\n\n\nDW',0,'1','','',0,0),(444,159,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-09-20 23:28:52','2007-09-20 23:28:52','@Sean, I\'m sure I will.\n\n@Dan, you\'ll catch me smoking again. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(445,160,'Erin','wyher@wharton.upenn.edu','http://www.wharton.upenn.edulearning','','2007-10-11 09:37:24','2007-10-11 09:37:24','Thanks, Terry! I just found this post by googling my name this morning. This session was very well attended both days, so thanks again for the advertisement. Sorry we missed your ColdFusion BOF at MAX, we were busy eating stuffed pizza. But we would have been better off at your session, no doubt. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(446,161,'Sam Farmer','sam.farmer@yahoo.com','http://samfarmer.com','','2007-09-21 15:16:44','2007-09-21 15:16:44','Very cool and the code comments made me LOL.',0,'1','','',0,0),(447,161,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-09-21 15:35:00','2007-09-21 15:35:00','Thanks, Sam.  Teasing people in comments is something I got used to doing, it helped increasing reading rates among the developers before a code review.',0,'1','','',0,0),(448,163,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-10-08 11:38:51','2007-10-08 11:38:51','I\'ve answered this question in my latest post.\nhttp://www.numtopia.com/terry/blog/archives/2007/10/ why_i_use_coldfusion.cfm',0,'1','','',0,0),(449,163,'John Farrar','johnfarrar@sosensible.com','','','2007-10-03 20:25:41','2007-10-03 20:25:41','So, you didn\'t mention why you use CF. How can you bring anything meaningful (seriously) to the topic without an opinion? Oh, your holding back! Post what happens after MAX if you will. (please)\n\nI can tell you that one of the reasons people use CF is as you said. It is easier. Yet what are the reasons people use other tools. Many of the MS tools are about seperating processing from markup. In fact there are some new Flex/Air tools being presented at MAX with the same goal in mind. That is alos what I am doing with COOP. This is an open source project that goes to RC1 next week. It provides (but doesn\'t demand) seperation of markup from processing.\n\nWhat is my point. The power of ColdFusion is a mix of CFCs and Custom Tags... in addition to the easy stuff. In fact in general CF is so easy that many developers have been to lazy to innovate and make it easier still. Ruby isn\'t \"easy\"... but RoR improved the picture. dotNet isn\'t easy... but the IDE improved the picture for startup users. (Note: The deeper you go the more challenging it becomes. It should be the deeper you get the easier it becomes.) That is what I have found by returning back to the use of Custom Tags with CFCs.',0,'1','','',0,0),(450,164,'Raymond Camden','ray@camdenfamily.com','http://www.coldfusionjedi.com','','2008-06-26 17:51:37','2008-06-26 17:51:37','Another idea to possibly make this a bit cooler. You can even make the application name dynamic - perhaps based on a hash of the path. That way you can install N copies of the same app - at different locations - and not even need to change the app name. Just drop it in and it works.',0,'1','','',0,0),(451,164,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2008-06-26 18:08:54','2008-06-26 18:08:54','Great point, Ray. I only recently discovered that technique/pattern.  You\'re right, it would be a great addition to this. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(452,167,'Jeffry Houser','jeff@farcryfly.com','http://www.jeffryhouser.com','','2007-10-01 15:56:27','2007-10-01 15:56:27','Since when did ColdFusion developer\'s have Refactoring or profiling tools?  Did I miss something? ',0,'1','','',0,0),(453,167,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-10-01 16:30:13','2007-10-01 16:30:13','@jeff.  Sorry for the confusion.  ColdFusion does not have refactoring.  But it does have detailed information about what\'s going on in each page request, the cfdebug output  That was what I was referring to in my statement. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(454,171,'Andrew','mail@literal6.net','','','2007-10-10 15:34:49','2007-10-10 15:34:49','Very nice. I downloaded the project because of this tute. Also, would Jing help with your video blues?\n\nhttp://www.jingproject.com/',0,'1','','',0,0),(455,171,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-10-10 15:53:35','2007-10-10 15:53:35','Dan Wilson suggested Jing to me.  I\'ll give it a try for my next screen capture demo. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(456,172,'Sam Farmer','sam.farmer@yahoo.com','http://samfarmer.com','','2007-10-08 12:47:19','2007-10-08 12:47:19','Interesting.  I came from a Perl background and took to CF for the same reasons you did.',0,'1','','',0,0),(457,172,'David','domalley@medifit.com','','','2007-10-08 15:11:09','2007-10-08 15:11:09','ColdFusion allows me to concentrate on the business solution, rather than the language. The productivity, and versatility of the language don\'t have me thinking \"can this even be done?\" The old days of technical solutions for the sake of the challenge are gone. Business invests alot of money in IT, they want solutions, and they want them quickly. The latest version of ColdFusion (8) gives incredible opportunities to innovate, while still retaining the productivity you come to expect from CF. That\'s why I use it.\n\nCheers,\n\nDavo',0,'1','','',0,0),(458,172,'Jason Holden','jason@jasonholden.com','http://www.jasonholden.com','','2007-10-08 16:20:01','2007-10-08 16:20:01','I came from a Foxpro background where being \"close\" to the data made me very productive.  I picked up CF for the same reason.  Although I now use more structured data access strategies they are all based around the simple &lt;cfquery&gt; tag.',0,'1','','',0,0),(459,172,'James Marshall','j.marshall@webtex.co.uk','http://blog.webtex.co.uk','','2007-10-09 06:34:36','2007-10-09 06:34:36','I started with Perl then moved to PHP. For this reason I found PHP to be very productive and relatively easy to learn.\n\nI\'m now a CF developer and love it, but I have to say that if I had to weigh up CF against PHP I\'d probably rank them evenly. I agree with you however that Perl is a #!',0,'1','','',0,0),(460,172,'Tom Chiverton','tom@rachaelandtom.info','http://rachaelandtom.info/blog/3','','2007-10-09 09:30:04','2007-10-09 09:30:04','I had the exact same experience.\nI was writing dynamic web sites for the company I worked for, using perl (use CGI;, them were the days !) as it was the same glue I used for day to day sysadmin jobs.\nWhen things really started taking off, we looked for something to make the hard stuff easy. ColdFusion (4 !) was that. We\'d looked at PHP and a few other things too and they were all more work to do even simple things like output a query as a nice table.',0,'1','','',0,0),(461,172,'Sebastian VanDyke','sebastian.vandyke@gmail.com','http://www.householdpages.com','','2007-10-09 14:26:01','2007-10-09 14:26:01','I\'m a CF developer and my twin brother uses ASP.NET.  He keeps telling me that I should take the time to learn ASP.NET.  I\'ve tried a few times and just can\'t bring myself to go through the pain.  I\'ve never seen anyone go from CF to ASP.  Any thoughts?',0,'1','','',0,0),(462,172,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-10-09 14:46:31','2007-10-09 14:46:31','@Sebastian, I tend to not be pushy with what I believe or like.  So if your brother likes ASP.Net, leave him be.\n\nBut if you do want to encourage him to use ColdFusion (or anything else for that matter) I find that showing is better than telling.  Talk to him about some cool idea for an application? Build it, and show him the RAD power of CF. It doesn\'t have to be a big application, just enough that he can see how fast your ideas become something you can click on. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(463,172,'Adrian Lynch','contact@adrianlynch.co.uk','http://www.adrianlynch.co.uk/','','2007-12-23 17:28:32','2007-12-23 17:28:32','I\'m the same. My path went something like, HTML, JavaScript, C++ (don\'t ask!), ColdFusion, SQL and so on. I\'m glad it was the first language I went forward with and it\'s one of the first languages I\'ll recommend to anyone who asks what language they should learn.\n\nI understand the benefits of learning other languages and have racked up many others myself, but CF is frickin\' awesome!\n\nNice post.',0,'1','','',0,0),(464,172,'Basem','basim@sptechs.com','http://www.sptechs.com/','','2008-01-17 07:32:48','2008-01-17 07:32:48','I started with ASP then moved to ASP.NET.\nI dont know why i am stucked with Microsoft .\nBut every time i decide to learn something new , i wondering what is it ?\nis it perl , CF , PHP ..\n\nThanks for encouraging .\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(465,172,'Kasimir','inet@buerotechnik-bayern.de','http://www.buerotechnik-bayern.de','','2008-02-25 03:31:38','2008-02-25 03:31:38','I can really agree with your statement. I am a long-time Perl and Java programmer, because I have to work in the languages. In my freetime I learned a bit ColdFusion and it was much easier, so I was able to talk my chef into using ColdFusion. He wasn\'t enthusiastic, but after a while he was happy about my better and faster results. So give ColdFusion a chance, you won\'t regret it!',0,'1','','',0,0),(466,172,'Mike','mike@mike.com','','','2008-04-21 11:31:54','2008-04-21 11:31:54','.net is even faster than CF... and does 100 times more... oh and isnt a dead technology :)',0,'1','','',0,0),(467,172,'Andrew','andrew_thompsonuk2@yahoo.co.uk','','','2008-06-04 07:23:45','2008-06-04 07:23:45','Just reading the comments. I used to work with CF. However it seamed to go out of fasion. I now work with .NET and Java at half the productivity, unfortunatly the programmers have won the battle. The real challenge with Web develmpment is keeping the generated HTML under control. Programmers in the Java and .NET world spend far too much effort abstracting everything into an unnessary contorted layer of objects before attempting to render it. In CF you just \"glue\" it all together. The original ASP .NET was a disaster for the internet generating a boring user experience with huge costs on bandwidth and server power (not to mention the cost overruns and project failures). Java is so flexible you can make it do sensible things given the time however coldFusion just does it.\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(468,172,'Maria','info@kredit-consultant.de','http://www.kredit-consultant.de/umschuldung.html','','2008-09-08 06:20:01','2008-09-08 06:20:01','Very useful information for me. Thank you.',0,'1','','',0,0),(469,174,'Steve Bryant','steve@bryantwebconsulting.com','http://www.bryantwebconsulting.com/','','2007-10-18 10:11:37','2007-10-18 10:11:37','This is a great description of when and when not to use Squidhead. This type of description would be helpful for a lot of products.',0,'1','','',0,0),(470,174,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-10-18 10:24:32','2007-10-18 10:24:32','Thanks Steve.\n\nIn fairness, it\'s not always easy to see what makes your product compelling (especially when you just have a small project and a small community).  The only reason I could come up with this is that I talked to a few recent samplers, and asked what brought them to it. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(471,174,'Boyan Kostadinov','boyank@gmail.com','http://blog.tech-cats.com','','2007-10-18 12:30:00','2007-10-18 12:30:00','Damn it! I get excited every time I think about using Squidhead until I go download it and realize that it required CF8. Doh! I\'m guessing it uses the database metadata to get table info and such, correct? What would it take to make it work on CF7 since some of us can\'t afford the upgrade yet?',0,'1','','',0,0),(472,174,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-10-19 00:02:00','2007-10-19 00:02:00','Sorry Boyan,\n\nI can\'t think of anything necessary that requires 8. I haven\'t been running 7 on my development box in so long. You can always run it locally, and transfer the resulting application over to your seven box.',0,'1','','',0,0),(473,175,'Richard','rdillman@gmail.com','http://www.yourwebsetup.com','','2007-10-25 14:06:17','2007-10-25 14:06:17','Was just testing out Squidhead and I have got to tell you this is EXTREMELY handy.\n\nThat being said, I have a lot of clients that need to use Varchar(48) as their primary key. Specifically, I have clients in the foster care system where each kid might have a UUID that was created and copied to multiple systems, or a combination of First initial + Last name + last 4 of the social ( yea 3-field key)\n\nI need those numbers to be unique in my apps.\n\nAny thoughts on how we would integrate something other than an auto-incrementing INT as the primary key using your app?',0,'1','','',0,0),(474,175,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-10-26 10:55:27','2007-10-26 10:55:27','To handle non-identity primary keys is on my list of things to explore. However, it\'s going to be tough, so I make no promises.\n\nAs for multiple complex keys, I really can\'t see me going forward with that.  It\'s a bit too much for me to promise to support. On the other hand though, one can always write the crud procs for these tables manually, (since as these tables aren\'t proper squidhead tables they will be ignored) and squidhead will still suck in the procs to scaffold the  cfc\'s.  ',0,'1','','',0,0),(475,177,'zac spitzer','zac.spitzer@gmail.com','http://zacster.blogspot.com/','','2007-11-03 21:30:37','2007-11-03 21:30:37','I would have to agree with your comments about oracle... it\'s all about sql... everything is available via tables, simple. sql 2005 moved in this direction.\n\nThe thing is tho, for 95% of db work, a bound CF query is the same as a SP... CF creates a cursor and it runs pretty much the same as a SP. Unless your doing a lot of work with the data, I would be avoiding SP\'s...\n\nit\'s much easier to version, change and test an application using just a CF layer for DB interaction\n\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(476,177,'Robert Gatti','robert.gatti@edomgroup.com','http://edomgroup.com','','2007-11-04 13:49:17','2007-11-04 13:49:17','Great article. I\'ve often wondered how easy/hard it would be to go from Microsoft SQL Server to Oracle for a long time. I consider them the grandfather of databases since the first Oracle DB was offered in 1979. If you work more with the db please post your experiences. Thanks.',0,'1','','',0,0),(477,177,'zac spitzer','zac.spitzer@gmail.com','http://zacster.blogspot.com/','','2007-11-04 22:19:23','2007-11-04 22:19:23','I have worked extensively with both databases. Oracle has gone a long way to be more user friendly since the 9i and 10g releases.\n\nOracle now support the standard outer join syntax and case statements (even tho oracle\'s decode is nicer) which makes migration easy.\n\nThere is the XE version which is free for up to 4Gb of data. Beyond that, the major difference between the two is sequences, which is how oracle handles auto-increment pk\'s.\n\nSequences are a lot cleaner and more flexible from my experience. There are always times to use proprietary features in a database, it\'s  always better to use the more portable features in a database.\n ',0,'1','','',0,0),(478,177,'Ramola','eramola@gmail.com','','','2008-03-20 03:03:55','2008-03-20 03:03:55','1.How can i create database using SQL Server in Visual Studio 2005?\n2.Can i have the major syntax differences between MS SQL and MS Access\nThanks',0,'1','','',0,0),(479,177,'Andre','andre@andre.com','','','2008-05-16 18:09:40','2008-05-16 18:09:40','What a nonsense in previous comment! Rubbish! I have several MS Sql severs and couple of Oracle boxes around here and done bunch of comparisons. And I can say - MS SQL not even close! Especially when it comes to scalability! What a disaster with MS with all the dead locks , recourse contention etc. MS SQL doesn\'t scale well at all -  I had a case when pretty powerful server was dying with 280 ~ 300 or so concurrent users. Performance would grind to a halt and it required great finesse on my part to keep it going. So even with an overabundance of hardware, can\'t hack it. They\'ve tweaked it, but there is still the point, like all things, of diminishing returns. Oracle is engineered to scale - and scale it does! ',0,'1','','',0,0),(480,177,'Kapil','kapil.ibs@gmail.com','','','2008-08-08 03:39:28','2008-08-08 03:39:28','It was worth reading article and also the comments, can any one of you share any comparison between the price for both the databases, I mean which one is more economical.',0,'1','','',0,0),(481,178,'Tom Chiverton','tom.chiverton@halliwells.com','http://rachaelandtom.info/','','2007-11-12 05:53:33','2007-11-12 05:53:33','Do general purpose web mirroring tools like wget cope with CSS\'ed images ?',0,'1','','',0,0),(482,178,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.nutopia.com/terry','','2007-11-12 08:53:29','2007-11-12 08:53:29','I haven\'t tried that yet Tom. Actually it hit me last night; I should just parse the css files like I parse the html and rip out the image locations. I haven\'t done it yet though.',0,'1','','',0,0),(483,179,'Sam Farmer','sam.farmer@yahoo.com','http://samfarmer.com','','2007-11-14 08:59:19','2007-11-14 08:59:19','This is pretty damn cool.',0,'1','','',0,0),(484,179,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-11-14 17:36:36','2007-11-14 17:36:36','Thanks Sam, I \'m glad you like it. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(485,180,'dt','dt@dt.com','','','2007-11-14 20:31:27','2007-11-14 20:31:27','I enjoy the squidhead',0,'1','','',0,0),(486,180,'Nathan Mische','nmische@gmail.com','http://www.mischefamily.com/nathan','','2007-11-15 08:25:32','2007-11-15 08:25:32','I downloaded Squidhead yesterday and I plan on giving it a try in the next few days. I\'ll let you know how it goes. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(487,183,'Peter Bell','pbell@systemsforge.com','http://www.pbell.com','','2007-12-13 03:38:58','2007-12-13 03:38:58','It\'ll be good to see you there. Looks like I\'ll also be presenting there. I think it\'s gonna be a cool, conference!',0,'1','','',0,0),(488,183,'mensch','mensch53@hotmail.com','','','2007-12-13 09:09:07','2007-12-13 09:09:07','WOO!  DC!  I know where you should stay...',0,'1','','',0,0),(489,183,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2007-12-13 12:16:19','2007-12-13 12:16:19','@peter, yeah I noticed that you were one of the speakers. I look forward to finally meeting you.\n\n@Mensch, well I might just be bugging you for a place to stay. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(490,183,'Rob','ewhs59a@gmail.com','http://www.talkgold.com/forum/','','2007-12-16 14:10:16','2007-12-16 14:10:16','I\'ll see you guys there!',0,'1','','',0,0),(491,184,'Peter Bell','pbell@systemsforge.com','http://www.pbell.com','','2007-12-20 04:46:56','2007-12-20 04:46:56','Hey Terrence,\n\n(i) It\'ll be great to see you at cf.o().\n\n(ii) Hit me up offline about this. It matches perfectly with a set of issues I\'m working on and blog posts I\'ve been writing. I\'d definitely like to chat and compare notes.\nYou might also want to check out some of the TDD, XP and Agile lists as these topics come up quite a lot there since it\'s something we\'re all trying to figure out.\n\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(492,184,'Sammy Larbi','sam@codeodor.com','http://www.codeodor.com','','2007-12-20 08:30:28','2007-12-20 08:30:28','That definitely sounds like a good presentation.  Best of luck!',0,'1','','',0,0),(493,184,'J.Cruz','jcruz@wharton.upenn.edu','http://guamaniac.wordpress.com','','2007-12-21 21:00:08','2007-12-21 21:00:08','Dude, this sounds like some compelling stuff! Hopefully I can download some of the materials \'cause it sounds like it\'s riddled with soft skills that i\'m dying to learn more about!\n\nCongrats on the CFObjective nod, and break a leg!',0,'1','','',0,0),(494,184,'Peter Bell','pbell@systemsforge.com','http://www.pbell.com','','2007-12-23 22:02:14','2007-12-23 22:02:14','I just saw a quote from Martin Fowler that fits this perfectly:\n\n\"Change your organization - or change your organization.\"\n\nFor me it\'s client rather than organizations, but I do find I\'m starting to do a fair bit of both by changing my \"ground rules\" for engagements and focusing on the clients who can understand the benefits of the new approach. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(495,184,'James Burt','admin@nhse.org','http://www.nhse.org','','2008-02-26 01:02:00','2008-02-26 01:02:00','Congrats on your successful presentation!',0,'1','','',0,0),(496,185,'sriram','vijayareena@gmail.com','http://www.cattechnologies.com/offshoreColdFusionDevelopment.aspx','','2008-01-18 05:01:30','2008-01-18 05:01:30','how is coldfusion related to market shares.',0,'1','','',0,0),(497,188,'Sam Farmer','sam.farmer@yahoo.com','http://samfarmer.com','','2008-01-23 10:28:57','2008-01-23 10:28:57','Congratulations!  Well deserved.',0,'1','','',0,0),(498,188,'Rob Brooks-Bilson','rbils@amkor.com','','','2008-01-23 11:14:34','2008-01-23 11:14:34','Congrats!',0,'1','','',0,0),(499,188,'Kurt','kurtklinger@gmail.com','http://blog.kurtopia.com','','2008-01-23 16:59:06','2008-01-23 16:59:06','Congratulations, Terry!',0,'1','','',0,0),(500,188,'nicholas','mail@nicksollecito.com','http://nicksollecito.com','','2008-01-23 17:51:02','2008-01-23 17:51:02','Congrats!\n\n7 months into the whole \"being a dad\" thing myself, I\'m not sure you can ever get the hang of it!\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(501,188,'Peter Bell','pbell@systemsforge.com','http://www.pbell.com','','2008-01-27 23:53:19','2008-01-27 23:53:19','Congratulations!',0,'1','','',0,0),(502,189,'John Allen','johnfallen@gmail.com','http://johnfallen@instantspot.com','','2008-01-31 22:21:18','2008-01-31 22:21:18','Cool.\n\nVery cool.',0,'1','','',0,0),(503,189,'Clint Herlihy','clint49@yahoo.com','','','2008-02-01 09:15:41','2008-02-01 09:15:41','You\'re very creative :)\nI whish I knew that way when I was using Basecamp, it could be less painfull then. Well, anyway, I gave up on Basecamp. I\'m with Wrike.com now.\n\nGood luck with your projects!',0,'1','','',0,0),(504,189,'Nicolas','n@walkingmen.com','','','2008-02-04 06:40:30','2008-02-04 06:40:30','Great idea, Terry, thanks!\nI\'ve been trying to get it to work on my dev server but I can\'t go pass the login screen.\nThe error is thrown by line 629:  \"Error in Underlying Web Call - 403 Forbidden\".\nI tried with http and even https BC accounts (https://basecampsandbox.projectpath.com guest/guest), but no joy.\nAny idea where I should start looking to fix this?\nThanks again for the good work!\nn.',0,'1','','',0,0),(505,189,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2008-02-04 17:16:05','2008-02-04 17:16:05','Nicolas: Is the Basecamp API enabled?',0,'1','','',0,0),(506,189,'Jay','jayb@jsarch.com','http://www.jsarch.com','','2008-02-05 07:30:24','2008-02-05 07:30:24','This is a great idea.  One problem...I\'m a non-technical, non-developer basecamp user who would like to use this.\n\nCan this be made accessible on the web?  This is such a great tool, I would be willing to pay for the priviledge of archiving my basecamp projects to PDF.  Seriously!  We already pay for basecamp, this would be a great addition.',0,'1','','',0,0),(507,189,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2008-02-05 10:06:38','2008-02-05 10:06:38','I responded to Jay off-blog, but I am exploring options and business models for a publicly available web application.\n\nIf anyone is interested please drop me a line through my contact page.',0,'1','','',0,0),(508,189,'Sandy Kirtland','sandykirtland@gmail.com','','','2008-02-06 15:59:05','2008-02-06 15:59:05','Hi Terry, please put me on the list of interested folks like Jay who could use a dead simple method getting a pdf archive of a project  ... probably other things too later ????\n\nThanks',0,'1','','',0,0),(509,190,'Brian Kotek','brian428@gmail.com','http://www.briankotek.com/blog','','2008-02-01 12:49:46','2008-02-01 12:49:46','Don\'t forget ColdMock! ;-) http://coldmock.riaforge.org',0,'1','','',0,0),(510,190,'Registered User','terry@numtopia.com','','','2008-02-01 17:54:28','2008-02-01 17:54:28','Sorry about that. I\'ve updated the post.',0,'1','','',0,0),(511,190,'Download','suarri@gmail.com','http://www.goodonlinegames.org','','2008-06-05 19:51:29','2008-06-05 19:51:29','If you have steady approach/religion by implementing/designing TDD I think is useless here. If you have some specific area and very specific logic where there\'s a more than few classes in collaboration process then yes, TDD can help to move to the mature/reusable status.',0,'1','','',0,0),(512,190,'alvin','alvins1982@hotmail.com','http://www.alvinsingh.org/blog','','2008-09-12 00:16:12','2008-09-12 00:16:12','The example you gave about testing the page you just changed in your browser or CFC app is not entirely correct (I can see where you were coming from though) -  this is not a unit test. It is an integration test.\n\nSlightly related to this - is still saving that test that you did in your browser or CFC app is important. I comment on this issue in my latest post here - http://www.alvinsingh.org/blog/2008/09/whats-wrong-with-current-web-testing-approaches/.',0,'1','','',0,0),(513,191,'Sam Farmer','sam.farmer@yahoo.com','http://samfarmer.com','','2008-02-07 13:21:59','2008-02-07 13:21:59','Nice.',0,'1','','',0,0),(514,192,'Hal Helms','hal.helms@gmail.com','','','2008-02-08 10:21:00','2008-02-08 10:21:00','Nice idea, Terrence. Documentation is too often left for last (or not at all). As you said, the key is having something that\'s easy and automatic.',0,'1','','',0,0),(515,192,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2008-02-08 10:23:18','2008-02-08 10:23:18','Thanks, Hal, that is high praise coming from you. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(516,192,'Jim Priest','priest@thecrumb.com','http://www.thecrumb.com','','2008-02-08 10:23:32','2008-02-08 10:23:32','Can we see some code :)\n\nThis sounds really cool and anything integrated with Ant is a plus! :)',0,'1','','',0,0),(517,192,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2008-02-08 11:49:56','2008-02-08 11:49:56','I\'ll try and post something this weekend. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(518,193,'Jim Priest','priest@thecrumb.com','http://www.thecrumb.com','','2008-02-08 12:57:37','2008-02-08 12:57:37','Thanks for the followup!  I\'m going to tinker with this just as soon as I finish up my current project!',0,'1','','',0,0),(519,193,'halloween costumes','halloweencostume@i.ua','http://www.netvibes.com/halloweencostumes','','2008-08-25 18:22:52','2008-08-25 18:22:52','very informative, thanks',0,'1','','',0,0),(520,194,'Big Mad Kev','kev@inner-rhythm.co.uk','http://inner-rhythm.co.uk/blog','','2008-02-14 11:18:59','2008-02-14 11:18:59','I have to agree, never install the ODBC Server options in either install, standard or Enterprise unless you know up front that you will need them, and as you say it\'s easy enough to install afterwards ;)\n\nODBC Services are the Devils spawn :D',0,'1','','',0,0),(521,194,'Torans','marlow.rence@gmail.com','','','2009-02-16 04:16:51','2009-02-16 04:16:51','I\'m newbie in this sphere, but need the issue for my work, thus try to educate myself - recently have downlaoded  a nice guide by means of http://rapid4me.com/ and now came across your article. Thanks for sharing!',0,'1','','',0,0),(522,194,'Rapidshare Search','qtel86@gmail.com','http://rapid4shared.com','','2009-02-23 14:03:17','2009-02-23 14:03:17','thank you for this article',0,'1','','',0,0),(523,195,'Mark Drew','mark.drew@gmail.com','http://www.markdrew.co.uk','','2008-07-01 04:42:01','2008-07-01 04:42:01','Which version of Eclipse does this work on? 3.3 and up?\n\nMD',0,'1','','',0,0),(524,195,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2008-07-01 13:58:57','2008-07-01 13:58:57','I can confirm it works in Eclipse 3.3.  I don\'t know a previous versions. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(525,195,'Eduardo','duardosm@gmail.com','','','2008-07-22 17:16:26','2008-07-22 17:16:26','Very good tip :)\n\nI was spending some time just to commit my codes.',0,'1','','',0,0),(526,196,'Jim Priest','priest@thecrumb.com','http://www.thecrumb.com','','2008-02-19 14:40:24','2008-02-19 14:40:24','Must find time to implement! :)',0,'1','','',0,0),(527,196,'zac spitzer','zac.spitzer@gmail.com','http://zacster.blogspot.com/','','2008-02-19 22:04:58','2008-02-19 22:04:58','I think your heading slightly down the wrong track here, SVN commit messages are intended for developer level info, not for the end user.\n\nMaking release notes off your commits would make me likely to commit less often and in big chunks, making rolling back harder.\n\nThis all relates back to the discussions on commenting your code as discussed here http://steve-yegge.blogspot.com/2008/02/portrait-of-n00b.html\n\nI use JIRA and include a task key in every commit message which ties back to a task in the project database. This task contains a nice title and description and can capture much more useful information (ie business related information).\n\nJIRA then parses all SVN commit messages and ties them back into the associated task.\n\nYou can then produce release notes based on a release (defined by the associated task in the project db) and just not a date range\n\nAt the end of the day it comes down to personal preference.\n\nThat said, useful stuff..have you looked into the JavaSVN library?',0,'1','','',0,0),(528,196,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2008-02-20 17:19:23','2008-02-20 17:19:23','@Zac We might be playing with semantics here.  \"Release notes\" might not be exactly what I\'m creating. The documentation I use this for does go to other developers, so maybe I\'m not quite getting the perfect term.\n\nI\'ve fooled around withe the JavaSVN stuff but bang for my effort just calling the executable from CF has given me great results. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(529,196,'honda new jersey','gorav@gmail.com','http://www.viphonda.com/','','2009-11-23 07:05:37','2009-11-23 07:05:37','I often read your blog and always find it very interesting. Thought it was about time i let you knowKeep up the great work',0,'1','','',0,0),(530,198,'Dan','danvega@gmail.com','http://www.danvega.org/blog','','2008-03-01 20:42:51','2008-03-01 20:42:51','The default action for a form is to post to itself. If I am posting a form to itself I just omit the action attribute.',0,'1','','',0,0),(531,198,'Todd Rafferty','webRat@gmail.com','http://www.web-rat.com/','','2008-03-01 21:54:54','2008-03-01 21:54:54','Just confirming what Dan said.',0,'1','','',0,0),(532,198,'Rob Huddleston','rob@filmstosee.com','http://www.robhuddleston.com','','2008-03-01 22:16:39','2008-03-01 22:16:39','Just to clarify Dan and Todd\'s comment: the default action of a <em>cfform</em> is to post to itself. There is no default action for plain old HTML forms.',0,'1','','',0,0),(533,198,'Dan G. Switzer, II','dswitzer@pengoworks.com','http://blog.pengoworks.com/','','2008-03-01 22:18:34','2008-03-01 22:18:34','Just remember that cgi.script_name may not always return the expected results. You can\'t always rely on CGI variables--since they\'re web  server specific.\n\nI prefer using getFileFromPath(getBaseTemplatePath()) as it should work with any web server.',0,'1','','',0,0),(534,198,'Ron Fuller','ron_fuller@mentor.com','','','2008-03-01 23:31:14','2008-03-01 23:31:14','Boring. I don\'t even use forms anymore.',0,'1','','',0,0),(535,198,'barry.b','barry.beattie@gmail.com','','','2008-03-02 07:31:10','2008-03-02 07:31:10','@Terrance\n\nI (mostly) agree with you and do exactly as you (and never had a problem with CGI variables doing this)\n\nbut the downside is that it takes a few cycles to get that SCRIPT_NAME whereas if it were hardcoded, there would be none.',0,'1','','',0,0),(536,198,'Todd Rafferty','webRat@gmail.com','http://www.web-rat.com/','','2008-03-02 08:34:46','2008-03-02 08:34:46','cgi.script_name isn\'t completely unpredictable here and Apache / IIS aren\'t that much of a screwball that they return randomness.  I have experience running CF on both Windows / Centos, as well as Apache / IIS.\n\nI also wanted to confirm that Rob\'s confirmation of Dan / Mine\'s confirmation was that the default action of cfform is to post to itself is definitely the correct confirmation.',0,'1','','',0,0),(537,198,'Terrence Ryan','terrence.p.ryan@gmail.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2008-03-03 10:24:00','2008-03-03 10:24:00','Wow, so much traction on such a small topic.\n\nOkay, good point about the default action of cfform.  I hadn\'t realized that. I would probably keep doing cgi.script_name as it would be consistent between cfform\'s and plain old forms.\n\nAs for the processing hit of getting a cgi variable.  I would have to conclude that this is premature optimization, as the variables already exist. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(538,199,'Steve Nelson','snelson@webapper.com','http://www.webapper.net','','2008-03-08 04:40:56','2008-03-08 04:40:56','Are you presenting at CFUNITED? I\'m doing a presentation on building offline apps using Google Gears (SQLLite).\n\nIf you\'re playing with SQLLite, I think you\'ll dig this presentation I\'m doing. It\'s mostly about rethinking how to build db driven apps so they work offline. All the concepts will apply to an AIR app.',0,'1','','',0,0),(539,199,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2008-03-09 00:37:35','2008-03-09 00:37:35','Actually I\'m presenting at Webmaniacs.\n\nJust trying to get some more sample example applications yet. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(540,200,'Jeff Porten','jeff@jeffporten.com','http://www.jeffporten.com','','2008-03-08 01:30:16','2008-03-08 01:30:16','Best of luck with the new venture!',0,'1','','',0,0),(541,200,'Sam Farmer','sam@samfarmer.com','http://samfarmer.com','','2008-03-08 09:13:28','2008-03-08 09:13:28','Good luck.  Looks cool.',0,'1','','',0,0),(542,200,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2008-03-09 00:39:41','2008-03-09 00:39:41','Thanks for the well wishes guys. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(543,201,'Mark Drew','mark.drew@gmail.com','http://www.markdrew.co.uk','','2008-03-11 02:57:49','2008-03-11 02:57:49','Ryan, I think one of the bonuses of this is the licensing of BD. Whatever my thoughts on the engine, it means I can develop an app, and package everything up including the engine as a WAR and deploy it, without problems with the license.\n\nNow, of course, I would have to have the right servlet container to deploy it to, but that is another rant!\n\n\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(544,201,'Tom Mollerus','tom@mollerus.net','http://www.mollerus.net/tom/blog/','','2008-03-11 09:03:49','2008-03-11 09:03:49','I disagree that cost is the direct reason that PHP or RoR are so popular compared to ColdFusion, because I doubt that any but a small portion of site owners have ever actually compared the cost of different application servers. Instead, I think they\'ve looked at two things: what\'s available in their hosting plan, and what languages the developers they know are familiar with.\n\nIn my opinion, CF needs to be put on many more web hosting accounts for people to even consider it, regardless of cost.',0,'1','','',0,0),(545,201,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2008-03-11 10:32:00','2008-03-11 10:32:00','Drew, I respect your opinion, and I believe a small segment of the communinity <strong>might</strong> take advantage of that, I don\'t think that really lights the community on fire.\n\nWho knows, maybe it will be used in ways I can\'t fathom, but I\'m very skeptical of this. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(546,201,'Mike Rankin','anodynepres@gmail.com','http://mrmx.blogspot.com','','2008-03-11 11:37:15','2008-03-11 11:37:15','I agree with you Terrence,  this is just not that much news.  I don\'t expect to see much impact from the change in the short term.  I think it\'s probably more of an attempt to utilize cfeclipse to get some additional distribution of the BD engine.  Then they will hope to use that the build a little product tie-in.  ',0,'1','','',0,0),(547,201,'Jim Priest','priest@thecrumb.com','http://www.thecrumb.com','','2008-03-11 14:38:53','2008-03-11 14:38:53','FWIW open-source != free!!!\n\n@Mike - where does CFEclipse come into this picture??\n\nI could really care less about market share (though I thought Adobe said CF was growing?).\n\nI do care about having the option to deploy a 100% open-source stack and not having to worry about licenses, etc.  It will be interesting to see how things go...\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(548,201,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2008-03-11 14:42:49','2008-03-11 14:42:49','@Jim - I was acknowledging that open source does not equal free when I said <ul><li>ColdFusion would gain market share if it was open source.</li>\n<li>By \"open source\" we actually mean \"free.\"</li></ul>\n\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(549,201,'Justin Carter','justin.w.carter@gmail.com','http://www.madfellas.com','','2008-03-11 18:55:37','2008-03-11 18:55:37','I\'m skeptical that much will change too, but I totally agree with Jim that there are plenty of people who care about deploying apps on a 100% open-source stack (or a platform that has no licensing costs). People outside the CF community are far less likely to ever choose to implement an open-source application written in CF because you have to pay for the license, whereas open-source apps from other platforms don\'t have this problem. This could also be a chance to get developers from the \"other\" side...',0,'1','','',0,0),(550,201,'David','domalley@medifit.com','','','2008-03-13 10:02:46','2008-03-13 10:02:46',' I think the great part about this announcement is that the \"open source ColdFusion\" fan boys will now have to put up or shut up. Think Adobe\'s CF would be a better product and win market share as open source? Great, prove it! Make BD open source totally kickass (To paraphrase Cartman)! I now expect legions of CF developers to start working on BD immediately, and post success after shining success to the blogosphere.\n\nOf course, there\'s the *very* slight possibility that it won\'t turn out like that. In which case I\'m sure the fanboys will attempt to move the goal posts and insist it was Adobe\'s fault because they didn\'t [insert open source buzzword here] the [insert ColdFusion framework jargon here] and if they did, there would have been total success - oh what an opportunity Adobe missed to increase market share!\n\nGet at it guys - I expect BD to be dominating this time next year.\n\nCheers,\n\nDavo\n\n\n\n\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(551,201,'H Jaber','393@7079.net','http://webexterminator.com','','2008-04-09 22:40:40','2008-04-09 22:40:40','Just ran across this post, one thing that we forget is how easy and fast it is to create a CF app. OpenBD may open things up for other devs in other languages to come on board and start writing more OS software. I just looked at the steering committee and it looks like a great list of devs who IMO will help to create more of what we need as developers.\n\nI look forward to the OpenBD, I think it\'s a plus for everyone!',0,'1','','',0,0),(552,201,'Pete','floydophone@gmail.com','','','2008-04-18 03:55:17','2008-04-18 03:55:17','First thing I\'m gonna do is fix all the stupid idiotic bugs that STILL exist in CF (forms tags etc).\n\nNext thing I\'m gonna do is replace the built-in expression and CFScript evaluator with Jython.',0,'1','','',0,0),(553,201,'Michael','prenust@gmail.com','http://www.virtualvillagers3.net','','2008-05-17 06:31:32','2008-05-17 06:31:32','This is great news and I am psyched about NA\'s decision to open source BD. I really think this will expand the install base and community!',0,'1','','',0,0),(554,201,'Steven','yangsadr@gmail.com','http://www.massiveonlinegames.org','','2008-05-19 17:54:23','2008-05-19 17:54:23','I don\'t agree, with a free version doors open to projects where having an overhead on the product doesn\'t make sense so you do it in PHP or .NET.',0,'1','','',0,0),(555,201,'Goreny','jegeso@gmail.com','http://www.webtelefonkonyv.hu','','2008-07-02 11:23:23','2008-07-02 11:23:23','I agree with you Terrence, ',0,'1','','',0,0),(556,201,'Goonie','selalujujur@gmail.com','http://www.xcarkey.com','','2008-07-03 05:31:51','2008-07-03 05:31:51','Ryan, it\'s a good news for me, but I a little bit skeptic with Open Source. many open source have many Bugs (I think because of Open Source=Free) so People do not deep care with the development.',0,'1','','',0,0),(557,202,'Play games','suarri@gmail.com','http://www.favplay.com','','2008-05-31 20:59:53','2008-05-31 20:59:53','ColdFusion Weekly Podcast is great podcast...',0,'1','','',0,0),(558,202,'earth4energy','jasontpopper@gmail.com','http://www.earth-4energy.org','','2008-09-27 03:05:21','2008-09-27 03:05:21','Great product',0,'1','','',0,0),(559,204,'marc esher','marc.esher@gmail.com','http://mxunit.org','','2008-03-26 15:46:34','2008-03-26 15:46:34','he will? but he seemed so nice at max last year. who knew he was a manhunter?',0,'1','','',0,0),(560,208,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2008-05-05 16:44:23','2008-05-05 16:44:23','@Guamanaic Thanks a lot.  I didn\'t think about it, but this definitely could be extended past development. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(561,208,'Ryan Stewart','rstewart@adobe.com','http://blog.digitalbackcountry.com','','2008-05-05 18:21:30','2008-05-05 18:21:30','Pssssttttt......(share.adobe.com).\n\nEmbeddable goodness ;)',0,'1','','',0,0),(562,208,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2008-05-05 18:47:50','2008-05-05 18:47:50','@ryan, dude, don\'t you know anything, share doesn\'t work with Powerpoint. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(563,208,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2008-05-05 19:26:03','2008-05-05 19:26:03','I *was* joking, but I uploaded my pptx files (Office 2008) and Share doesn\'t roll with them.    ',0,'1','','',0,0),(564,208,'Ryan Stewart','rstewart@adobe.com','http://blog.digitalbackcountry.com','','2008-05-05 19:37:03','2008-05-05 19:37:03','PPTX makes the baby Bruce Chizen cry.\n\nbackwards convert and then upload them. I want to see the pretty slides everyone was Twittering about.',0,'1','','',0,0),(565,208,'Ryan Stewart','ryan@ryanstewart.net','http://blog.digitalbackcountry.com','','2008-05-05 19:18:09','2008-05-05 19:18:09','Ummmm, I just uploaded some Powerpoints and they\'re working just fine.\n\nSpeed of innovation baby!',0,'1','','',0,0),(566,208,'Guamaniac','jcruz@wharton.upenn.edu','https://blogs.wharton.upenn.edu/staff/joecruz','','2008-05-04 12:24:01','2008-05-04 12:24:01','Great presentation, Terry.  I read through it and I think I can adopt some of what you\'re saying to push through some non-development projects that i\'m working on.  Great work!',0,'1','','',0,0),(567,208,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2008-05-05 22:10:22','2008-05-05 22:10:22','No need to invoke the baby Bruce Chizen.  There\'s your share version. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(568,208,'Brian Meloche','brianmeloche@gmail.com','http://www.brianmeloche.com','','2008-05-06 01:33:17','2008-05-06 01:33:17','Now I REALLY regret missing your presentation live, Terry!  Awesome stuff, and thanks for posting it.  You\'ve got the moral persuasion tactics down pat!  You have to get into the head of people to convince them, and this is great food for thought.  And, if you can ever convert a \"hostile\", let me know.',0,'1','','',0,0),(569,210,'Nick Kwiatkowski','quetwo@hostingplace.net','http://quetwo.wordpress.com','','2008-05-04 18:09:01','2008-05-04 18:09:01','I find myself doing this often -- and try to catch myself.  I always start with a thank you, but in an automatic mode (often time, after a long talk you are in a daze anyway), I tend to be down on myself and only take the criticisms (even if they are from myself).  It is just one of those things that you learn, I guess!',0,'1','','',0,0),(570,210,'charlie arehart','charlie_lists@carehart.org','http://carehart.org/','','2008-05-05 08:28:27','2008-05-05 08:28:27','You make a great point, Terrence. That said, I think there\'s a 3rd reason people may say this to a speaker: when it\'s true. :-) I\'ve observed occasions where people feel compelled to say \"great job\" even when, in fact, the speaker did screw up or flounder.\n\nFlipping the script, it\'s as if some people feel the need to bolster others even when they clearly dropped the ball. (Maybe goes back to childhood experiences: \"It\'s ok dear, mommy was gonna get rid of that old Ming vase anyway. You go out and play.\")\n\nSo the sad truth is that this confuses the whole issue, and I\'d bet that some speakers are savvy to this point, so if they DO feel they messed up, and someone still says \"great job\", they may be inclined to wonder if it\'s just vacuous propping up. :-)\n\nThat said, I agree that if someone\'s a) stuck around for the whole session and b) still comes up after and says great job, then they probably do mean it sincerely, and folks should consider your points.',0,'1','','',0,0),(571,210,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2008-05-05 16:09:31','2008-05-05 16:09:31','I hear what you\'re saying, but I would argue that even in that case, you have someone blowing smoke up your ass, you still shouldn\'t disagree with them. Either you did well or not; either you are capable of determining that for yourself or not.  But if an audience member is expressing happiness with you, roll with it.\nLeave the self-analysis in your head, unless the person is already a friend. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(572,210,'Bjorn H.','voidon@poczta.fm','','','2008-05-16 08:57:23','2008-05-16 08:57:23','Technically speaking, there is nothing wrong with \"Great job\" and \"I thought it went awfully\". What could be pleasing to one person, may be unacceptable in another person\'s standards. One may disagree about evaluation of accomplishments, especially when you judge harshly your own work. It is worse when one say \"I made great job\" and the audience is \"We though it went awfully\". ;-)\n\nAnd when presenter says \"I did not do anything special\" it may actually be the truth. It depends on the amount of work put into the process. ;-)\n\nLast but not least - MODESTY.\n\nTake care,\nBjorn H.\nGenerally, I agree on taking compliments with  grace. It is all about specific cases.\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(573,210,'Besty Buchanan','betsybuchanan1@yahoo.com','http://betsybuchanan.com/','','2008-07-08 20:58:01','2008-07-08 20:58:01','Funny thing, but I\'ve noticed that most people find it very difficult in excepting a compliment AND that they desperately need the person who gave them the compliment to come back and give them another because of their insecurities. I think most people really need to be \"stroked\" as they say.\nBest Wishes,\nBetsy Buchanan',0,'1','','',0,0),(574,210,'honda dealership pittsburgh','gorav@gmail.com','http://www.southhillshonda.com','','2009-11-24 05:16:13','2009-11-24 05:16:13','I subscribed to your blog when is the next post',0,'1','','',0,0),(575,210,'Jewel64','jewel_brite@yahoo.com','','','2010-10-19 17:40:57','2010-10-19 17:40:57','THIS IS UTTER BS!\nI always felt the only way people would like me if I constantly compliment them. I got friends this, way, but then these people kept expecting me to be their constant ego booster without complimenting me or supporting me in return. As a result of my desperation, I attracted selfish, self-absorbed, self-centered people instead of true friends. Once I stopped complimenting them, they stopped coming around. To me, complimenting people puts YOU in an INFERIOR position! It automatically is saying, \"you\'re great, I\'m not, so I have to acknowledge your greatness so you\'ll keep liking me.\" That is MY EXPERIENCE WITH COMPLIMENTS. Yeah, people need stroking, BUT SO DO I!!!! If you don\'t compliment people, stay aloof, and have a SUPERIOR ATTITUDE, then people will begin to think YOU ARE IMPORTANT and deserving of compliments. Then they will start. If you start the compliments, people will expect it and not give you any back when you are deserving.\nAND I HATE PEOPLE WHO FEIGN FALSE MODESTY AFTER YOU COMPLIMENT THEM!',0,'1','','',0,0),(576,211,'Nathan Mische','nmische@gmail.com','http://www.mischefamily.com/nathan','','2008-05-05 14:02:06','2008-05-05 14:02:06','I seem to remember I was in a similar state of \"sadness\" on day three of last year\'s conference... Sounds like this year\'s cfObjective was just as good as last year\'s, hopefully I\'ll have the opportunity to make the next one.',0,'1','','',0,0),(577,212,'Steve Bryant','steve@bryantwebconsulting.com','http://www.bryantwebconsulting.com/','','2008-05-06 09:47:32','2008-05-06 09:47:32','I would definitely vote for a \"Formal Code Reviews\" presentation from you. I have loved reading your blog entries on the topic and I think a live presentation would be even better.',0,'1','','',0,0),(578,212,'Richard Davies','Richard@richarddavies.us','http://www.richarddavies.us','','2008-05-06 14:46:45','2008-05-06 14:46:45','I had a good time at cf.Objective too and agree with your general assessment of the conference. I also enjoyed your presentation and the chance to meet you afterwards (remember me...?) ;-)\n\nI think any of your \"soft skills\" ideas would be interesting. BTW, how does one become a presenter at conferences? Is it by invitation, or do you submit an idea to the organizers, etc?',0,'1','','',0,0),(579,213,'Dan Roberts','danielmroberts@gmail.com','','','2008-05-14 14:22:19','2008-05-14 14:22:19','How about making IP phone calls out of ColdFusion. That would be cool.\n\nOnError:\n\n<cfphonecall callid=\"ERROR ERROR\" voicesynth=\"benforta\" call=\"#adminMobile#\">\n  Warning. An error has occurred.\n</cfphonecall>\n\nBetter yet an avatar on screen that talks\n\n<cfphonecall avatar=\"benforta\" creepyeyesfollowcursor=\"yes\">\n  Hello, welcome to my ColdFusion blog\n</cfphonecall>',0,'1','','',0,0),(580,213,'Dan Roberts','danielmroberts@gmail.com','','','2008-05-14 14:24:09','2008-05-14 14:24:09','...Well I failed in posting demo code, one more try...\n\nHow about making IP phone calls out of ColdFusion. That would be cool.\n\nOnError:\n\n&lt;cfphonecall callid=\"ERROR ERROR\" voicesynth=\"benforta\" call=\"#adminMobile#\"&gt;\n  Warning. An error has occurred.\n&lt;/cfphonecall&gt;\n\nBetter yet an avatar on screen that talks\n\n&lt;cfavatar model=\"benforta\" creepyeyesfollowcursor=\"yes\"&gt;\n  Hello, welcome to my ColdFusion blog\n&lt;/cfavatar&gt;',0,'1','','',0,0),(581,213,'someone','notd@important.com','','','2008-05-14 14:27:58','2008-05-14 14:27:58','Some CFers say that this kind of enhancements turn ColdFusion into a toy. I disagree, ColdFusion is great because of all \'complicated-things-made-easy\' and video manipulation is no exception. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(582,213,'Matt Woodward','matt@mattwoodward.com','http://mattwoodward.com/blog/','','2008-05-14 15:03:22','2008-05-14 15:03:22','Just to give a different perspective, video manipulation, encoding, etc. is SO not ColdFusion\'s job. If they put it in CF 9 I am going to have serious doubts about the decision-making process at Adobe. Just because they did it with images (which as an aside, I think does make sense) doesn\'t mean they should do it with video.\n\nDo people understand what a processor-intensive operation video encoding is, not to mention all the extra junk that will be in CF to handle this even if 99% of CF users never use it?',0,'1','','',0,0),(583,213,'Jason Dean','jason@12robots.com','http://www.12robots.com','','2008-05-14 15:19:04','2008-05-14 15:19:04','While it would be cool, I think I have to agree with Matt, it\'s not really ColdFusion\'s place to be doing video editing.\n\nThat said, there are other solutions to getting video done in such a way. Using something like SoThinkMedia\'s Flash Video Encoder with cfexecute and some creative use of custom tags may give you what you are looking for.\n\nJust a thought',0,'1','','',0,0),(584,213,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2008-05-14 16:14:48','2008-05-14 16:14:48','I hear what both @jason and @matt are saying.  However, I have to disagree, ColdFusion\'s job to me has always been make hard things easy.  Working with user developed video on the web isn\'t easy for the average developer yet. Adobe can make it so.\n\nAs for processor and space issues.  I agree that it is daunting, but we keep seeing power and space increase every year.  It takes multiple years to develop a CF version.  By the time cf9 comes out, the hardware will be a factor more ready to deal with these issues.\n\nAs opposed to cfimage, I would like to see Coldfusion ahead of customer demand instead of behind it. This demand is coming, it would be nice to see ColdFusion ready to handle it. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(585,213,'Matt Woodward','matt@mattwoodward.com','http://www.mattwoodward.com/blog','','2008-05-14 16:43:02','2008-05-14 16:43:02','I\'d counter by asking if it\'s a web developer\'s job to deal with video? Moreover, is it a web application server\'s job to deal with video? In both cases I\'d say no. Furthermore, there are already PLENTY of products that DO make dealing with video easy. I suspect that people asking for cfvideo haven\'t looked into what some of the enterprise-level video encoders and video servers can do. \"But it\'s not ColdFusion!\" people will counter, but I digress ...\n\nI\'m always VERY wary when people say things like \"Don\'t worry about it--the hardware will be so powerful it won\'t matter!\" Faster hardware is not an answer to bloatware, which is what adding video processing capabilities will turn ColdFusion into.\n\nAdobe has solutions to do everything with video you could possibly imagine, and yes, on the server side and programmatically, just not with ColdFusion. In my opinion it should stay that way. Throwing crap like this in to impress my boss and get him to buy more CF licenses is not the way to make a good product.\n\nI suppose this gets into the question of what ColdFusion is, and what Adobe wants it to be in the future. If they\'re going to indiscriminately say \"yes\" to every idea they hear, we\'re in for very rough times ahead.\n\nHey, I know, in addition to cfvideo let\'s throw ActionScript 3 support in there while we\'re at it! It\'ll be a big ol\' party! My server processors, RAM, and disk space as well as the performance of applications will suffer for it, but the eye candy will impress my boss! :-)',0,'1','','',0,0),(586,213,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2008-05-14 16:50:33','2008-05-14 16:50:33','Actually, Matt, I\'m a big user of Premiere and I have done a very little bit with Flash Media Server.  I am aware of Adobe\'s other tools.\n\nI\'m not saying that the hardware will definitely be ready to handle it.  I\'m saying that people are definitely going to want their web apps to handle video.\n\nSo is is a web developer/server\'s job to deal with video.  I would say increasing yes.  The success of YouTube is changing user\'s expectation of what can happen on the web. You might not see it as your job, but users are increasingly going to think it is.\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(587,213,'Brock Baxter','bb1985@hotmail.com','','','2008-05-14 16:50:54','2008-05-14 16:50:54','@Matt: Adobe got where it is in the marketplace by anticipating future demands--just like Terrence said.\n\nAdobe is not here for performance, or to avoid bloatware, or any of that (just check out the size of a CF8 installation if you have doubts).\n\nColdFusion is here to make things EASY, and if it helps make online video editing EASIER, then what is the problem?\n\nI\'m all for it--there were people who thought PDF manipulation was a bad idea a few years back, but now it\'s really the best thing CF has going for it!',0,'1','','',0,0),(588,213,'Matt Woodward','matt@mattwoodward.com','http://www.mattwoodward.com/blog','','2008-05-14 16:57:54','2008-05-14 16:57:54','Well, I could go back and forth with people on this all day, so I\'ll bow out by saying that it concerns me, with all the stuff they could be doing to make CF better, that they\'re going to spend engineering time (and likely a lot of it) rolling something into CF that just doesn\'t need to be there. I\'m sure Adobe is thinking \"one product to rule them all\" but where does it end? CF\'s going to collapse under its own weight if they keep going in this direction.',0,'1','','',0,0),(589,213,'Matt Woodward','matt@mattwoodward.com','http://mattwoodward.com/blog/','','2008-05-14 17:23:19','2008-05-14 17:23:19','Just to throw another idea out there (yeah, I know I said I\'d shut up), how about cfmusic? Music\'s pretty important on the web--why shouldn\'t CF be able to handle music encoding/re-encoding, auto-generating snippets, making ring tones, and doing remixes? I know--combine cfmusic and cfvideo into a cfvideosoundtrack tag to provide a fullly integrated solution!\n\nAnd if anyone says \"great idea!\" I may lose my mind. :-)',0,'1','','',0,0),(590,213,'Dan Roberts','danielmroberts@gmail.com','','','2008-05-14 18:23:08','2008-05-14 18:23:08','I think you are onto something Matt :-)',0,'1','','',0,0),(591,213,'Terrence Ryan','terry@numtopia.com','http://www.numtopia.com/terry','','2008-05-14 18:29:33','2008-05-14 18:29:33','Well, cfvideo would require some cfaudio. You would have to be able to cut and manipulate the accompanying sound.\n\nI think it is Reductio Ad Absurdum to go as far as ring tones as remixes.  ',0,'1','','',0,0),(592,213,'Matt Woodward','matt@mattwoodward.com','http://www.mattwoodward.com/blog','','2008-05-14 20:16:46','2008-05-14 20:16:46','So we\'re talking cfaudio too. FANtastic. Can hardly wait.\n\nI guess I just think about this stuff completely differently than the people who want this because cutting and manipulating SOUND now too--in ColdFusion?!?!?--that\'s Reductio Ad Absurdum to me.',0,'1','','',0,0),(593,213,'Mark Galeassi','aitf311@gmail.com','http://www.career.umkc.edu','','2008-05-14 20:49:41','2008-05-14 20:49:41','This would be a great idea. I have seen Railo has implemented cfvideo but I have not had a chance to check it out yet.',0,'1','','',0,0),(594,213,'Michael Streit','michael.streit@railo.ch','http://www.railo.ch','','2008-05-15 04:38:16','2008-05-15 04:38:16','Next release (available at June) of Railo will indroduce 3 new Tags:\n- cfvideo\n- cfvideoplayer\n- cfvideoplayerparam\n\ncfvideo allows to convert, concat videos, get info about the video and cut out images. all in various formats.\n\ncfvideoplayer/cfvideoplayerparam will allows playing flash and mp4 (flash 9 required) videos in a online player, you can arrange video group, playlists ...\n\ntake a first view of the player and some attribute infos of the tags at http://preview.railo.ch/video/\n\ngreetings Michael\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(595,213,'IJWebsites','ijwebsites@comcast.net','http://www.robs3dblog.com/','','2008-05-16 17:42:38','2008-05-16 17:42:38','I just stumbled upon this blog post and i wanted to throw in my two cents.\n\nI\'m not exactly sure how I feel about a cfvideo tag.  I know I would like a Coldfusion tag that I could just type in something like this:\n\n<cfvideo src=\"/myvideo.swf\" skin=\"orange\" width=\"300\" height=\"250\"></cfvideo>\n\nAll the tag would do is display my .swf video or .flv video file in a Flash compatible skinned player.\n\nI would also love a <cfflash> tag, one that would automatically correct the problem in IE and how it displays flash.  All you would need to do is type in <cfflash src=\"/myFlash.swf\" width=\"\" height=\"\"></cfflash> and that would write all of the code needed to display a .swf file in any browser on the internet.  It would auto-correct the crappy IE problem.\n\nI\'m not sure how you would use CF to manipulate video.  I guess I have always seen Flash Pro and Premiere the tools to do that with from Adobe.\n\nI\'d love to see CF become free, btw.  I think the number of users would go up and the community would grow.  If anything a free license to run on a server for non-commerical endeavors.  I want this from Adobe, not Dragon.',0,'1','','',0,0),(596,213,'Mark Phillips','mark@vertabase.com','http://www.vertabase.com/','','2008-05-20 00:19:23','2008-05-20 00:19:23','If you can now embed videos in PDF with InDesign and edit video in Photoshop I gotta believe Adobe is going to put some video capabilities into CF. ',0,'1','','',0,0),(597,213,'Steve \'Cutter\' Blades','no.junk@cutterscrossing.com','http://blog.cutterscrossing.com','','2008-06-04 23:54:11','2008-06-04 23:54:11','But would they though? Would they add audio/video manipulation into CF? I don\'t think so. They already have Flash video server, which has a pretty interesting (and lucrative for them) licensing model, the last time I checked. Would they water down their own market by putting in a low level equivalent? And it would have to be low level, very low, because it does chew up a ton of processor to buffer and encode video. Would it be cool? A valid \'next step\'? Sure it would. But I think it would be better to provide a better licensing model on FMS, and nice hooks from CF, with tunnels to \'push\' the encoding request to another machine hosting the FMS.\n\nCan I see them doing it? Well, PDF generation chews up major processor power now, so anything can happen, I guess.',0,'1','','',0,0),(598,214,'Janet','womengeeks@yahoo.com','http://www.womengeeks.com','','2008-05-29 05:09:40','2008-05-29 05:09:40','Thanks for posting the download of your presentation, I thought it was pretty good and made some great points!',0,'1','','',0,0),(599,214,'Scott','humantorch@gmail.com','','','2008-06-24 15:52:47','2008-06-24 15:52:47','Perfect! This is EXACTLY the kind of resource I\'ve been looking for all day. I\'m pretty experienced in web development but new to AIR, and some of the idiosyncrasies of the platform were kicking my ass. Muchly appreciated!',0,'1','','',0,0),(600,214,'goonie','selalujujur@gmail.com','http://www.applerepo.com','','2008-07-09 22:01:58','2008-07-09 22:01:58','Thanks Ryan, Downloading the Zip files now, and will watch your presentation :)\n\nGoonie',0,'1','','',0,0),(601,214,'pierre','pierrechaigneau@yahoo.FR','','','2008-08-25 11:21:29','2008-08-25 11:21:29','Hello,\n\nThanks for yours sliders. Base on the scripts from Adobe. I trying to update the database, from few days, but the action don\'t work can you help me please\n\nThe script is : http://www.flexx.fr/forum/viewtopic.php?p=2411\n\nThank for your help\n\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(602,214,'ghd','ghds@gmail.com','http://www.ghds.me','','2009-12-05 23:48:21','2009-12-05 23:48:21','Its very critical to know youre buying the real thing that the  GHD hair straightener is safe. With so many companies selling the GHD IV, how do you know if youre buying an authentic item?\n  I believe that it should  f ollow these  steps to authenticate your GHD straightener:- Buy from a respected retailer  Products sold from overseas or auction sites are frequently counterfeit. There is no accountability and these companies or individuals do not need to answer to Trading Standards. Buy GHD hair straighteners only from a reputable merchant located in your home country.Off course,you must assure the GHD which is producted the factories  have  a quality assurance.',0,'1','','',0,0),(603,214,'Seostuckmaher','seotools@mail15.com','http://web-promotion-services.net','','2010-08-15 20:12:41','2010-08-15 20:12:41','When you need to improve  web site, you can find many offers from everywhere, but you have to know, that   there is one seo tool, that automati