an whose custom license plate was:\n\"HOK P2E\". ',0,'1','','',0,0),(635,225,'marc esher','marc.esher@gmail.com','http://mxunit.org','','2008-09-17 07:24:02','2008-09-17 07:24:02','that\'s awesome! Funny because when i saw that last night i thought of you, too.\n\nnow, i did hear that whenever a stogie is smoked in San Francisco, a hippie turns republican. But I\'m willing to take that risk.\n\nSee you there!',0,'1','','',0,0),(636,225,'Brian Rinaldi','brian.rinaldi@gmail.com','http://www.remotesynthesis.com','','2008-09-17 08:03:20','2008-09-17 08:03:20','I commented that I would attend but I was only the second commenter. I suspect we might need more.',0,'1','','',0,0),(637,225,'Kevin Hoyt','khoyt@adobe.com','http://blog.kevinhoyt.org','','2008-09-18 00:29:21','2008-09-18 00:29:21','Terrence, thanks for posting!  And thanks to those who\'ve come on over to let me know that they\'re interested!\n\nBetween those that have commented, and those that have expressed interested to me in person, I suspect that we\'re around 15 - 20 strong thus far.  That\'s a good momentum.  There\'s still a few weeks before MAX (wink), so we\'ll see what happens.\n\nThanks again!\nKevin',0,'1','','',0,0),(638,226,'Jerry','jerry.loggins@yahoo.com','http://jerryloggins.com/','','2008-09-20 20:55:59','2008-09-20 20:55:59','Thanks for this post - I\'ll be checking out that website.  The country is in a horrible mess!  Very scary time for us all.',0,'1','','',0,0),(639,226,'Andrea','apspencer28@yahoo.com','','','2008-09-26 11:45:18','2008-09-26 11:45:18','I am beginning to agree that this bailout is not good for reasons other than the obvious fact that the bill for this hefty bailout will be mailed to \"We the People,\" but also because of my skepticism of the rush to pass it. These problems did not happen overnight. So why are we in such a rush to fix them in 24 hours. Take the damn time to find the best solution. Yes, I believe that the government should act expeditously. We certainly don\'t want Congress to drag this process out like it does every decision that is placed on the table. But, when we are talking about this much money, which will mammoth the deficit even further, we need to think about the best interest of the people. All people. Not just the rich and these mega corporations! Not just whites, but minorities too.\n\nI am not one to point the finger, but the system that we have been operating under for so many years, is flawed. In my estimation, the root of the problemis racism and classism,designed to separate people into these categories. Why else do you think it is possible for a white person who makes the same income, and whom has the same credit rating as his black counterpart, to get approval for loans that would be denied to his black counterpart. That is why we have so many foreclosures in the vanilla suburbs, because the whites don\'t want to live next door to blacks or other minorities. So, they moved out to the burbs, and we aided by the government and business infrastructure including the banks, who enabled them to do so. They in essence have enabled these old cancers to survive by approving white people for loans that they otherwise would not be eligible for. Thus ensuring de facto segreagtion.\n\nSadly, it is nothing new, but simply more of the racism this country was built upon. To remedy this situation, (yeah right, it hasn\'t happened in 400 years) Americans need to unite, and hold our lawmakers accountable. White, black, red, brown, and yellow, will all suffer because of the green. China and the Middle Eastern countries already own substantial pieces of America in the form of loans, banks,  and companies. If this money were to be called due today, my God. If law makers don\'t make the correct decisions for us, the little man will be left holding the bag, and things will continue to worsen.\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(640,226,'Julie','juliecallaway789@gmail.com','http://juliecallaway.com/','','2008-09-28 16:33:54','2008-09-28 16:33:54','I hope the bailout works!  This is such a scary time - so many people that I know are afraid that their companies are going to fold and they will lose their jobs, and then their houses.  We need help fast!',0,'1','','',0,0),(641,226,'p sarver','jpmagnum@gmail.com','','','2008-09-30 03:18:12','2008-09-30 03:18:12','I can tell you this.I wouldn\'t be voting for Obama come Nov 4th.You really want to kill the economy this man is it.He\'s clueless.\n\nI\'ve listened to his speeches,debates, checked his record,his plans etc\n\nThe man is an empty suit that doesn\'t have an original thought.He just parrots everyone else and tells the middle class he\'s for them.\n\nPelosi has such poor leadership for one that she couldn\'t get her own party on board w/ this and then she so politicized the process you would cut the tension with a knife.\n\nThis wasn\'t the time for partisanship and it was up to her to set the tone.Right now what she cares about is getting Obama elected.\nWhat SOME in the Congress care about is getting re-elected and they didn\'t dare vote  yes.\n\nThere were a few hold outs who know there is a possibility of a better bill if they hold out instead of having one shoved down their throats.\nTime is critical but this is just Congress at its finest.\nObama plans on raising taxes and pushing programs.He\'s trying to keep as far away from Congress as possible so he doesn\'t have to get lined up with anything at all.\nNO spine. He\'ll do anything to get elected so he\'s being real fuzzy about where he stands on this.\nRemember this is the same guy that said folks cling to guns and religion because he thought that was a private conversation.No thanks.\nIf he says one thing to one group of ppl and quite another to another group of ppl who honestly knows what he\'s thinking.\nCan\'t be trusted.I can tell you flat out one thing that won\'t cure this problem.Tax and spend.\nBack later-we\'ll take a look at Freddie Mac and Fannie Mae.Not that it was under-regulated.It was over regulated and created what happened.We\'ll take a look at famous last words of Barney Franks and all the warnings he got(and ignored calling it fear mongering)!\n',0,'1','','',0,0),(642,228,'Karen Leary','learyk@wharton.upenn.edu','','','2008-09-25 11:26:30','2008-09-25 11:26:30','I\'d be really interested in you showing off the inner workings at our developer\'s hangout next week.',0,'1','','',0,0),(643,229,'Eric','ecobb@ecartech.com','','','2008-09-29 14:24:25','2008-09-29 14:24:25','I just found Squidhead last week, and I gotta tell ya I\'m lovin\' it!  I haven\'t had a chance to go through it like I want to, but what I have seen so far rocks!\n\nThanks for all of your hard work and effort on this project, and I can\'t wait to see what you guys have coming down the pipes!',0,'1','','',0,0),(644,229,'Kaitlyn','kaitlynmackenzie625@gmail.com','http://www.kaitlynmackenzie.com/','','2008-09-29 20:19:10','2008-09-29 20:19:10','Am looking forward to see what your new \"chefs\" can contribute to Squidhead!  Good luck!',0,'1','','',0,0),(645,230,'Abby','abby_rants@yahoo.com','http://abbyvanburen.com/','','2008-11-01 00:34:45','2008-11-01 00:34:45','My friends were talking about Unfuddle recently so I gave it a look. I like the dashboard - I\'m a fan of everything at a glance. We\'ll probably give it a try after this end of year wrap up and reporting. Thanks.',0,'1','','',0,0),(646,231,'Hector Arment','harment@hotmail.com','','','2009-10-20 16:30:36','2009-10-20 16:30:36','Great post. Save me lots of time and trouble. Thanks',0,'1','','',0,0),(647,231,'Diego Arias','dak.col@gmail.com','','','2010-03-11 17:17:29','2010-03-11 17:17:29','Hi:\n\nthank you for the info i was looking why my NLB didnt work on 2008 but ok on 2003',0,'1','','',0,0),(648,232,'Tariq Ahmed','tariq@dopejam.com','http://www.dopejam.com','','2008-11-25 14:08:53','2008-11-25 14:08:53','Hey Terrance!\n\nI think I spotted you at Max - was going to say hi, but lost you in the vast sea of attendees. :)',0,'1','','',0,0),(649,233,'Jim Priest','priest@thecrumb.com','http://www.thecrumb.com','','2008-11-25 09:01:04','2008-11-25 09:01:04','Awesome job!!!\n\nPaging Ben Forta for prime example of proper use of ColdFusion... :)',0,'1','','',0,0),(650,233,'Terrence Ryan','terry@terrenceryan.com','http://www.terrenceryan.com','','2008-11-25 10:20:12','2008-11-25 10:20:12','Thanks, Jim.',0,'1','','',0,0),(651,236,'Steve Rittler','srittler@countermarch.com','','','2008-11-16 21:38:56','2008-11-16 21:38:56','Higher ed is just starting to get on the CRM bandwagon.  Lots of commercial vendors running in to the space, but the vast majority of them don\'t grasp the complexities of the higher ed environment.\n\nKey differences:\n* scope - running a college is like running a small city\n* terminology (simple fix in some respects)\n* roles and relationships - very complex\n* even slower to change (you know that already)\n* customer lifecycle really is just about a lifetime\n* more reluctance to trust offsite vendors\n\nThere are more, but it\'s late ;-)\n\nSo they try...shipping a rebranded, relabeled commercial product and bash the square peg in to a round hole.  Then there are other vendors who are aggressively targeting the space with a really flexible and/or designed-for-higher-education solution.  No surprise that Salesforce is trying to make inroads here.',0,'1','','',0,0),(652,236,'Brian Swartzfager','bcswartz@umd.edu','http://www.swartzfager.org/blog','','2008-11-17 12:14:23','2008-11-17 12:14:23','I second Steve\'s comments.  The previous two attempts by our central university IT department to take commercial CRM products and retrofit them to our computing environment ended in failure.  Attempt #3 just started but it sounds like they kept the tinkering to a minimum this time, so maybe it\'ll turn out better.\n\nStill, the idea of Salesforce targeting the education sector is an interesting one.',0,'1','','',0,0),(653,239,'brian','brian.mccairn@medicapp.com','','','2009-07-13 15:34:30','2009-07-13 15:34:30','Hi - enjoyed the CF9 preso.\n\nI\'m looking into a really simple failover scenario with NLB with single standalone CF8 instances on 2 machines in an NLB cluster. I don\'t fully understand though how NLB determines if CF is unresponsive.\n\nIs it just checking if the server is alive? Or can it detect if CF iteself is unresponsive even if the server is still up?',0,'1','','',0,0),(654,241,'Joshua Curtiss','jc@joshandamanda.com','http://blog.crankybit.com','','2008-12-16 12:04:30','2008-12-16 12:04:30','Perfect. This is perfect timing. I needed this for a Transfer decorator using onMissingMethod(), and it works great. Thanks!!!',0,'1','','',0,0),(655,241,'Ben Nadel','ben@bennadel.com','http://www.bennadel.com','','2008-11-25 10:12:21','2008-11-25 10:12:21','Looks good. I wish that we could do something like this:\n\nvariables[ functionName ]();\n\nThis works at a \"functional\" level (as it is what you are essentially doing); but, this fails to compile due to parsing issues.',0,'1','','',0,0),(656,241,'Terrence Ryan','terry@terrenceryan.com','http://www.terrenceryan.com','','2008-11-25 10:17:10','2008-11-25 10:17:10','I agree, Ben, as that method would also work with method calls on other objects too.',0,'1','','',0,0),(657,241,'Sean Corfield','seancorfield@gmail.com','http://corfield.org/','','2008-11-25 10:37:27','2008-11-25 10:37:27','I think you\'ll find that if you do this with CFC methods, the called function doesn\'t correctly bind to VARIABLES or THIS scope...',0,'1','','',0,0),(658,241,'Henry Ho','henryho167@gmail.com','http://henrylearnstorock.blogspot.com/','','2008-11-25 11:23:39','2008-11-25 11:23:39','@Sean, so this method doesn\'t really work for calling CFC methods?',0,'1','','',0,0),(659,241,'Terrence Ryan','terry@terrenceryan.com','http://www.terrenceryan.com','','2008-11-25 11:24:45','2008-11-25 11:24:45','Do you mean intra-cfc or external to that CFC?\n\nI know it doesn\'t work externally.  but it does work intra-cfc. I assume as the variables and this scope are same for the dynamic call.',0,'1','','',0,0),(660,241,'Mark Mandel','mark@compoundtheory.com','http://www.compoundtheory.com','','2008-11-25 13:17:09','2008-11-25 13:17:09','@Terrence, yeah, you are fine intra-cfc. I do this all the time when I don\'t want to escape out of a cfscript block to use cfinvoke.\n\nEither that or when I pass a function to a function, as otherwise, for some reason cf throws a wobbly if you try and call arguments.foo(argumentCollection=args);',0,'1','','',0,0),(661,241,'Aaron Neff','coldfusion-rocks@itisdesign.com','http://itisdesign.com','','2010-01-06 02:29:47','2010-01-06 02:29:47','\"variables[functionName]();\"\n\n+1',0,'1','','',0,0),(662,241,'Chris Weller','wellercs@gmail.com','','','2011-08-09 11:38:45','2011-08-09 11:38:45','It appears I\'m late to the party on this one, but I have several methods in a CFC for saving form data. I was trying to create a single action page to call these save functions, but do so dynamically similar to what you\'ve done here. I just used cfinvoke method=\"#functionName#\". Is there a drawback to doing it this way with cfinvoke?  Thanks for the great example!',0,'1','','',0,0),(663,241,'delijah','raffael.wannenmacher@gmail.com','','','2011-04-05 08:05:36','2011-04-05 08:05:36','Does not work on persistent objects :(',0,'1','','',0,0),(664,242,'Dan Lancelot','danlance@gmail.com','http://www.danlance.co.uk','','2008-12-10 10:05:43','2008-12-10 10:05:43','Alternatively, use the  Team > Copy To command on the folder context menu...\n\nSee comments on http://www.danlance.co.uk/index.cfm/2007/8/17/Do-not-copy-SVN-working-folders-to-another-location-in-project for more info...\n\nI first came across this issue with Subclipse, but the same applies to Subversive...',0,'1','','',0,0),(665,242,'Terrence Ryan','terry@terrenceryan.com','http://www.terrenceryan.com','','2008-12-10 19:13:23','2008-12-10 19:13:23','Thanks Dan, that\'s a great alternative.',0,'1','','',0,0),(666,242,'Sean Corfield','seancorfield@gmail.com','http://corfield.org/','','2009-01-04 15:25:17','2009-01-04 15:25:17','I tend to export directly from SVN to the new tree when I want to copy version controlled files - so Dan\'s hint is a useful one that will make my life easier! :)',0,'1','','',0,0),(667,242,'Daniel Felix Ferber','dff4321@gmail.com','','','2010-07-27 16:42:56','2010-07-27 16:42:56','This looks like a reasonable explanation. But I dont think this is an acceptable situation. The worst on this issue is that Java refactor like package rename or class move always breaks the SVN data structure. Older versions of Subeclipse did not suffer on this. That was the great fun of Eclipse+SVN: You had liberty to move/copy files anywhere anytime. Current Subversive is a long step backwards to times of CVS.',0,'1','','',0,0),(668,242,'Bob Chesley','bob.chesley@nhsoftwerks.com','http://www.nhsoftwerks.com','','2010-08-05 15:30:40','2010-08-05 15:30:40','Just bumped into this one as well using ColdFusion Builder.  Thanks for the heads up - should have known better.',0,'1','','',0,0),(669,242,'juneskirt223','emilystart387@hotmail.com','http://www.promdressesol.ca','','2010-08-17 04:31:42','2010-08-17 04:31:42','Nice article.I cant believe I missed this blog for so long. Its just great stuff all round.I cant wait to read what you\'ve got next. I love everything that youre saying and want more, more, MORE! Keep this up, man! Its just too good.',0,'1','','',0,0),(670,242,'Ray','raysjunkmail@gmail.com','','','2010-07-21 09:58:28','2010-07-21 09:58:28','Not sure if this will help anyone but I\'m using Eclipse Helios with the Subversive plug and came upon this site while trying to find out what the red exclamation point at my project root was indicating. This explanation seemed to have merit, but I later found that the cause of the red exclamation point in my case was actually a missing jar that was referenced in the projects build path. Happy hunting :)',0,'1','','',0,0),(671,242,'Chris','chrislott@maultech.com','','','2011-06-01 08:58:16','2011-06-01 08:58:16','Me too.  Yesterday Subversive bit me rather badly when I used the Eclipse refactoring operation move to move a folder from a SVN project to a non-SVN project. It completely did the wrong thing; failed to execute the proper SVN command to delete the folder from the controlled workspace, and preserved the .svn subfolders in the copy it dropped in the non-controlled workspace. For the record I am using Eclipse Helios SR2 with Subversive 0.7.9.I20110207-1700. Sure the advice about not moving folders is sound, but this is adapting user behavior to buggy code, ugh.  At the very least Subversive could put up a gosh-darned dialog to say \"Hey buddy this operation will break your workspace do you really want to continue\"?  At this point I think the Eclipse project should revoke the incubation status and set it back to raw. Does anyone know if Subclipse suffers from the same problems??',0,'1','','',0,0),(672,243,'Sam Farmer','sam@samfarmer.com','http://samfarmer.com','','2008-12-16 14:51:51','2008-12-16 14:51:51','Do you use the other Unfuddle features like Projects, etc?  And, if so, and I know your a basecamp fan, is the Unfuddle stuff better or worse than Basecamp?',0,'1','','',0,0),(673,243,'Terrence Ryan','terry@terrenceryan.com','http://www.terrenceryan.com','','2008-12-16 18:09:30','2008-12-16 18:09:30','We do use them to various degrees.\n\nI would say that the project management features of Unfuddle are different from Basecamp.  Basecamp is more about communicating with clients.  Unfuddle is more about communicating intra-organization, and specifically developers.\n\nSo I use both, but for very different reasons.',0,'1','','',0,0),(674,243,'Sam Farmer','sam@samfarmer.com','http://samfarmer.com','','2008-12-17 06:24:05','2008-12-17 06:24:05','Cool.  Thanks.',0,'1','','',0,0),(675,244,'Ken Olofsen','ken@atlassian.com','http://www.atlassian.com/software/crucible/','','2009-01-05 13:54:12','2009-01-05 13:54:12','Great post!\n\nI\'m with Atlassian, makers of &lt;a href=http://www.atlassian.com/software/crucible/&gt;Crucible&lt;/a&gt;.  Automated tools make a great compliment to the code review process, but cannot take the place of second pair of eyes interpreting what it is your code is trying to say..',0,'1','','',0,0),(676,245,'Tim Allen','flipper@peregrinesalon.com','http://www.peregrinesalon.com/','','2008-12-31 07:54:58','2008-12-31 07:54:58','That\'s a spot-on take on technology purchases. For several years, I\'ve heard quite a few younger developers proclaim that hardware is cheap, so effeciency should take a back seat to other concerns when writing code. Granted, code portability, accessibility, and efficiency are often at odds with one another, but it feels to me that efficiency has been taking a back seat lately, due to Moore\'s law and the ever decreasing price of hardware. Throwing a new, shiny piece of hardware at a problem has been considered an acceptable solution, and one I abhor.\n\nI\'m going to say that efficiencies in code are going to be making a come back. Saving valuable system resources and CPU cycles wherever you can all adds up when it comes to trying to scale your application properly.\n\nI\'d love to see you do a more in-depth entry on what is coming in Centaur. As a relative CF noob, I\'ve been impressed with how the language has evolved since I last used it early this century!\n\nRegards,\n\n-Tim',0,'1','','',0,0),(677,245,'Kevin Hoyt','khoyt@adobe.com','http://blog.kevinhoyt.org','','2008-12-31 12:16:07','2008-12-31 12:16:07','What?  No predictions for technology in higher ed?  ;-)',0,'1','','',0,0),(678,245,'David Maggard','david@ddkdevelopment.com','','','2009-01-01 11:22:10','2009-01-01 11:22:10','Tim:\n\nMy opinion has always been that if the cost for additional hardware to match performance is cheaper than the cost of additional programming time to improve natural performance then hardware is an acceptable solution. But quite frankly in my experience if code is written with an eye towards performance to begin with the additional time is minimal, and additional hardware cost, especially if the app needs to scale is often times $1000\'s more over the life of an app, and poor performance can cost even more.',0,'1','','',0,0),(679,245,'Steve \'Cutter\' Blades','no.junk@cutterscrossing.com','http://blog.cutterscrossing.com','','2009-01-02 09:36:11','2009-01-02 09:36:11','Terry,\n\nNice. I look forward to seeing how spot on you are. Your corporate spending prediction hits home with me:\n\nhttp://blog.cutterscrossing.com/index.cfm/2008/6/22/Build-Applications-That-Scale\n\nI\'ll add one to your list though: expect a much higher rate of malicious web-based attacks, on both conventional and mobile platforms, propogated by organized crime and targeting identity theft. Keyloggers, Phishing attacks, etc will become much more sneaky and sophisticated. Big business will be in credit monitoring. Far more so than in the past.',0,'1','','',0,0),(680,245,'Gerald Guido','Gerald.Guido@gmail.com','http://www.myinternetisbroken.com/','','2009-01-09 11:09:46','2009-01-09 11:09:46','I am psyched about bolt and Hibernate. Like yourself I am a big fan of code generation/automation. From what I have gathered from the blog posts and quips I have &quot;over heard&quot; I am guessing that the Bolt and Hibernate combo will be a productivity monster.\n\nTho only other thing I would have added to that is Railo 3.1 will make great strides as well seeing that will have Hibernate/ORM support. That and I think we will see a higher degree of CF runtime interoperability as a result of the CFML advisory board.',0,'1','','',0,0),(681,246,'Scott P','scott@scottpinkston.org','http://www.scottpinkston.org/blog','','2009-01-01 15:00:48','2009-01-01 15:00:48','My perception is that over the past few years there has been a shift  towards hosted services in IHE, especially at smaller institutions.  We (smaller institutions) have to seriously look at them because the expectations  from this facebook/myspace/youtube generation.  We don\'t have the staff or time to build everything internally not to mention the sysadmin functions of maintaining systems.\n\n2009 and beyond is going to be an interesting time in higher ed.',0,'1','','',0,0),(682,247,'Rob Brooks-Bilson','rbils@amkor.com','http://www.brooks-bilson.com/blogs/rob/','','2009-01-08 11:31:40','2009-01-08 11:31:40','Terry,\n\nThanks for sharing. I\'ll be filing this one away for later.\n\nOh, and you are truly a master at spreading rumors!',0,'1','','',0,0),(683,247,'Chris Diller','cdiller@nvisagemedia.com','','','2009-01-08 12:10:38','2009-01-08 12:10:38','I always had my suspicions about Mark...',0,'1','','',0,0),(684,247,'Dave Konopka','dave.konopka@gmail.com','http://imakewebjunk.com','','2009-01-08 12:41:52','2009-01-08 12:41:52','Very nice solution. Who knew Apache could talk with the dead? Maybe only you and the marsupials.',0,'1','','',0,0),(685,247,'Sami Hoda','sami@bytestopshere.com','http://www.bytestopshere.com','','2009-01-08 14:25:57','2009-01-08 14:25:57','This should go on RiaForge!',0,'1','','',0,0),(686,247,'Terrence Ryan','terry@terrenceryan.com','http://terrenceryan.com','','2009-01-08 14:30:38','2009-01-08 14:30:38','@Sami, I kinda rushed it out as a response to CF is dead nonsense today.  I might give that a try, but I\'m looking at a swamped next few weeks.\n\nAnyone who wants to steal the code and release on Riaforge can be my guest.',0,'1','','',0,0),(687,247,'pat branley','patrickb@webqem.com','','','2009-01-08 15:38:45','2009-01-08 15:38:45','Hi Guys\nyou can do the same thing on windows with the XMLHTTP COM object.\nyou don\'t need to install anything because its part of the OS.',0,'1','','',0,0),(688,247,'James','james@sparkos.com','http://www.sparkos.com','','2009-02-12 03:34:53','2009-02-12 03:34:53','Talk about perfect timing! Decided I wanted to get my work calendar, which is hosted on an OS X Caldav server, into my Google calendar. Trouble was Google doesn\'t support remote calendars with authentication so I needed a CF proxy in between. This worked a treat, although for some reason I needed to put the port number in the URL string as well as the port attribute.\nMany thanks!',0,'1','','',0,0),(689,247,'Ben Margolis','bmargolis@isitedesign.com','http://www.isitedesign.com','','2009-03-18 11:32:30','2009-03-18 11:32:30','I have to say great timing as well. I\'m just starting to do some API programming with Constant Contact in a ColdFusion page. Make sure you use the &quot;realm&quot; argument with &quot;api.constantcontact.com&quot; as the value. Thanks for the post.',0,'1','','',0,0),(690,247,'Ben Margolis','bmargolis@isitedesign.com','http://www.isitedesign.com','','2009-03-18 15:08:31','2009-03-18 15:08:31','You can do a post also, just copy the get function, replacing &quot;get&quot; with &quot;post&quot; and then:\n\n...\n        &lt;cfargument name=&quot;url&quot; type=&quot;string&quot; required=&quot;TRUE&quot; hint=&quot;The url to call.&quot; /&gt;\n        &lt;cfargument name=&quot;body&quot; type=&quot;string&quot; required=&quot;TRUE&quot; hint=&quot;What to send to the URL&quot; /&gt;\n\n....\n\n            var AuthScope = loader.create(&quot;org.apache.commons.httpclient.auth.AuthScope&quot;);\n            var myStringRequestEntity = loader.create(&quot;org.apache.commons.httpclient.methods.StringRequestEntity&quot;);\n\n....\n\n            httpPost.init(arguments.url);\n            httpPost.setRequestEntity(myStringRequestEntity.init(arguments.body, &quot;application/atom+xml&quot;, &quot;UTF-8&quot;));\n\n....\n\nNOTE: This is for posting an ATOM XML document as a string.',0,'1','','',0,0),(691,247,'.jonah','jonah.terrenceryan@creori.com','','','2009-03-19 04:48:35','2009-03-19 04:48:35','Excellent! I\'m about to need a constant contact API wrapper myself. If it\'s alright w/you, I\'ll use your code as a starting point and release it and the CC api on riaforge once they\'re done.',0,'1','','',0,0),(692,247,'Ben Margolis','ben833@gmail.com','http://www.isitedesign.com','','2009-07-17 15:49:45','2009-07-17 15:49:45','Constant Contact\'s API is switching from Digest Authentication to Basic Authentication over HTTPS. Since you don\'t indicate the authentication type (digest versus basic), it appears there\'s nothing that needs to change in the code. We just need to make sure the URLs have &quot;https&quot; instead of &quot;http.&quot; I\'ll update you if anything changes after I test this strategy out.',0,'1','','',0,0),(693,247,'Ben Margolis','ben833@gmail.com','http://www.isitedesign.com','','2009-08-04 11:02:20','2009-08-04 11:02:20','You need to change default=&quot;80&quot; to default=&quot;443&quot; in order to use https correctly. That, and changing the URL, will do the trick.',0,'1','','',0,0),(694,247,'ColdFusion','martin.parry@beetrootstreet.com','http://www.beetrootstreet.com','','2010-05-27 05:49:45','2010-05-27 05:49:45','This begs the question - WHY don\'t Adobe support NTLM in CFHTTP when the functionality is obviously there by using your method?!?!?!?!  Dumbfounded!\n\nThank for the fix BTW\n\nMartin',0,'1','','',0,0),(695,247,'Steve','steve@fusecast.com','','','2010-10-07 18:55:34','2010-10-07 18:55:34','Terrence,\n\nPlease forgive a rookie question. Can you show me how to implement the code written above? I am new to some of this and I can\'t seem to get it going.\n\nThank you.',0,'1','','',0,0),(696,249,'Nathan Mische','nmische@gmail.com','http://www.mischefamily.com/nathan','','2009-01-15 15:16:22','2009-01-15 15:16:22','You\'ll definitely be missed here, but I wish you the best of luck with whatever you have lined up.',0,'1','','',0,0),(697,249,'Brian Swartzfager','bcswartz@umd.edu','http://www.swartzfager.org/blog','','2009-01-15 15:22:42','2009-01-15 15:22:42','Sounds like you had a great experience at Wharton.  Good luck with your new endeavor/project!',0,'1','','',0,0),(698,249,'Tim Allen','flipper@peregrinesalon.com','http://www.peregrinesalon.com','','2009-01-15 15:33:46','2009-01-15 15:33:46','Good luck moving forward, I\'m sure you\'ll do well it whatever is next. Thanks for the ColdFusion tips on the site!',0,'1','','',0,0),(699,249,'Scott McNulty','smcnulty@gmail.com','http://blog.blankbaby.com/','','2009-01-15 16:23:02','2009-01-15 16:23:02','It looks like I started a trend! Congrats to you, and best of luck in whatever it is you\'ll be doing.\n\nLeaving Wharton is pretty tough (says the guy who leave on Tuesday), so I have an idea of what you went through while making the decision.',0,'1','','',0,0),(700,249,'Kendall Whitehouse','whitehou@wharton.upenn.edu','https://blogs.wharton.upenn.edu/staff/kendallwhitehouse/','','2009-01-15 18:14:21','2009-01-15 18:14:21','All the best, Terry. Somehow I think we\'ll still be working together as you move on to your next gig. See you then!',0,'1','','',0,0),(701,249,'Rachel Lehman','raelehman@gmail.com','','','2009-01-15 18:21:04','2009-01-15 18:21:04','A lot of what you said about your experience at Wharton reminds me of my first professional job - 7 years, 3 positions, and several transitions that didn\'t make it feel like the \'same job\'. But I reached a point where I realized I didn\'t want to be a \'lifer\' at that company, and made the difficult choice to move on. I\'m still good friends with a lot of the people I worked with there, but I never regret leaving because the experiences at new jobs definitely broadened my horizons. So here\'s to those tough decisions, and best of luck with your future endeavor!',0,'1','','',0,0),(702,249,'Dave Konopka','dave.konopka@gmail.com','http://imakewebjunk.com','','2009-01-15 20:09:18','2009-01-15 20:09:18','As my first supervisor at Wharton you brought me into the fold. It\'s been a great experience working for and with you. Congratulations and best of luck on your next move. I know you\'ll make a splash wherever you land.',0,'1','','',0,0),(703,249,'Mike W.','Watsonmj@gmail.com','','','2009-01-15 22:36:17','2009-01-15 22:36:17','Congratulations Terry. I can attest to the fact that you are one of the best at what you do and I am glad you have some exciting opportunities coming your way.  Keep us updated with what is next.',0,'1','','',0,0),(704,249,'Mike W.','Watsonmj@gmail.com','','','2009-01-15 22:36:59','2009-01-15 22:36:59','Congratulations Terry. I can attest to the fact that you are one of the best at what you do and I am glad you have some exciting opportunities coming your way.  Keep us updated with what is next.',0,'1','','',0,0),(705,249,'Tariq Ahmed','tariq@dopejam.com','http://www.amcomtech.net','','2009-01-16 01:03:48','2009-01-16 01:03:48','Hey Terrence! Well I patiently wait for the day you\'ll join us. When you\'re ready for California, let me know. :)',0,'1','','',0,0),(706,249,'Peter Bell','peter@pbell.com','http://www.pbell.com','','2009-01-16 13:25:01','2009-01-16 13:25:01','Hi Terry,\n\nWow, big changes! All the best with your next adventure.',0,'1','','',0,0),(707,250,'Ben Forta','ben@forta.com','http://forta.com/','','2009-01-16 14:55:23','2009-01-16 14:55:23','[Typing quickly so as to be the first to respond]\n\nWelcome aboard Terry, good to be having you join the team!\n\n--- Ben',0,'1','','',0,0),(708,250,'Adam Lehman','adrocknaphobia@gmail.com','http://www.adrocknaphobia.com','','2009-01-16 14:56:31','2009-01-16 14:56:31','Wow. That was fast. Welcome to the party! I\'m super excited we got you on board. I love it when a plan comes together!',0,'1','','',0,0),(709,250,'Kevin Hoyt','khoyt@adobe.com','http://blog.kevinhoyt.org','','2009-01-16 14:56:35','2009-01-16 14:56:35','Super excited to have you on board, Terry!\n\nOh, by the way, when you get an Adobe email address, can you drop me a line?  I\'ve already got a couple of accounts that need your attention (smile).\n\nCongratulations, and welcome,\nKevin',0,'1','','',0,0),(710,250,'Dan Vega','danvega@gmail.com','http://www.danvega.org/blog/','','2009-01-16 15:00:56','2009-01-16 15:00:56','What an amazing opportunity to be a part of a great team! Congratulations to both you and Adobe!',0,'1','','',0,0),(711,250,'Rachel Luxemburg','rlux@adobe.com','','','2009-01-16 15:01:41','2009-01-16 15:01:41','woot!',0,'1','','',0,0),(712,250,'Chris Scott','asstrochris@comcast.net','http://cdscott.blogspot.com','','2009-01-16 15:02:27','2009-01-16 15:02:27','Excellent news! Congratulations man, I hope you have a great career with Adobe!',0,'1','','',0,0),(713,250,'Tim Buntel','buntel@adobe.com','http://www.adobe.com','','2009-01-16 15:03:03','2009-01-16 15:03:03','Absolutely thrilled to have you Terry!',0,'1','','',0,0),(714,250,'Adrian J. Moreno','amoreno@iKnowKungFoo.com','http://www.iknowkungfoo.com','','2009-01-16 15:03:40','2009-01-16 15:03:40','Congratulations Terry!',0,'1','','',0,0),(715,250,'bill shelton','billshelton@comcast.net','http://mxunit.org','','2009-01-16 15:04:42','2009-01-16 15:04:42','Awesome, Terry! Congrats. Great choice by Adobe!\n\nbill',0,'1','','',0,0),(716,250,'Nathan Mische','nmische@gmail.com','http://www.mischefamily.com/nathan','','2009-01-16 15:05:10','2009-01-16 15:05:10','Congrats!',0,'1','','',0,0),(717,250,'Raymond Camden','ray@camdenfamily.com','http://www.coldfusionjedi.com','','2009-01-16 15:05:15','2009-01-16 15:05:15','Congrats Terry!',0,'1','','',0,0),(718,250,'Nick Lansbury','nick.lansbury@gmail.com','http://localhost','','2009-01-16 15:05:31','2009-01-16 15:05:31','Congratulations from England',0,'1','','',0,0),(719,250,'Simon Free','simon@simonfree.com','http://www.simonfree.com','','2009-01-16 15:10:07','2009-01-16 15:10:07','Aweomse news! Congrats!  So we get to bug you to get us the new ColdFusion t-shirt? :-)',0,'1','','',0,0),(720,250,'Ryan Stewart','ryan@adobe.com','http://blog.digitalbackcountry.com','','2009-01-16 15:11:08','2009-01-16 15:11:08','Damn, everyone beat me to it. I was taking a nap.\n\nBut congratulations :)\n\n=Ryan',0,'1','','',0,0),(721,250,'David Siedell','dsiedell@hotmail.com','http://knowledge.wharton.upenn.edu','','2009-01-16 15:11:33','2009-01-16 15:11:33','As your outgoing boss it is appropriate that I am your 13th comment as the unlucky one...Congratulations and the door is always open where ever I am.',0,'1','','',0,0),(722,250,'Rob Brooks-Bilson','rbils@amkor.com','http://www.brooks-bilson.com','','2009-01-16 15:14:49','2009-01-16 15:14:49','Congrats Terry! Adobe\'s lucky to have ya ;-)',0,'1','','',0,0),(723,250,'Sam Farmer','sam@samfarmer.com','http://samfarmer.com','','2009-01-16 15:16:00','2009-01-16 15:16:00','Congrats and great news all round!',0,'1','','',0,0),(724,250,'andy matthews','amatthews@dealerskins.com','http://andymatthews.net','','2009-01-16 15:26:09','2009-01-16 15:26:09','Congratulations dude! That\'s going to be awesome. Where will you be working from?',0,'1','','',0,0),(725,250,'Phil','phil@philduba.com','http://www.philduba.com','','2009-01-16 15:26:52','2009-01-16 15:26:52','Congrats Terry!',0,'1','','',0,0),(726,250,'Brian Swartzfager','bcswartz@umd.edu','http://www.swartzfager.org/blog','','2009-01-16 15:27:03','2009-01-16 15:27:03','Congratulations on the new job!  Since I work in higher ed myself, I\'ll be very interested in seeing what you have planned.',0,'1','','',0,0),(727,250,'John Bliss','bliss.john@gmail.com','','','2009-01-16 15:35:42','2009-01-16 15:35:42','Congratulations on being beamed into the mothership!  :-)',0,'1','','',0,0),(728,250,'marc esher','marc.esher@gmail.com','http://mxunit.org','','2009-01-16 15:45:31','2009-01-16 15:45:31','Excellent -- Congratulations Terry!\n\nCan you send me some stickers?\n\nOr maybe some big fat torpedo cigars (like the kind the kings always smoke in the Disney movies) with Adobe bands on \'em',0,'1','','',0,0),(729,250,'Dan Wilson','sipacate@gmail.com','http://www.nodans.com','','2009-01-16 15:50:28','2009-01-16 15:50:28','Much Congrats!\nI can\'t wait to see the Adobe branded Cigars you\'ll pass around to UGMs and such!\n\n(Are you sure this isn\'t one of your famous rumours?)\n\n\n\nDW',0,'1','','',0,0),(730,250,'Ben Nadel','ben@bennadel.com','http://www.bennadel.com','','2009-01-16 15:51:06','2009-01-16 15:51:06','Dude, that\'s awesome! Congratulations!',0,'1','','',0,0),(731,250,'Steven Erat','talkingtree@gmail.com','http://www.talkingtree.com/blog/','','2009-01-16 16:09:12','2009-01-16 16:09:12','Congratulations on your new role.  I considered myself a steward of the product for quite a time, and I have every confidence that you will succeed in your mission and revitalize ColdFusion in the academic community.  All the best!',0,'1','','',0,0),(732,250,'Joseph Labrecque','Joseph.Labrecque@du.edu','http://inflagrantedelicto.memoryspiral.com/','','2009-01-16 17:03:11','2009-01-16 17:03:11','Congratulations.  Nice to hear the bit about a focus on Higher Ed.  I work and teach for the University of Denver so if you need someone to bounce ideas off of- you are more than welcome!',0,'1','','',0,0),(733,250,'Terrence Ryan','terry@terrenceryan.com','http://terrenceryan.com','','2009-01-16 23:16:19','2009-01-16 23:16:19','Thanks for all the well wishes.\n\n@Adobe folks I can\'t wait to start.',0,'1','','',0,0),(734,250,'Scott Barnes','scbarnes@microsoft.com','http://blogs.msdn.com/msmossyblog','','2009-01-17 02:59:32','2009-01-17 02:59:32','Welcome to the rat race :)\n\n-\nScott Barnes\nMicrosoft.',0,'1','','',0,0),(735,250,'Mark Doherty','mdoherty@adobe.com','http://www.flashmobileblog.com','','2009-01-17 08:09:04','2009-01-17 08:09:04','Welcome to the team!',0,'1','','',0,0),(736,250,'Adam Tuttle','adam@fusiongrokker.com','http://fusiongrokker.com','','2009-01-17 08:09:21','2009-01-17 08:09:21','Congrats on the new job!',0,'1','','',0,0),(737,250,'Brian Rinaldi','brian.rinaldi@gmail.com','http://www.remotesynthesis.com','','2009-01-17 09:57:42','2009-01-17 09:57:42','Congrats man! Adobe is lucky to have you. Steven Erat and I have both worked with the Harvard Extension School which has some curriculum containing ColdFusion...perhaps we can connect you.',0,'1','','',0,0),(738,250,'Megan Stewart','mstewart@adobe.com','','','2009-01-18 23:27:01','2009-01-18 23:27:01','Welcome Terry, woohoo! We\'re so excited to have you join us on the Higher Ed team!',0,'1','','',0,0),(739,250,'Ed Tabara','1smartsolution@gmail.com','http://blog.1smartsolution.com','','2009-01-19 08:12:24','2009-01-19 08:12:24','Awesome news! Congratulations!!!',0,'1','','',0,0),(740,250,'Kristen Schofield','kwebb0814@yahoo.com','http://www.webbschofield.com','','2009-01-19 11:24:13','2009-01-19 11:24:13','I look forward to working with you, Terry. Welcome aboard!!!',0,'1','','',0,0),(741,250,'Mark Phillips','mark@vertabase.com','http://www.vertabase.com','','2009-01-19 17:59:44','2009-01-19 17:59:44','Wow -congratulations.  That is great!',0,'1','','',0,0),(742,250,'Rob Munn','robert.munn@emergentpath.com','http://www.emergentpath.com','','2009-01-23 16:33:05','2009-01-23 16:33:05','Very cool, congrats!',0,'1','','',0,0),(743,250,'Chris Herdt','chris@osric.com','http://osric.com/chris/accidental-developer/','','2009-01-24 08:30:09','2009-01-24 08:30:09','That\'s big news--Congratulations, Terry!',0,'1','','',0,0),(744,250,'Robert M. Hall','rhall@impossibilities.com','http://www.impossibilities.com/','','2009-01-26 19:37:06','2009-01-26 19:37:06','Hey Terry - congratulation - just heard the good news today! Rock on!',0,'1','','',0,0),(745,250,'Charlie Arehart','charlie_lists@carehart.org','http://www.carehart.org','','2009-02-04 13:48:05','2009-02-04 13:48:05','Wow, just heard the news (was teaching last week so under a bit of a rock keeping up on news). That\'s just awesome, and a great thing for Adobe and the CF community.\n\nSo PA now has 3 champions: Steelers for football, Phillies for baseball, and Terry for Adobe. :-)\n\nHope the new role brings you much satisfaction.',0,'1','','',0,0),(746,250,'Josh Adams','joadams@adobe.com','http://blog.joshuaadams.com','','2009-02-18 10:54:25','2009-02-18 10:54:25','Hmm--I should have added a comment earlier; not sure what happened on that. But anyway: welcome aboard, Terry! We\'re thrilled to have ya!',0,'1','','',0,0),(747,250,'PatsySMALL22','karenwalker@mail15.com','http://www.bestfinance-blog.com','','2011-07-21 01:21:02','2011-07-21 01:21:02','That is understandable that money makes people free. But how to act when somebody doesn\'t have money? The only one way is to get the <a href=\"http://bestfinance-blog.com/topics/business-loans\" rel=\"nofollow\">business loans</a> and sba loan.',0,'1','','',0,0),(748,251,'Brian Rinaldi','brian.rinaldi@gmail.com','http://www.remotesynthesis.com','','2009-01-27 13:50:33','2009-01-27 13:50:33','I think you\'ll find that most people are in agreement with you. Nonetheless, its far easier said than done. First of all, getting a Ruby person (to continue your example) to respond to a ColdFusion position opening or even want to necessarily accept said position once they learn it is mostly CF is difficult. Second, having been in on a lot of searches, I think we forget that 90% of developers don\'t study regularly, read blogs, subscribe to journals (I made that number up...but I\'d be willing to bet its not far from true). I would bet that goes for almost any language. To me what makes a good developer great is a curiosity that is lacking in many CF developers (if not in developers in general).\n\nI would argue that some other languages offer more opportunities for continued learning than CF and few places teach it. It\'s even hard to find anyplace running the training regularly in a lot of places. The lousy job market seems to have put a lot of talented people on the market and if you are lucky to have the ability to hire right now, you might find it not so difficult to find great talent at lower rates...but I doubt it is easy still.',0,'1','','',0,0),(749,251,'Andy Sandefer','asandefer@teammis.com','http://www.teammis.com','','2009-01-27 13:52:13','2009-01-27 13:52:13','I think that this is just a symptom of a larger disease, a disease that is actually being treated and getting better - lack of mainstream CF market penetration.  You won\'t find .NETters arguing this point on their blogs because there are tons of them out there in a job market that\'s way bigger than the market for CF developers.\nThere is hope as Adobe seems to be doing what it needs to do to get back in the mainstream game.  For one thing they\'re going after new blood by hiring folks like you to hit colleges and universities to get CF and FLEX out there.\nCleaning up the whole certification process and eradicating some of the misinformation that\'s out there will help too.\nWhat is the CF market share and what is the direction for making it grow?  Are we going to start seeing mainstream advertising for CF in 2009 or is Adobe happy to sell a lot of copies of Enterprise Edition to the same old reliable customer base?\nI\'ve been doing my part.  I\'ve personally gotten CF into 7 new companies in the last 2 years while continuing to provide great (I hope) new CFAJAX solutions to existing clients.',0,'1','','',0,0),(750,251,'Glyn Jackson','glyn.jackson@newebia.co.uk','http://www.newebia.co.uk/blog','','2009-01-27 13:58:04','2009-01-27 13:58:04','my sentiments in a way. I find hiring a developer with OO and design patten experience better. Yes CF is easy to learn but its also very easy to learn &quot;badly&quot;. I am sure any web designer can learn any other language in a short time but its kinda hard to say that any developer will be coding like a pro in months of learning CF. 3+ years and I am still learning new things. I think its only fair to say the learning curve is shorter than perhaps ASP .NET etc but there is much more deeper under that JAVA hood that most companies will need a developer to get to grips with, some concepts that only take practical experience to become proficient.\n\nno another note: JAVA and .NET developers seem to take to CF more easily than PHP, I dont know why thats just been my own experience at work.',0,'1','','',0,0),(751,251,'Steven Erat','talkingtree@gmail.com','http://www.talkingtree.com/blog/about.cfm','','2009-01-27 14:37:16','2009-01-27 14:37:16','I can barely contain myself at the sight of this post, but I\'ll try to stay focused.\n\nAs a long timer with ColdFusion as developer / tech supp / QA for Adobe itself and now looking for employment, I can testify that its a cold out there.  Its an employer\'s market flooded with job seekers.\n\nEmployers are being very picky by splitting hairs about requirements and previous experience.  In a better economy I would imagine that related skill silos would be viewed as easily transferable, but now the prevailing opinion seems to be that they won\'t choose someone who can &quot;grow into it&quot;. In my experience employers want to see that you have done *precisely* the task they are looking to hire.\n\nI\'m fortunate to have had some friends reach out to me, but I haven\'t found a match for my own criteria, but with every week that passes I throw another criterion out.\n\nNow compare today with the dotcom bubble.  I remember when companies were seeking warm bodies anywhere they could find\'em.   I was self trained in some Linux and ColdFusion and had never worked in IT when I landed a job at Allaire nine years ago.\n\nIts a complete reversal today even though I consider myself to qualify as &quot;good people&quot;.  Having a broad skill set is viewed as not being focused, even if those skill sets run deep.',0,'1','','',0,0),(752,251,'Hector Castro','hectcastro@gmail.com','','','2009-01-27 16:23:18','2009-01-27 16:23:18','I agree with your view on hiring quality web developers, but I also agree with a few of Brian\'s points.  ColdFusion appears to be a very high-level language that is easy to learn (relative to other server-side languages), but I do not believe there are many good language X developers that are open to the idea of learning ColdFusion.  In my experience, I typically find quality developers pursuing open languages -- where the cost of setting up a server in the basement is next to nothing.',0,'1','','',0,0),(753,251,'Jeff Porten','pager@jeffporten.com','http://www.jeffporten.com','','2009-01-27 20:08:48','2009-01-27 20:08:48','For what it\'s worth: I had one six-month gig as a ColdFusion developer, in which I was thrown into the deep end of the pool as the sole developer when my manager left two weeks after my arrival. By my own standards, I wouldn\'t have called myself anything higher than &quot;proficient&quot; at the end of my stint, but I was able to ramp up sufficiently quickly to keep my internal and external clients happy throughout.',0,'1','','',0,0),(754,251,'Dav','dstott@theiet.org','','','2009-01-28 10:44:10','2009-01-28 10:44:10','I\'ll sign that. I would much rather hire an expert programmer and get them to pick up a new language rather than spending ages hunting around for somebody who\'s experienced in my particular language or environment. Syntax is just syntax after all, it\'s analytical skills, design patterns, algorithm derivation and willingness to learn that marks a successful developer from the rest of the crowd.',0,'1','','',0,0),(755,251,'Steven Erat','talkingtree@gmail.com','http://www.talkingtree.com/blog/about.cfm','','2009-01-28 10:54:45','2009-01-28 10:54:45','To demonstrate how narrow and rigid employers are being right now, I just received a reply to a letter I wrote to a local startup, where the reply started off &quot;We\'re looking for a Developer, your QA experience is kind of throwing me off track&quot;.\n\nMy experience in QA was developing tests written in the very language being tested, i.e. CF, Flex, and AS3.',0,'1','','',0,0),(756,251,'Terrence Ryan','terry@terrenceryan.com','http://terrenceryan.com','','2009-01-28 14:12:55','2009-01-28 14:12:55','@Steven I guess I\'m saying as someone who has been hiring in the ColdFusion market: Stop being focused on specific skills, start focusing on quality of worker, don\'t be hung up on getting the exact skill set you want, hire the most quality person, and train the rest.',0,'1','','',0,0),(757,251,'Steven Erat','talkingtree@gmail.com','http://www.talkingtree.com/blog/about.cfm','','2009-01-28 14:27:21','2009-01-28 14:27:21','@Terry - I think our wires got crossed somewhere.  I not hiring, but I am seeking employment.   I understand what your saying about being a good web application developer in general, regardless of specific technology, and I\'m trying to say that the employers out there right now don\'t care about that, at least not around here.  They seem to want a precise fit, not a generalist and not someone that\'s really good in a similar technology.   Sorry to derail your blog entry,  but I nearly blew a gasket when I saw the blog title.  :-)',0,'1','','',0,0),(758,251,'Terrence Ryan','terry@terrenceryan.com','http://terrenceryan.com','','2009-01-28 14:44:40','2009-01-28 14:44:40','@Steven I totally understand.',0,'1','','',0,0),(759,251,'John Piotrowski','johnrp@wharton.upenn.edu','','','2009-01-29 16:16:34','2009-01-29 16:16:34','Speaking from personal experience, i support Terry\'s statement.  I was hired into my current CF position with zero experience in CF.  I had graduated from the Univ. of Penn with a Comp Sci degree and had been doing some web application development with C# 1.1 when i had applied.  Luckily, my to be boss was willing to take a chance and provide me with anything that i needed to learn.  It took me about 3 months to convert our enterprise application to CF 7 utilizing the new application cfc architecture and to learn a large percentage of the language.  3+ years later I am still with my employer, still programming in CF and learning something new with CF almost every week, and loving every minute of it. The great thing about CF is that it is really easy to learn and just having a good programming background is really the key when trying to hire someone and if they have CF experience it can only be a bonus.',0,'1','','',0,0),(760,251,'Aaron West','trajik210@gmail.com','http://www.trajiklyhip.com/blog','','2009-01-31 12:50:35','2009-01-31 12:50:35','I couldn\'t agree more Terrence. I\'ve hired every member of the development team at Dealerskins except for two people. One of the best hires on the team was an entry level programmer right out of college. Not only was he incredibly teachable but he had more passion for programming than just about everyone else on the team.\n\nHe was able to learn the basics of ColdFusion in the first few weeks and has now been with Dealerskins for over two years. He has become an incredible asset to my team and our entire organization. We took the time to not look for someone especially interested in ColdFusion, but someone really interested in being part of a great team doing great things.\n\nAttitude and passion are the top two things I look for in candidates. Skill can be honed or taught.',0,'1','','',0,0),(761,251,'janleefran','industry_pro9@yahoo.com','','','2009-02-25 17:13:50','2009-02-25 17:13:50','I am looking for a CF developer for a medium size (adult oriented) project, and stumbled across this blog. I\'d be willing to take on someone who is proficient in another language but would like to learn. We are already working with an expert level cf developer and have more work that he can handle! If there is anyone out there reading this who is interested, please feel free to contact me.\n\nindustry_pro at yahoo dot com',0,'1','','',0,0),(762,251,'Ozzy','oc@thesitestudio.com','http://www.thesitestudio.com','','2011-06-09 15:44:16','2011-06-09 15:44:16','The difference between CF guys and all other developers is that most CF guys do it all - GUI, OOP, SQL, GIS, multi-media, reports, security, administration, you name it we do it. You may find PHP, ASP.NET, JSP guy to do all that but there will be huge variation in their toolset when it comes to anything beyond the actual code. CF guys do most of it in CF, so they all use pretty much the same tools, on any\n platform, so there is less of learning curve from job to job, tighter integration, less training, less money on various tools, etc. So, hiring a non CF developer and expecting them to understand all that ColdFusion offers is not reasonable. Get a CF guy who has an Adobe Certification or somebody with 2 years experience.',0,'1','','',0,0),(763,251,'DeveloperJenny','jmostert@rittal-corp.com','http://rittal-corp.com/company/careers/','','2011-03-30 16:42:23','2011-03-30 16:42:23','I know I\'m 2 years late to the conversation, but we are looking to hire a CF developer. One of our questions is \"Do you have at least 2 years of ColdFusion experience?\". I\'m swamped and would definitely prefer someone that can hit the ground running, but if the right passionate, qualified (in programming in general) came along, we might be willing to entertain them. If you\'re interested, my name should link to our careers page. Apply and put somewhere in your application that you saw this post.\n\nThanks!\nJenny',0,'1','','',0,0),(764,252,'Aaron West','trajik210@gmail.com','http://www.trajiklyhip.com/blog','','2009-01-28 17:27:11','2009-01-28 17:27:11','We\'re looking forward to your talk Terrence!',0,'1','','',0,0),(765,254,'Steve Howard','spammersarescummy@gmail.com','http://stevehoward999.wordpress.com/','','2009-02-01 14:27:32','2009-02-01 14:27:32','Four little letters ... NNTP\n\nFind something as efficient, web based or not, and I don\'t mind trying it out :-) Time for a focus group ...',0,'1','','',0,0),(766,254,'Scott McNulty','smcnulty@gmail.com','http://blog.blankbaby.com','','2009-02-01 14:29:15','2009-02-01 14:29:15','Just to nitpick here, Apple isn\'t a technology, it is a technology company. :)',0,'1','','',0,0),(767,254,'Terrence Ryan','terry@terrenceryan.com','http://terrenceryan.com','','2009-02-01 14:35:39','2009-02-01 14:35:39','I hear you Scott, but I figured, the &quot;It\'s dead&quot;, &quot;It\'s dying&quot; predictions have typically gone after Apple as a whole, and not any one product.\n\nAlthough I thought I did see an uptick in &quot;the IPod is dead&quot; tales.\n\nLong story short, a lot of CF people see CF as the underdog, and I almost never hear Apple fans speaking that way about Apple, despite there being many similarities in their markets.',0,'1','','',0,0),(768,254,'Freelance Web Developer','jules@universeg.com','http://www.webveteran.com/','','2009-02-01 15:24:50','2009-02-01 15:24:50','As soon as you said \'zealotry\' I thought Apple... but as Scott said Apple is not a product.\n\nSo, being that I develop CF apps on a Mac, I guess I am as niche as can be!',0,'1','','',0,0),(769,255,'Rob Brooks-Bilson','rbils@yahoo.com','http://www.brooks-bilson.com','','2009-02-05 18:26:31','2009-02-05 18:26:31','Terry,\n\nThanks for the insights. As a community member, it\'s good to be reminded every now and then just how community driven Adobe is.',0,'1','','',0,0),(770,255,'John Farrar','johnfarrar@sosensible.com','','','2009-02-06 07:47:41','2009-02-06 07:47:41','I know Adobe listens... and in this new communication media driven society it is great to know they hear on given issues. Adobe has told us they are working on getting Flash on the iPhone, even if Apple isn\'t responding. GREAT! Some products didn\'t get upgraded in the CS4 cycle and we would love to know things like Visual Communicator are still being advanced. Any word on that product?',0,'1','','',0,0),(771,255,'Rachel Luxemburg','rlux@adobe.com','http://www.adobe.com','','2009-02-06 19:03:12','2009-02-06 19:03:12','I know the feeling Terry :)',0,'1','','',0,0),(772,255,'Terrence Ryan','terry@terrenceryan.com','http://terrenceryan.com','','2009-02-07 07:51:37','2009-02-07 07:51:37','@John I\'m still getting up to speed, and Visual Communicator is in another wing of Adobe, so I\'m having trouble figuring just who to ask to get that answered for you.  As soon as I have an answer for you, I\'ll let you know.',0,'1','','',0,0),(773,257,'Raymond Camden','ray@camdenfamily.com','http://www.coldfusionbloggers.org','','2009-02-09 11:19:48','2009-02-09 11:19:48','I\'m a bit biased, but I\'d also add ColdFusionBloggers to the last list: http://www.coldfusionbloggers.org\n\nFor folks who don\'t know, it is a blog aggregator, like AXNA, but just for CF blogs.\n\nAlso, do you think it makes sense to mention RIAForge? It would be a good place to download and play with a lot of sample code.',0,'1','','',0,0),(774,257,'John Farrar','johnfarrar@sosensible.com','','','2009-02-09 12:24:03','2009-02-09 12:24:03','Well there is also my ColdFusion book here or at Amazon.\n\nhttp://www.packtpub.com/coldfusion-8-developer-tutorial/book',0,'1','','',0,0),(775,257,'Daniel Sellers','daniel@designfrontier.net','http://www.designfrontier.net','','2009-02-09 12:32:25','2009-02-09 12:32:25','I have to second Ray\'s http://www.coldfusionbloggers.org  Great way to stay on top of things and to learn new things.',0,'1','','',0,0),(776,257,'Terrence Ryan','terry@terrenceryan.com','http://terrenceryan.com','','2009-02-09 13:37:20','2009-02-09 13:37:20','Thanks guys for the feedback.  I have edited the post accordingly.',0,'1','','',0,0),(777,257,'OS-FTW','jones911@gmail.com','','','2009-02-09 17:41:48','2009-02-09 17:41:48','Don\'t forget the 2 open source ( free ) CFML engines:\nOpen BlueDraon:  http://www.openbluedragon.org/  and\nRailo:  http://www.railo-technologies.com/',0,'1','','',0,0),(778,257,'Jeff Porten','pager@jeffporten.com','http://www.jeffporten.com','','2009-02-09 21:52:12','2009-02-09 21:52:12','Terry -- as an IT developer with a passing interest in CF, I appreciate having this primer for putting it back into my quiver of useful tools. But I have two unanswered questions which I\'ll ask you to cover in future posts:\n\n1) I currently have a half-dozen tools I use regularly, and my heuristic for adding a new tool (and taking on that learning curve) is &quot;does this blow the doors off my existing toolset for problem X which I\'m considering?&quot; So from my perspective, a good evangelization tactic would be learning specific scenarios where you think CF blows the doors off.\n\n2) The link you posted to the trial server takes me into the &quot;register with Adobe&quot; firewall before I get more information. Without the &quot;doors blown off&quot; example, I\'m not yet interested enough to take more than 10 seconds answering the question of whether I can run a dev server on my MacBook. (Call me lazy, or call me a stereotypical potential customer.) So a future post with details would be useful: on an Intel MacBook running Apache, am I virtualizing another OS to do this? Or is there a less invasive option?',0,'1','','',0,0),(779,257,'Henry Ho','henryho167@gmail.com','http://henrylearnstorock.blogspot.com','','2009-02-10 16:25:54','2009-02-10 16:25:54','How can you miss UGTV? :)\nhttp://www.carehart.org/ugtv/',0,'1','','',0,0),(780,257,'Terrence Ryan','terry@terrenceryan.com','http://terrenceryan.com','','2009-02-10 20:43:04','2009-02-10 20:43:04','@Henry Video presentations have been added. Good catch!',0,'1','','',0,0),(781,258,'Sarah','dzone_db@yahoo.com','http://grillsblog.com','','2009-04-02 09:24:11','2009-04-02 09:24:11','I recently came across your blog and have been reading along. I thought I would leave my first comment. I don\'t know what to say except that I have enjoyed reading. Nice blog. I will keep visiting this blog very often.\n\nSarah\n\nhttp://grillsblog.com',0,'1','','',0,0),(782,260,'Sam Farmer','sam@samfarmer.com','http://samfarmer.com','','2009-02-10 17:16:53','2009-02-10 17:16:53','Nice entry.  I touched upon some similar themes with this 10 CF One-Liners post:\nhttp://samfarmer.instantspot.com/blog/2007/8/1/Ten-ColdFusion-8-OneLiners',0,'1','','',0,0),(783,260,'Terrence Ryan','terry@terrenceryan.com','http://terrenceryan.com','','2009-02-10 21:15:52','2009-02-10 21:15:52','Thanks Sam, I hope I didn\'t steal anything inadvertently.',0,'1','','',0,0),(784,260,'Sam Farmer','sam@samfarmer.com','http://samfarmer.com','','2009-02-10 21:49:48','2009-02-10 21:49:48','@Terry: Oh, not at all.  Just wanted to post more examples of the power of the CF! :)',0,'1','','',0,0),(785,260,'Kevin Hoyt','khoyt@adobe.com','http://blog.kevinhoyt.org','','2009-02-10 22:58:00','2009-02-10 22:58:00','Nice work, Terry!\n\nPerhaps we should have a web site \"makeshiteasy.com\" where there\'s just a gazillion crazy examples of how it just ain\'t easier than with CF.  My personal favorite is the oft forgotten query of queries, but I dig your .NET to Java in two lines too.\n\nKevin',0,'1','','',0,0),(786,260,'Steven Erat','talkingtree@gmail.com','http://www.talkingtree.com/blog/about.cfm','','2009-02-11 13:14:39','2009-02-11 13:14:39','Great to see so many ColdFusion blog entries this week!\n\nHere\'s my homage to how ColdFusion makes hard things easy:\nhttp://farm2.static.flickr.com/1205/1462403613_3a8338e429_o.jpg',0,'1','','',0,0),(787,261,'SanjayM','modis@wharton.upenn.edu','','','2009-02-11 11:45:09','2009-02-11 11:45:09','Very cool post Terry. it\'s nice to be reminded or refreshed on things that we forget about Cf. Keep \'em coming.',0,'1','','',0,0),(788,261,'Dan Laughland','daniel@laughland.com','http://www.jabberwikaba.com','','2009-02-11 13:08:40','2009-02-11 13:08:40','This sounds a lot like LINQ, the relatively new query language in .NET. Do you know how that compares to ColdFusion\'s query abilities?',0,'1','','',0,0),(789,261,'andy matthews','amatthews@dealerskins.com','http://andymatthews.net','','2009-02-11 13:27:38','2009-02-11 13:27:38','Great post.\n\nJust an FYI about joining (unions) between two different RDBMS. I just asked our senior DBA here and he said that you can connect two RDBMS together, as long as you\'ve got the names and paths and permissions correct.',0,'1','','',0,0),(790,261,'Daniel Sellers','daniel@designfrontier.net','http://www.designfrontier.net','','2009-02-11 14:51:40','2009-02-11 14:51:40','Have to watch those joins in QoQs. You cannot do INNER or OUTER joins in the same way you do in SQL on the server side. Those kinda of joins must be done in the WHERE clause.\n\nFor Instance:\n\nSELECT name, zip\nFROM users INNER JOIN address ON users.id = address.userid\n\nwill work fine as an SQL query but fails as a QoQ.\n\nSELECT name, zip\nFROM users, address\nWHERE users.id = address.userid\n\nbeing the QoQ equivalent.\n\nI forget this every couple of months and have to go look it up in the CF docs. You also left off the ability to create new query objects from scratch with the query functions.',0,'1','','',0,0),(791,261,'Terrence Ryan','terry@terrenceryan.com','http://terrenceryan.com','','2009-02-11 16:03:46','2009-02-11 16:03:46','@Dan I haven\'t done an in depth look.  What strikes me as different, and IMHO better about CF is that LINQ (Language-Integrated Query) is a language for dealing with database queries. On the other hand ColdFusion allows you to punch a hole in it\'s syntax to write in SQL, the language you already use for queries (for better or worse.)\nNow, I caution that I only have a superficial overview of LINQ and if someone who has a better understanding wants to disagree with me, feel free.',0,'1','','',0,0),(792,261,'Magnus Thyvold','magnus@vcn.bc.ca','http://www.earshot-online.com','','2009-02-11 19:06:19','2009-02-11 19:06:19','You didn\'t mention the great ease with which one can work with grouped data. This comes up a lot where you have one master record related to several records in another table in a one to many relationship. cfquery or cfloop makes it very very easy to output without repeating data common to multiple rows and therefore gives you a lot of control over the presentation of your data. Faced with a similar situation in PHP, I searched high and low to find out how to do it and was told basically that you can\'t. (You can but it is quite complicated). The &quot;easy&quot; PHP solution was to query one table, loop over it to output the row AND query the other table to get rows matching the current row from the first table and output that in a nested loop(ie, another query for each row in the first query. The result is dozens or even hundreds(or more) database hits instead of just oned needed by CF.\nYou can even group on parts of field data such as date parts. I once took a year\'s worth of data and was able to create nice neat presentation of it by grouping on the Year, then the Month, then the Week, then created links of each item and then (getting carried away a bit) put the components of each item in a tool tip. Even as a novice CF programmer it was easy. It\'s like magic.',0,'1','','',0,0),(793,261,'Jeff Porten','pager@jeffporten.com','http://www.jeffporten.com','','2009-02-11 22:57:17','2009-02-11 22:57:17','Okay, so some light is beginning to dawn. Most of the tools I use are best at working with internal databases which are meant to replace legacy systems. What you\'re describing here is a middleware tool when the databases continue to exist elsewhere, yes? I\'ve been using Lasso for such things, and you can count the number of times I\'ve done so by reviewing the bloody headprints on the wall. So please keep up the tutorial.',0,'1','','',0,0),(794,261,'Daniel Sellers','daniel@designfrontier.net','http://www.designfrontier.net','','2009-02-12 13:33:38','2009-02-12 13:33:38','@Terrence\nI agree wholeheartedly about the power and ease that using actual SQL syntax in internal queries provides. I use this more and more often lately. It really is a fantastically useful feature in CF.\n\nI do wish normal join syntax was supported but either way this allows for some very powerful data manipulation with fewer SQL server calls.',0,'1','','',0,0),(795,263,'Raymond Camden','ray@camdenfamily.com','http://www.coldfusionbloggers.org','','2009-02-12 12:01:57','2009-02-12 12:01:57','I\'d maybe also bring up cffeed as another way CF plays with others. You may also want to list cfinvoke next to cfhttp for running web services.',0,'1','','',0,0),(796,263,'Nathan Strutz','strutz@gmail.com','http://www.dopefly.com/','','2009-02-12 12:06:03','2009-02-12 12:06:03','Yeah ColdFusion plays well with others. As an 11 year CF developer, I can testify to that! It\'s the duct tape of the internet. It can interface with literally anything.',0,'1','','',0,0),(797,263,'Terrence Ryan','terry@terrenceryan.com','http://terrenceryan.com','','2009-02-12 12:13:08','2009-02-12 12:13:08','Nice catch, Ray.  I\'ve added cfinvoke.',0,'1','','',0,0),(798,263,'Rob Munn','robert.munn@emergentpath.com','http://www.emergentpath.com','','2009-02-12 17:58:46','2009-02-12 17:58:46','Good stuff. I would include the integration with AJAX libraries, Flex, event gateways and LCDS/BlazeDS, too. I find that more and more of the really interesting work I do is &quot;on the edges&quot;, and ColdFusion does a remarkable job of communicating with user interfaces in Flex, AIR and AJAX.',0,'1','','',0,0),(799,263,'Paul','kukielp@gmail.com','http://blog.kukiel.net/2009/01/windows-7-coldfusion-and-apache.html','','2009-02-13 18:28:48','2009-02-13 18:28:48','CF8 Worked on Windows 7 with no issues with both apache and IIS  aswell. ;)',0,'1','','',0,0),(800,265,'charlie arehart','charlie_lists@carehart.org','http://www.carehart.org','','2009-02-21 15:45:14','2009-02-21 15:45:14','Very, very nice post, Terry. Not only a great apologetic for CF, but a succinct and compelling demo of functionality to help the converted appreciate the power at their fingertips. Thanks for doing it.\n\nActually, this could make a nifty user group talk (just showing the examples, and expanding on things a little). If you may be interested, I\'m always happy to have any CF speakers on my weekly Online ColdFusion Meetup (coldfusionmeetup.com), and now (in your new role) as much as before, you\'d be most welcomed. If you may be interested, drop me a note: charlie at carehart dot org. If you can\'t do it for some reason, flat out too busy for several weeks, let me know if you\'d prefer to have me put one together. It really does deserve to be highlighted. I\'d even propose doing it as an Adobe Dev Center article, and again if you can\'t get the time to do it, I\'d be willing to co-author something.\n\nKeep up the good work.',0,'1','','',0,0),(801,266,'Bob','bob@bobclingan.com','http://www.bobclingan.com','','2009-02-17 14:03:25','2009-02-17 14:03:25','Just curious... I see the obvious draw in doing an event in Washington, DC, but is there any interest in doing an event in Baltimore? I believe Adobe did a Flex event here last year and the Adobe AIR tour bus came through as well....',0,'1','','',0,0),(802,266,'Terrence Ryan','terry@terrenceryan.com','http://terrenceryan.com','','2009-02-17 15:07:03','2009-02-17 15:07:03','I\'m not entirely sure for the criteria for picking cities for Adobe Days. I\'ll pass the question along, and make sure that I drop you a line if there is a Adobe Day Baltimore.',0,'1','','',0,0),(803,266,'bill shelton','billshelton@comcast.net','http://mxunit.org','','2009-02-18 10:01:12','2009-02-18 10:01:12','very cool, Terry. i\'ll try to make it and see if others @work can, too.',0,'1','','',0,0),(804,267,'Dave Konopka','dave.konopka@gmail.com','http://imakewebjunk.com','','2009-02-18 10:51:52','2009-02-18 10:51:52','What constitutes &quot;academic purposes&quot; for no-cost ColdFusion licenses? Does running servers for academic users count?',0,'1','','',0,0),(805,267,'Adrian J. Moreno','amoreno@iKnowKungFoo.com','http://www.iknowkungfoo.com','','2009-02-18 11:06:32','2009-02-18 11:06:32','I always tell people to check their campus bookstore. I worked at the UNT Bookstore for years and we always stocked the most popular &quot;Academic Use&quot; software titles. If we didn\'t have it in stock, we would always try to order it or find out how a student could order it directly.',0,'1','','',0,0),(806,267,'Terrence Ryan','terry@terrenceryan.com','http://terrenceryan.com','','2009-02-18 13:52:51','2009-02-18 13:52:51','@Dave As far as I know, ColdFusion is free if you are using to further the learning of ColdFusion.  We can go back and forth on what exactly it means, but at the end of the day, we don\'t provide support for these licenses of ColdFusion, so you wouldn\'t want to build a production system on them. Does that make sense?',0,'1','','',0,0),(807,267,'Terrence Ryan','terry@terrenceryan.com','http://terrenceryan.com','','2009-02-18 13:54:06','2009-02-18 13:54:06','@Adrian The store locator will find those stores.  It found my college bookstore, as well as a few others in my area.',0,'1','','',0,0),(808,269,'Nathan Mische','nmische@gmail.com','http://www.mischefamily.com/nathan','','2009-02-24 11:16:52','2009-02-24 11:16:52','I used Total Training for Flex 2 and found it pretty helpful. Looks like there is a new version out for &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.totaltraining.com/prod/adobe/flex3_riaa.asp&quot;&gt;Flex 3&lt;/a&gt;.\n\nOnce I got my feet wet I found myself on the &lt;a href=&quot;http://blog.flexexamples.com/&quot;&gt;Flex Examples&lt;/a&gt; blog quite a bit.',0,'1','','',0,0),(809,269,'Jeffrey Groneberg','inkvine@gmx.net','http://www.inkvine.de','','2009-02-24 14:58:27','2009-02-24 14:58:27','I dont know why, those are pretty good references, but the best thing to learn flex is by using the F1 button within the Flex Builder. You will learn much better by trying to understand the whole stuff than trying to rebuild some tutorials.\n\nBut thats just how I learn a new &quot;thing&quot;.\nNevertheless Flex is an awesome framework and these provided links are very useful.',0,'1','','',0,0),(810,270,'Sam Farmer','sam@samfarmer.com','http://samfarmer.com','','2009-02-25 15:00:50','2009-02-25 15:00:50','We have one but I can\'t talk publicly about it so I\'ll ping you.',0,'1','','',0,0),(811,270,'Alirio Boquin','info@alirio.com','http://www.alirio.com/blog','','2009-02-27 18:30:42','2009-02-27 18:30:42','Hi Ryan.\n\nI didn\'t know was possible to build AIR applications using ColdFusion. I understand until CF 9. Is there some documentation to start learn?',0,'1','','',0,0),(812,270,'Chris Dawes','forums@dawes.id.au','','','2009-03-01 18:10:23','2009-03-01 18:10:23','I\'ll be releasing a tool for extjs shortly (aka before April Conference) that is data-powered by ColdFusion... also a mini-ide...\n\nping me off list for more detail...',0,'1','','',0,0),(813,270,'Aaron West','trajik210@gmail.com','http://www.trajiklyhip.com/blog','','2009-03-08 11:25:36','2009-03-08 11:25:36','Andy Matthews new Shrinkadoo (http://andymatthews.net/code/Shrinkadoo/) HTML AIR app uses ColdFusion. The app hits his shrinkURL (http://shrinkurl.riaforge.org) CFC to integrate with a dozen or so URL shortening services. It\'s a nice app.',0,'1','','',0,0),(814,270,'Jay','jay@serebra.com','https://www.serebraconnect.com/index.cfm?fuseaction=static.staticContent&amp;template=download_alerts_tool','','2009-03-10 10:40:38','2009-03-10 10:40:38','Hi Ryan,\n\nMy Company Serebra has an AIR tool running with CF to create live updates on our Serebra Connect product:\n\nhttps://www.serebraconnect.com/index.cfm?fuseaction=static.staticContent&amp;template=download_alerts_tool',0,'1','','',0,0),(815,271,'Hector','hectcastro@gmail.com','','','2009-03-09 17:54:23','2009-03-09 17:54:23','I clicked on the first ColdFusion vs. PHP bullet.  After reading the third paragraph, I\'m done.  You cannot just say Ruby on Rails was the wrong tool for Twitter and proceed to give no solid technical explanation why.  Perhaps the author of that article should take a second understand the problems Twitter faced and how they\'re solving them.  Scaling for the amount of users Twitter serves is not a trivial task solved by ColdFusion -- it is an ongoing battle to reduce bottlenecks in many areas.\n\nhttp://highscalability.com/scaling-twitter-making-twitter-10000-percent-faster',0,'1','','',0,0),(816,271,'Jon Hartmann','jon.hartmann@gmail.com','http://www.jonhartmann.com','','2009-03-09 17:14:13','2009-03-09 17:14:13','Ok, let me first say that I love ColdFusion.\n\nThat said, picking out single examples of code and saying &quot;its smaller, so is better&quot; isn\'t really a comparison at all. I mean, why don\'t we compare CF and Rails and see &quot;How many lines of code does it take to implement an MVC implementation?&quot; The answer in Rails is 0 and the answer in CF is quite a lot. The real questions are how well does it scale, how quickly can a usable application be created, how flexible is the code, etc. Those are answer\'s you can\'t get by counting lines.',0,'1','','',0,0),(817,271,'Terrence Ryan','terry@terrenceryan.com','http://terrenceryan.com','','2009-03-09 17:44:12','2009-03-09 17:44:12','@Jon, I think if you\'re trying to compare on lines of code as a straight metric, then you\'re right.  But I think all of the examples take into account both lines of code and simplicity of execution.\n\nSimplicity of execution is where I think CF shines in these coding examples.',0,'1','','',0,0),(818,271,'denny','valliantster@gmail.com','','','2009-03-09 18:46:19','2009-03-09 18:46:19','@Jon  Rails is a framework, not exactly a programming language [insert scripting/programming language jokes here].\n\nCF has code generation frameworks too (although everything takes at least *some* code-- depending on how you quantify &quot;code&quot;-- there are no 0 line programs (depending on your definition of a program, I guess.) ;])\n\nRuby not scaling well has been beaten to death (I think a good bit of this is because of one of the &quot;main dev&quot; dudes bouncing and then bitching), but I would like to point out that things in Rails-land are *much* better in this regard these days.\n\nSeems like some things are harder with certain &quot;languages&quot; than others, and it really depends on WTF you\'re trying to accomplish, your &quot;end goals&quot;, available talent, etc..\n\nThere is no single right answer, really.  Well, besides philosophy, of course.  :-)p\n\nSome Philosophy (or something like that):\n\nhttp://blog.objectmentor.com/articles/2009/02/26/10-papers-every-programmer-should-read-at-least-twice',0,'1','','',0,0),(819,271,'Jon Hartmann','jon.hartmann@gmail.com','http://www.jonhartmann.com','','2009-03-09 21:32:47','2009-03-09 21:32:47','@Terrence: I agree, and its one of the reasons I can\'t stand coding PHP anymore (despite having started with it before CF).\n\n@Denny: I think I was hinting at what you say explicitly; it all depends on what you\'re doing. If you\'re doing lots of smaller e-commerce sites, Rails might be your best friend. Working somewhere that does lots of heavy number crunching, you might go for Java or something else. I also wasn\'t trying to rag on Rails performance, but simply point out that there are other features then lines of code on which to evaluate a server and language. And thanks for the link; those look like awesome reads.',0,'1','','',0,0),(820,271,'Brandon Hansen','brandon@melissa-brandon.com','http://melissa-brandon.com','','2009-03-10 01:25:31','2009-03-10 01:25:31','@Hector\nThe point of the article was not at all to say that RoR is a bad framework.  I actually love the framework, more and more each day.  There is no framework that gets it done that quickly and effectively.\n\nThe reason that I stated that RoR should not have been used is simply because it is untested to that scale.  I went on to say that it has performed quite well, and now we have an example of a site that does well using RoR.  I actually don\'t know that CF would have been a good solution for that site.  My suggestion would be to go with either PHP or Java (PHP powers facebook, and Java powers linkedin).\n\nPlease don\'t mistake a small point in the article for the purpose of the article.  I do welcome your criticism, and will learn from my mistakes.',0,'1','','',0,0),(821,271,'Brandon Hansen','brandon@melissa-brandon.com','http://melissa-brandon.com','','2009-03-10 01:25:56','2009-03-10 01:25:56','@Hector\nThe point of the article was not at all to say that RoR is a bad framework.  I actually love the framework, more and more each day.  There is no framework that gets it done that quickly and effectively.\n\nThe reason that I stated that RoR should not have been used is simply because it is untested to that scale.  I went on to say that it has performed quite well, and now we have an example of a site that does well using RoR.  I actually don\'t know that CF would have been a good solution for that site.  My suggestion would be to go with either PHP or Java (PHP powers facebook, and Java powers linkedin).\n\nPlease don\'t mistake a small point in the article for the purpose of the article.  I do welcome your criticism, and will learn from my mistakes.',0,'1','','',0,0),(822,271,'Brandon Hansen','brandon@melissa-brandon.com','http://melissa-brandon.com','','2009-03-10 01:26:10','2009-03-10 01:26:10','@Hector\nThe point of the article was not at all to say that RoR is a bad framework.  I actually love the framework, more and more each day.  There is no framework that gets it done that quickly and effectively.\n\nThe reason that I stated that RoR should not have been used is simply because it is untested to that scale.  I went on to say that it has performed quite well, and now we have an example of a site that does well using RoR.  I actually don\'t know that CF would have been a good solution for that site.  My suggestion would be to go with either PHP or Java (PHP powers facebook, and Java powers linkedin).\n\nPlease don\'t mistake a small point in the article for the purpose of the article.  I do welcome your criticism, and will learn from my mistakes.',0,'1','','',0,0),(823,271,'Brandon Hansen','brandon@melissa-brandon.com','http://melissa-brandon.com','','2009-03-10 01:27:10','2009-03-10 01:27:10','Terrance,\nThe comments form is not closing when the form is submitted for some reason.  Please delete my extra comments when you get the chance (I posted the same thing 3x)',0,'1','','',0,0),(824,271,'Hector','hectcastro@gmail.com','','','2009-03-10 05:29:51','2009-03-10 05:29:51','@Brandon: First, I\'d like to apologize for the tone of my comment -- it was rather aggressive (long day).  Second, I understand the goal of your article, but I do not believe Ruby on Rails should have been excluded as an option simply because there was no precedent.  If decisions were made that way, we\'d all be developing web applications in C.  PHP does power Facebook, but so does C++, Java, Python, Ruby, and Erlang.\n\nI agree that we have learned much from Twitter\'s decisions.  Anyone who wants to create a web application based on Ruby on Rails now has something of a scaling roadmap to follow.  We\'re all lucky they revealed as much detail about their struggles as they did.',0,'1','','',0,0),(825,271,'Mike','magnetion@gmail.com','http://blog.magnetion.com','','2009-03-10 06:51:51','2009-03-10 06:51:51','Terrance, thanks for the links over to my articles on the Magnetion Blog.  I would like to note that I have known (and loved) ColdFusion for 10 years now.  My background in web development started with CF and has evolved from there.  I have been digging into .NET recently and thought it would be cool to share the experiences with both.  I agree with another commenter, that just comparing the number of lines of code is not the correct way to compare languages.  If that were the case ColdFusion would be the best by a mile (as you can do so much with so little code).  Becoming a seasoned developer means you can objectively look into the requirements of a project and then determine the best language or platform to meet those needs and goals.  As much as I love ColdFusion, it is not the best choice for every situation.  There are others that it meets perfectly.  I tend to stay away from the flame wars of &quot;this language is better than that language&quot;, as it 100% depends on the requirements of the project or the application.',0,'1','','',0,0),(826,271,'Brandon Hansen','brandon@melissa-brandon.com','http://melissa-brandon.com','','2009-03-10 11:38:35','2009-03-10 11:38:35','@Hector\nThis is a great article to read, straight from the horses mouth-\nhttp://www.radicalbehavior.com/5-question-interview-with-twitter-developer-alex-payne/',0,'1','','',0,0),(827,275,'Liz Frederick','liz@cfunited.com','http://cfunited.com','','2009-03-18 15:04:25','2009-03-18 15:04:25','Awesome. This is really worth spreading the news about. Thanks for the post.',0,'1','','',0,0),(828,275,'Javier Julio','JJfutbol@gmail.com','http://www.javier-julio.com','','2009-03-18 16:18:01','2009-03-18 16:18:01','Yeah this really is Liz! I\'ve made sure to pass this along to others who\'d be interested. Thanks!',0,'1','','',0,0),(829,275,'inj','576871@gmail.com','http://injun.ru','','2009-03-19 11:13:51','2009-03-19 11:13:51','Hi!\nLink on 6 page to download Curriculum course files (http://adobe.com/go/cfcurriculum) is broken.',0,'1','','',0,0),(830,275,'Rod Nolan','rodn@newyyz.com','http://www.newyyz.com','','2009-05-22 14:03:42','2009-05-22 14:03:42','Since this material used to be made available only to Adobe Certified Training Partners, I, as an employee of one such company, am shocked to see this material being made freely available. Terrence, can you comment on the reasoning behind this move?',0,'1','','',0,0),(831,276,'Dave Shuck','dshuck@gmail.com','http://www.coldfusionisdead.com','','2009-03-18 15:39:46','2009-03-18 15:39:46','I will go out on a limb and call it &quot;cool&quot; :)',0,'1','','',0,0),(832,276,'Raymond Camden','ray@camdenfamily.com','http://www.coldfusionjedi.com','','2009-03-18 16:46:29','2009-03-18 16:46:29','Ditto. Pretty neat. :)',0,'1','','',0,0),(833,276,'Henry Ho','henryho167@gmail.com','http://henrylearnstorock.blogspot.com','','2009-03-18 18:56:45','2009-03-18 18:56:45','Does this work?\njavaProxy[missingMethodName](argumentCollection=missingMethodArguments)\n\nIf not, you can still optimize your code by using ArrayToList() for your loop.',0,'1','','',0,0),(834,278,'Henry Ho','henryho167@gmail.com','http://henrylearnstorock.blogspot.com','','2009-03-27 13:51:38','2009-03-27 13:51:38','In the embed video player, it says:\n\n&quot;Error #18: XML does not conform to BOSS standard&quot;',0,'1','','',0,0),(835,278,'Kevin Hoyt','khoyt@adobe.com','http://blog.kevinhoyt.org','','2009-04-07 14:00:42','2009-04-07 14:00:42','Not bad for the first day on the job!  ;-)',0,'1','','',0,0),(836,279,'John Farrar','johnfarrar@sosensible.com','','','2009-03-31 10:52:59','2009-03-31 10:52:59','Will there be a US version?',0,'1','','',0,0),(837,282,'Al','flex9n@gmail.com','','','2009-04-20 15:53:40','2009-04-20 15:53:40','See you tomorrow...',0,'1','','',0,0),(838,282,'John Piotrowski','johnrp@wharton.upenn.edu','','','2009-04-22 11:14:59','2009-04-22 11:14:59','I attended the Adobe Road Show Denver a few weeks ago and it is definitely worth attending if you can make it.  Terry kept it interesting and a did a real good job presenting the information.',0,'1','','',0,0),(839,286,'Nathan Mische','nmische@gmail.com','http://www.mischefamily.com/nathan','','2009-05-06 09:53:42','2009-05-06 09:53:42','I\'m bummed that it looks like I\'m not going to make it to any conferences this year. I\'d love to see the Extending Adobe Bolt with CFML and Centaur and Gumbo presentations...',0,'1','','',0,0),(840,286,'andy matthews','amatthews@dealerskins.com','http://andymatthews.net','','2009-05-01 18:46:15','2009-05-01 18:46:15','Looking forward to seeing you again my friend. Have fun in Dublin!',0,'1','','',0,0),(841,288,'charlie arehart','charlie_lists@carehart.org','http://www.carehart.org','','2009-05-15 22:39:22','2009-05-15 22:39:22','Terry, I think you might want to edit the entry (for those who don\'t read comments) to clarify that these are the cities *you\'re* speaking in. Since you say &quot;we\'re doing a multi-city&quot; tour, some may presume this is the list of all UG tours.\n\nSure, if people visit Ben\'s site we see too he has listed only &quot;his&quot; talks, but not all reading this will do that and connect the dots. just trying to help.\n\nIndeed, in case any would wonder, is there any one list of all the CFUG tours, for those who wonder if their city is covered by somebody?\n\nHope it goes well for you and all the speaker and attendees.',0,'1','','',0,0),(842,288,'Suze','snoonan@csc.com','','','2009-05-14 12:30:05','2009-05-14 12:30:05','are there going to be any talks in Southern California??',0,'1','','',0,0),(843,288,'Rick Mason','Rick@Coldfusion.org','http://www.coldfusion.org','','2009-05-13 08:23:02','2009-05-13 08:23:02','Excited to have you coming to East Lansing.',0,'1','','',0,0),(844,288,'Daniel Sellers','daniel@designfrontier.net','http://www.designfrontier.net','','2009-05-13 09:43:06','2009-05-13 09:43:06','Look forward to having y\'all in Houston. Should be a lot of fun!',0,'1','','',0,0),(845,288,'Sami Hoda','sami@bytestopshere.com','http://www.bytestopshere.com','','2009-05-13 11:22:26','2009-05-13 11:22:26','Don\'t forget LA. The IECFUG would love to have you!',0,'1','','',0,0),(846,288,'Steve Brownlee','steven.brownlee@gmail.com','http://www.fusioncube.net','','2009-05-13 16:00:37','2009-05-13 16:00:37','Hey!  How come Texas gets all the lovin\'?   :)\n\nWe\'d love to have you in Nashville, or hereabouts.',0,'1','','',0,0),(847,288,'charlie arehart','charlie_lists@carehart.org','http://www.carehart.org','','2009-05-17 15:20:46','2009-05-17 15:20:46','For those who see this thread and not the other, Terry graciously responded the next day (after my comment above) with a new blog entry. He also points there to a link that has all the dates for all the tours. Check out his follow-up entry:\n\nhttp://www.terrenceryan.com/blog/index.cfm/2009/5/16/User-Group-Tour--Clarification\n\nThanks, Terry.',0,'1','','',0,0),(848,292,'Bob Flynn','reflynn@indiana.edu','http://bobflynn.info','','2009-07-06 10:57:22','2009-07-06 10:57:22','Hey Terry,\n\nUnless you want to revisit the treaty of Trianon you should clarify where Mihai is based. Bucharest is in Romania. Budapast is Hungary. ;-)',0,'1','','',0,0),(849,294,'Brian Swartzfager','bcswartz@gmail.com','http://www.swartzfager.org/blog','','2009-06-22 20:08:23','2009-06-22 20:08:23','I\'m a bit puzzled by the end of the post:  why would I need to convince my DBAs that Hibernate is a good thing?  Normally, I just ask them to create the tablespace I need and give me the information needed to set up the datasource on ColdFusion:  would I need anything additional from them to use Hibernate?',0,'1','','',0,0),(850,294,'Sean Corfield','seancorfield@gmail.com','http://corfield.org/','','2009-06-22 20:28:43','2009-06-22 20:28:43','I suspect the &quot;My DBA isn\'t going to like that!&quot; comments come more from CFers than actual DBAs. Whilst some DBAs do have a bit of an axe to grind with Hibernate, in general I\'ve found them to be reasonably happy to work with what Hibernate creates and do the analysis and tuning that they\'d do with any DB created by someone outside their team.\n\nOf course, if you have the sort of DBA that doesn\'t let you so much as alter the length of an existing column, you\'re going to run into a lot of resistance to the idea of software that automatically generates the entire schema for you :)\n\nI hope that CF-ORM means more people will start their design with objects and relationships and let Hibernate take care of creating and maintaining the schema so that we can get better designed applications (model-focused, instead of database-focused).\n\nIt\'ll be very interesting to see how CF-ORM is received in the wild (I\'m already sold on Hibernate having used it with Groovy at Broadchoice!).',0,'1','','',0,0),(851,294,'Andrew Scott','andrews@andyscott.id.au','','','2009-06-23 01:16:50','2009-06-23 01:16:50','There is also the other side of the coin with Hibernate as well. And that is that one can use what is called legacy databases with Hibernate. That coupled with the mapping can still give the best of both worlds, I don\'t see DBA\'s having to much of a complaint as Sean has stated most that I have worked with are more than happy to work with hibernate.',0,'1','','',0,0),(852,294,'Chris Hayes','chris@hayesdata.com','http://www.hayesdata.com','','2009-06-23 02:05:35','2009-06-23 02:05:35','I for one welcome our new ORM overlords.\n\nIn all seriousness this is yet another positive abstraction layer that will make an application more portable over time.  Hibernate is proven technology and let\'s face it there are an awful lot of apps out there with poorly written SQL that an ORM system would have helped avoid.  Best practices are still necessary however this will make life easier for many and hopefully drive people further down the wonderful road of abstracted objects with well defined relationships.',0,'1','','',0,0),(853,294,'Jake Munson','yacoubean@gmail.com','http://techfeed.net/blog/','','2009-06-23 22:46:25','2009-06-23 22:46:25','I think Sean got it right...it depends on the DBA.  If your DBA is very protective of his database, they are not going to like you using a code that creates SQL on the fly.\n\nPut yourself in their shoes.  What if a graphic designer were to come to you and say, &quot;Hey CFer...I\'ve got this tool that generates CF code to support my designs...you can just plug this code into your server and you won\'t have to do anything else!&quot;  Would you be very happy about this?  Wouldn\'t you be a little skeptical about this auto-generated CF code?',0,'1','','',0,0),(854,294,'Ben Shichman','bshichman@yahoo.com','','','2009-07-06 13:46:28','2009-07-06 13:46:28','Having just completed a massive Java based project using Hibernate, I would say it is far from a panacea.  If you are working with complex and large datasets (meaning hundreds of thousands to millions of rows) then Hibernate can actually bog you down when it is constructing the datasets for your queries.   We are looking at removing Hibernate from this application and writing the queries directly to the JDBC driver.  Hibernate is great, but seems best suited to smaller sizes of data.',0,'1','','',0,0),(855,294,'catering company raleigh','pictures23herpes@gmail.com','http://www.trianglecatering.com/','','2010-01-20 08:15:53','2010-01-20 08:15:53','You seem to have got the niche from the root, Awesome work\n\nRegards',0,'1','','',0,0),(856,294,'MeganF1ch','elmiker07@yahoo.com','http://iesvelesevents.edu.gva.es/moodle/user/view.php?id=1205&amp;course=1','','2010-01-25 19:34:13','2010-01-25 19:34:13','Strong time. , replacing lawnmower blade, buy men\'s shirts, new mens shirts, blade cut off, stripe button down shirt, buy personalized t shirts, floral mens shirt, tee shirt printing, blade z xtr 250, white and orange shirt, shirt by shirt clothing,',0,'1','','',0,0),(857,295,'Chris Rockett','rockettman@pokeitwithastick.com','','','2009-07-06 11:06:50','2009-07-06 11:06:50','Terry, in your post you talk about a hotfix being devloped for this but I don\'t see that it\'s available.  Do you know when it will be available?',0,'1','','',0,0),(858,295,'','ray@camdenfamily.com','','','2009-07-06 10:55:01','2009-07-06 10:55:01','',0,'1','','',0,0),(859,295,'Terrence Ryan','terry@terrenceryan.com','http://terrenceryan.com','','2009-07-06 13:46:17','2009-07-06 13:46:17','It should be &quot;soon.&quot;  I think we\'ve said something along the lines of later in the week.',0,'1','','',0,0),(860,295,'John Mason','mason@fusionlink.com','http://www.codfusion.com','','2009-07-06 16:48:28','2009-07-06 16:48:28','Chris, to be clear here. Don\'t wait for the patch to get released - you need to check for this as soon as possible and do the recommended setting change.',0,'1','','',0,0),(861,295,'John Mason','mason@fusionlink.com','http://www.codfusion.com','','2009-07-06 19:52:02','2009-07-06 19:52:02','Well I was holding back on this to see if anyone wanted to question this first, but I\'ll go ahead.\n\n\n\n&quot;Personally, in hindsight, there\'s one decision we should have gone another way on: we should have released the workaround sooner.&quot; Naturally I agree and hope this happens in the future.\n The damage is done. The key at this point is to fix the problem and prevent this from happening again. That is the light I\'m taking in my following questions.\n\n\n&quot;Is it true that Adobe had a fix for months and sat on it?&quot; Your time line says essentially 8 weeks ago from this week (so about 2 months). Bare in mind the hotfix still isn\'t out yet so the clock is still running. So 8 weeks ago, was that the official post/request for the hotfix or the initial contact?\n\n\n\n&quot;The customer was not satisfied with just a workaround for several reasons including concern that we were not actually fixing the correct problem. (This concern ended up being true.)&quot; Sounds like confusion on the Adobe end of this. That naturally makes me even more concerned about the internal process at Adobe. Yes, there should be a procedure, but once a security vulnerability of this level has been detected, the black hats typically already know. Perhaps I\'m missing something, but I simply can\'t think of any reason why it should have taken this long given the nature of the vulnerability.\n\n\n\n&quot;Additionally, our security people were also not entirely convinced that the workaround was entirely the right solution.&quot; Why? It really is a simple solution. What other options did they really have?\n\n\n\nOn the flip side of this, did management not understand the nature of the problem? What was their reaction to this initially? It\'s on them to understand the gravity of this and to act. I suspect from this post that some of this is being dump on the security team when management really has to take full responsibility.\n\n\n\nThe other part of this is why the vulnerability was allowed to live on in the CF 8.0.1 trials / downloads from Adobe. Some people had fairly new instances being created in the meantime that didn\'t need to have this bug open. Basically, you could have limited the fire by doing that.',0,'1','','',0,0),(862,295,'John Mason','mason@fusionlink.com','http://www.codfusion.com','','2009-07-06 21:54:00','2009-07-06 21:54:00','The current PSIRT posts still says \'potential\' security issue (http://blogs.adobe.com/psirt/2009/07/potential_coldfusion_security.html). Avoiding confusion at this point is very important. Some may read that title and think it\'s not a big deal. It\'s not a \'potential\' issue but a very high security risk that has been confirmed by a number of people. I would advise modifying the title to make that completely clear.',0,'1','','',0,0),(863,295,'Brian Panulla','bpanulla@gmail.com','http://ghostednotes.com','','2009-07-07 13:15:36','2009-07-07 13:15:36','I hope for one thing this doesn\'t hurt Adobe\'s attitude towards Open Source projects. I for one am very hopeful that Adobe continues  to integrate high-quality OSS like FCK (in ColdFusion) and Subversion (in Dreamweaver) into their products. I\'ve been using both with ColdFusion for almost six years now, and I\'m very happy to see this sort of action on Adobe\'s part. Too often OSS project teams are difficult for corporate product teams to deal with, either through personality conflicts or the slow communications that come from dealing with largely volunteer efforts.\n\nI\'m not very familar with the FCK developers, but I hope Adobe\'s interaction was a positive one over this matter.',0,'1','','',0,0),(864,295,'Terrence Ryan','terry@terrenceryan.com','http://terrenceryan.com','','2009-07-08 20:44:22','2009-07-08 20:44:22','Brian:  We use OSS in CF pretty extensively.  I don\'t think this will be affecting our use of it.',0,'1','','',0,0),(865,295,'Josh Adams','joadams@adobe.com','http://blog.joshuaadams.com','','2009-07-09 00:18:03','2009-07-09 00:18:03','As Ben Forta has posted on his blog at http://forta.com/blog/index.cfm/2009/7/8/ColdFusion-8-Security-Bulletin-Posted, we (Adobe) have now posted the Hotfix for this issue and you can read more about it in the accompanying security bulletin available at http://www.adobe.com/support/security/bulletins/apsb09-09.html',0,'1','','',0,0),(866,295,'Jeremy Prevost','j-prevost@northwestern.edu','','','2009-07-10 13:44:34','2009-07-10 13:44:34','I actually submitted a security report to PSIRT on Feb 3 for this issue and was told February 20 (after requesting a status report) &quot;the development team is closing in on a fix, and we should have a tentative patch schedule to pass along to you soon&quot;.',0,'1','','',0,0),(867,295,'RyanTJ','thompsonjewell.ryan@mayo.edu','http://mayoclinic.com','','2009-07-22 09:48:47','2009-07-22 09:48:47','In the end I think Adobe did a great job and what most companies do and would do. Its a tough to know how much information disclosure will help or could fuel more exploits.  I actually hope Adobe bundles more open source and RIA Forge projects with releases. It seems like their are great solutions out there for many things that could be bundled. Not that we need true CF tags to interface with these but some better integration. Standard extensions type folders and even a standard mechanism by which someone could check for updates to the bundle code.  It could just be some xml with an extension ID, name, code repository url, author, license, version, etc.',0,'1','','',0,0),(868,296,'John Masonn','mason@fusionlink.com','http://www.codfusion.com','','2009-07-08 11:59:58','2009-07-08 11:59:58','Figure I write up a post about the art of writing up a proper bug report to help this process out. It\'s at http://www.codfusion.com/blog/post.cfm/how-to-submit-a-bug-report. Want to prevent emails flying into Adobe will bogus or badly documented reports.',0,'1','','',0,0),(869,297,'Joseph Labrecque','joseph.labrecque@du.edu','http://inflagrantedelicto.memoryspiral.com/','','2009-07-08 20:06:02','2009-07-08 20:06:02','That\'s really good to know.  I do a lot of chromeless AIR with Flex SDK 3.x and this is very different from the way I set things up, currently.\n\nIn the planning stages for a chromeless v4 app- so your post is good timing for me!',0,'1','','',0,0),(870,297,'Dan Martin','dmartin@dmartin.org','http://dmartin.org','','2009-07-09 11:03:55','2009-07-09 11:03:55','This is the way I do it:\n1) in *-app.xml:\n 	                &lt;systemChrome&gt;none&lt;/systemChrome&gt;\n 	                &lt;transparent&gt;true&lt;/transparent&gt;\n\n2) In your WindowedApplication in your root mxml:\n     layout=&quot;absolute&quot; showStatusBar=&quot;false&quot; showTitleBar=&quot;false&quot; showGripper=&quot;false&quot; backgroundAlpha=&quot;0&quot; borderThickness=&quot;0&quot;\n\nThen, I have an Canvas inside WindowedApplication that is visible, with left=&quot;0&quot; right=&quot;0&quot; top=&quot;0&quot; bottom=&quot;0&quot;.  The main purpose of having an inner canvas is that it allows you to have rounded corners, semi-opaque background, etc unlike WindowedApplication.',0,'1','','',0,0),(871,297,'Thibault Imbert','thibault@bytearray.org','http://www.bytearray.org','','2009-07-09 11:43:55','2009-07-09 11:43:55','Thanks a lot, I had the exact same problem, cool ;)',0,'1','','',0,0),(872,297,'Matthew Wallace','mswallace.com@gmail.com','http://mswallace.com','','2009-09-09 22:46:03','2009-09-09 22:46:03','Your blog post was the only one that had a solution on it that I could find easily.\n\nFor the most part I would say the new component Skinning that is coming with Flex 4 is awesome but..... something like setting background alpha to 0 shouldn\'t be so hard to do. Ahhhhh Adobe sometimes I have to ask myself why.\n\nThanks for the post fo show!\n-Matthew',0,'1','','',0,0),(873,297,'Andre Venter','andre.n.venter@gmail.com','http://think-a-doo.net','','2009-10-10 17:56:19','2009-10-10 17:56:19','To Dan Martin,\n\nYour solution sounds great. How do you end up moving the AIR app around the screen and closing it?\n\nI find when I suppress customchrome the AIR app does not want to go to my screen 0,0 and ends up floating in some arbitrary location near, but not at the center of my screen. It sucks not knowing how to control it\'s position.',0,'1','','',0,0),(874,297,'Javier R.E.','web@jrayon.net','http://www.jrayon.net','','2010-01-04 07:02:34','2010-01-04 07:02:34','Hi!\n\nCan you explain a bit more how to use this code? I need to apply it to a Window component (not to the main WindowedApplication, but only to a window opened by the main app).\n\nthanks!\nJavier',0,'1','','',0,0),(875,297,'Mike','mike.coppola@gmail.com','','','2009-11-13 14:15:50','2009-11-13 14:15:50','Thanks , this was what I was looking for',0,'1','','',0,0),(876,297,'Giorgos','info@primecut.gr','','','2010-01-24 14:06:45','2010-01-24 14:06:45','Could you explain the code a bit, its not that clear how to work this out, i\'ve tried many things either but none of the tutorials worked for sdk 4.0.\n\nCheers!\nGiorgos',0,'1','','',0,0),(877,297,'Sarbagna','arijit.sarbagna@innindia.com','http://www.innindia.com','','2010-05-07 07:28:18','2010-05-07 07:28:18','Even for your WindowedApplication,\nin your *-app.xml:\n    <systemChrome>none</systemChrome>\n    <transparent>true</transparent>\n\nThis should do the trick.',0,'1','','',0,0),(878,297,'James','yanlilei64@gmail.com','','','2010-11-12 01:31:51','2010-11-12 01:31:51','For more demo, download Tour De Flex',0,'1','','',0,0),(879,297,'Rodislav Moldovan','rodislav@gmail.com','http://despre.md/ideapress','','2011-05-23 11:59:47','2011-05-23 11:59:47','@Sarbagna, you\'r right. That does the trick!\n\nbut! one thing! :))\n\nif that is not working, you need to create new project - change properties in app.xml (how Sarbagna wrote) then test, if everything is ok, add you code to the project. And everything will be ok, but! don\'t touch this - EVER!!!!\n\nbecause chrome may appear again :D',0,'1','','',0,0),(880,297,'Kurt','kurt@stirnkorb.com','http://www.windycitydev.com','','2010-12-23 11:49:38','2010-12-23 11:49:38','Thanks a bunch. Tried to do the transparency thing for about 2 hours. Not as easy as Flex 3 but this worked great.',0,'1','','',0,0),(881,297,'Rodislav Moldovan','rodislav@gmail.com','http://despre.md/ideapress','','2011-04-28 04:02:10','2011-04-28 04:02:10','@Dan Martin,\nHi, thanks a lot!!!!',0,'1','','',0,0),(882,297,'Zurgerok','zurgerz9@gmail.com','http://mg-portal.com.ua/raskrutka-saytov.html','','2011-07-04 14:17:01','2011-07-04 14:17:01','<a href=http://mg-portal.com.ua/raskrutka-saytov.html rel=\"nofollow\"> ????????? ?????? </a>\n\n<img>http://mgp.ua/img/13/3.jpg</img>',0,'1','','',0,0),(883,300,'John Barrett','johnbarr@hawaii.edu','http://hawaiiflash.net/blog','','2009-07-13 01:51:16','2009-07-13 01:51:16','Thanks`-`\nI am downloading the Mac installers now!\n\nI will be attending tomorrow as well!\nOne question I have(not sure if you can answer) is will CF 9 have verity on the Mac?\nThanks again,\nJohnny`-`',0,'1','','',0,0),(884,300,'Chris','coldfusion@procept.net','http://www.cfug.de','','2009-07-13 06:10:02','2009-07-13 06:10:02','@John: Even better... CF9 has SolR Search Services, which are based on Apache Lucene. It also includes a Verity 2 SolR conversionwizard. ;-)\n\nCheers\n\nChris',0,'1','','',0,0),(885,300,'John Barrett','johnbarr@hawaii.edu','http://hawaiiflash.net/blog','','2009-07-15 02:37:01','2009-07-15 02:37:01','Hi Chris,\nThanks!',0,'1','','',0,0),(886,301,'healthy food recipes discount','asdfwerj8@gmail.com','http://www.gravatar.com/healthyfoodrecipesa','','2011-06-26 09:34:01','2011-06-26 09:34:01','Your Site Is Great!, http://www.gravatar.com/marthastewartdessere All about martha stewart dessert recipes,  583,',0,'1','','',0,0),(887,302,'Nathan Mische','nmische@gmail.com','http://www.mischefamily.com/nathan','','2009-07-13 14:02:39','2009-07-13 14:02:39','This is awesome news. If we can\'t find an issue we previously submitted via the wish form, should we re-enter it here?',0,'1','','',0,0),(888,302,'Terrence Ryan','terry@terrenceryan.com','http://terrenceryan.com','','2009-07-13 14:34:44','2009-07-13 14:34:44','I would recommend it.  I think go/wish entries just got sent out to mailing lists.',0,'1','','',0,0),(889,303,'Dan G. Switzer, II','dswitzer@pengoworks.com','http://blog.pengoworks.com/','','2009-07-13 15:23:17','2009-07-13 15:23:17','@Terry:\n\nI\'m sure you\'ve been told already, but audio dropage is horrible in the saved presentation. Once you get into it past 40 minutes it seems like almost half the audio is gone. It\'ll go fairly long (5-10) seconds with no audio.\n\nI know people where complaining about the dropage during the live presentation and Charlie seemed to think the recording might not be affected, but it makes this pretty unwatchable.\n\n(My intent isn\'t to complain, just to give you a heads up since you probably have no reason to listen to the recording--you know what you said!.)',0,'1','','',0,0),(890,303,'Terrence Ryan','terry@terrenceryan.com','http://terrenceryan.com','','2009-07-13 15:27:00','2009-07-13 15:27:00','So yeah, I hear you about the audio problem.\n\nI\'ll see if I can\'t schedule another session to see if we can get a better recording.  I can\'t promise anything, but we\'ll see.',0,'1','','',0,0),(891,303,'Jeremy Prevost','j-prevost@northwestern.edu','','','2009-07-17 14:11:04','2009-07-17 14:11:04','I\'d recommend doing an offline recording... and break it up into smaller sections (i.e. one recording for each Bolt feature you describe). It\'ll be way easier to watch a few short clips than one 1+ long talk on multiple topics. The short clips will also allow you to reshoot just little pieces if there are any audio problems, demo failures, etc. Green screen optional.',0,'1','','',0,0),(892,304,'Rupesh Kumar','rukumar@adobe.com','http://www.rupeshk.org','','2009-07-17 00:58:40','2009-07-17 00:58:40','Great post Terry! I completely agree with you and that is the power of ColdFusion :-)',0,'1','','',0,0),(893,305,'Steven Erat','serat@webapper.com','http://www.webapper.com/','','2009-07-14 12:00:34','2009-07-14 12:00:34','Thanks Terry.  My fingers are starting to unwrap from my death grip on Homesite+ 5.5.',0,'1','','',0,0),(894,305,'Sam Farmer','sam@samfarmer.com','http://samfarmer.com','','2009-07-14 15:36:28','2009-07-14 15:36:28','Thanks Terry.\n\nThe word wrap looks and works really well.  You might even like it! ;)',0,'1','','',0,0),(895,305,'Matt','matt@moleinteractive.com','','','2009-07-14 15:40:25','2009-07-14 15:40:25','Thanks for this, I was looking as well.  Have I missed code folding anywhere?  When I open CFC\'s I liked how CFEclipse collapsed all of them by default',0,'1','','',0,0),(896,305,'Stodgy','yeah@right.com','','','2009-07-14 16:32:36','2009-07-14 16:32:36','How is this not a simple toggle button on a toolbar somewhere? Amazing.',0,'1','','',0,0),(897,305,'Sam','mitchell.samuel@gmail.com','','','2009-07-21 21:28:33','2009-07-21 21:28:33','Yes, please give us the option to initially fold methods in CFC\'s. Also, it would be nice to have the option to un-select code we don\'t want folded by default like loops, conditionals etc. It can get very annoying when every little snipit wants to fold up in your functions.',0,'1','','',0,0),(898,305,'Adam Cameron','adam_junk@hotmail.com','','','2009-07-28 06:13:46','2009-07-28 06:13:46','Interesting.  Making that change makes absolutely no difference for me (in either *.htm? or *cf? files).\n\nI\'m running the stand-alone version, on Windows Vista Home Premium.\n\nOne thing that leapt to mind when you said Adobe were looking at putting the option somewhere more obvious was &quot;well... yes, definitely.  Why would one expect a setting under the HTML options have any impact of CF templates anyhow?&quot;  I could understand if it switched line wrap on for HTM/HTML files, but that option shouldn\'t impact CFM/CFC files at all, should it?  If it\'s a global option for all file types, it should be under Prefs &gt; General &gt; Editors, shouldn\'t it?\n\nIn reality, though, this option should be on a toolbar somewhere on the main edit screen, I think. And it should be toggle-able without needing to restart the workspace.\n\nCheers for  the tip though.  Any thoughts as to why it dun\'t work for me?\n\n--\nAdam',0,'1','','',0,0),(899,305,'Adam Cameron','adam_junk@hotmail.com','','','2009-07-28 06:15:08','2009-07-28 06:15:08','Just an observation: your comments - when displayed - do not preserve any formatting, like the para breaks I put in my previous comment.  Reduces readability somewhat.\n\n--\nAdam',0,'1','','',0,0),(900,305,'Don Burnstein','donb@theimagefactory.com','http://www.theimagefactory.com','','2010-03-21 19:07:35','2010-03-21 19:07:35','As much as we have to keep in our heads at any given time ( and the older we are) it\'s amazing that word wrap reminds me of a typical Microsft Application where a critical feature is so far off the beaten path that I may have top make a snippet for it.\n\nWhy not put it in the right click button menu at the top and a text based icon that is easily visible?\n\nWhile were on the general topic of ease of use: is there a way to bookmark files that one is currently working on so we don\'t have to go through the project heirarchy or create projects that just contain those files? How about under tasks or a work in progress pallete we have a choice of adding all open documents to the pallet, naming it and then call it back up instead of going through setting up a new project.\n\nFinally, under the CRS heading, one feature of dreamweaver that was appreciated that I can\'t seem to find here was Inserts. I see it on the html, JS, CSS and CFML but I\'d like to see SPRY or our choice of insets based on Ajax frameworks, Jquery etc.',0,'1','','',0,0),(901,305,'ManOnTheMoon','pbagnato@sbcglobal.net','','','2010-04-13 12:26:31','2010-04-13 12:26:31','thanks for pointing out where the word wrap is! It even turned on the line numbers for me. Yay!!\n\nWho would ever think those would be advanced options?\n\nIn any case, does anyone know how to jump to a particular line number? (Like using Ctrl-G in Dreamweaver... man I am happy to dump Dreamweaver!!)',0,'1','','',0,0),(902,305,'datico','darrentcook@gmail.com','','','2010-04-16 12:44:41','2010-04-16 12:44:41','@ManOnTheMoon:\nCtrl-L to jump to a line number.',0,'1','','',0,0),(903,305,'Terri B','bellanger@sunycgcc.edu','','','2010-09-02 10:12:01','2010-09-02 10:12:01','Thanks for posting where to find it - but it is still just horribly inconvenient. I only want to use word wrap when editing content that is extra long. I rarely use it when coding, and generally do not want to have it on.  To have to dig that deep into the preferences AND to have to restart the program every time I want to turn it on or off is just unacceptable.',0,'1','','',0,0),(904,305,'Clint','clint317@gmail.com','','','2010-12-02 20:21:41','2010-12-02 20:21:41','If you have Aptana installed, it\'s located in Preferences -> Aptana -> Editors (Advanced tab). And you do need to restart, otherwise it looks like wrap puts it on a new line. So restart.',0,'1','','',0,0),(905,305,'caotoxvadU','hydaa5t6uymail@gmail.com','http://www.formspring.me/memelosd','','2011-09-21 07:49:03','2011-09-21 07:49:03','<a href=http://texomashomepage.com/entertainment/forums/131-local-sports/605287-lasix-cod-next-day-delivery-no-rx-overnight#605287  rel=\"nofollow\"> Lasix cheap  Patterson  </a>\n<a href=http://www.wisebread.com/forums/lifehacks-personal-development/soma-overnight-delivery-79881.html#post124995  rel=\"nofollow\"> soma buy  described  </a>\n<a href=http://www.formspring.me/latrewak  rel=\"nofollow\"> buy tramadol prescription  coolangatta29yahoo  </a>\n<a href=http://texomashomepage.com/entertainment/forums/132-local-weather/605717-doxycycline-cod-next-day-delivery-no-rx-ove