/pre>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This advice was taken from the guide for <a href=\"https://gae-php-tips.appspot.com/2013/10/22/getting-started-with-laravel-on-php-for-app-engine/\">Laravel on PHP for App Engine</a>.</p>\r\nAll in all, it is a relatively quick little framework, and having using App Engine to scale out the services it provides seems like a no-brainer.\r\n\r\nAll code shown here is licensed under Apache 2. For more details find the original source<a href=\"https://github.com/tpryan/SharedCode/tree/master/BlogPosts/2015/04/Lumen%20on%20App%20Engine\">on Github</a>.','Lumen on App Engine','Lumen from Laravel works just fine on Php for App Engine. ','inherit','open','open','','770-revision-v1','','','2015-04-14 19:17:38','2015-04-14 19:17:38','',770,'https://arctic-marking-865.appspot.com/blog/index.php/770-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(778,1,'2015-04-16 20:52:59','2015-04-16 20:52:59','A few weeks ago Google Cloud Platform released an <a href=\"https://groups.google.com/forum/#!topic/google-appengine/9PMjrTxVy4w\">update for PHP on App Engine</a> that enabled PHP 5.5 on App Engine. It was all very exciting, and there was a <a href=\"https://groups.google.com/forum/#!topic/google-appengine/9PMjrTxVy4w\">forum post</a> about it any everything. At the bottom though there is a little note:\r\n<blockquote>After 16th April, 2015 we will begin automatically migrating all applications to the php55 runtime.</blockquote>\r\nYou may have also seen emails from\"Google App Engine\" reminding you of this.<b> </b>In those notices it has been changed to:\r\n<blockquote>in approximately 2 weeks we will begin automatically migrating your application over to use the PHP 5.5</blockquote>\r\nIf you need an extension on PHP 5.4 you can <a href=\"https://support.google.com/cloud/contact/php_request_form\">fill out a form to request one</a>.\r\n\r\nSo this change is coming, and this post is yet another heads up to remind people.','PHP on App Engine Updating to PHP 5.5','PHP on App Engine will be updating to PHP 5.5. Make sure you test your apps. ','publish','open','open','','php-on-app-engine-updating-to-php-5-5','','','2015-04-16 20:52:59','2015-04-16 20:52:59','',0,'https://arctic-marking-865.appspot.com/blog/?p=778',0,'post','',0),(779,1,'2015-04-16 20:48:20','2015-04-16 20:48:20','A few weeks back we released an <a href=\"https://groups.google.com/forum/#!topic/google-appengine/9PMjrTxVy4w\">update for PHP on App Engine</a> that allowed developers to upgrade themselves to PHP 5.5. It was all very exciting, and there was a <a href=\"https://groups.google.com/forum/#!topic/google-appengine/9PMjrTxVy4w\">forum post</a> about it any everything. At the bottom though there is a little note:\r\n<blockquote><strong>After 16th April, 2015 we will begin automatically migrating all applications to the php55 runtime.</strong></blockquote>\r\nYou may have gotten emails from\"Google App Engine\" reminding you of this.<b> </b>In those notices it has been changed to:\r\n<blockquote>in approximately 2 weeks we will begin automatically migrating your application over to use the PHP 5.5</blockquote>\r\nIf you need an extension on PHP 5.4 you can <a href=\"https://support.google.com/cloud/contact/php_request_form\">fill out a form to request one</a>.\r\n\r\nJust yet another heads up to remind people that this is coming.','PHP on App Engine Going to PHP 5.5','','inherit','open','open','','778-revision-v1','','','2015-04-16 20:48:20','2015-04-16 20:48:20','',778,'https://arctic-marking-865.appspot.com/blog/index.php/778-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(780,1,'2015-04-16 20:52:31','2015-04-16 20:52:31','A few weeks ago Google Cloud Platform released an <a href=\"https://groups.google.com/forum/#!topic/google-appengine/9PMjrTxVy4w\">update for PHP on App Engine</a> that enabled PHP 5.5 on App Engine. It was all very exciting, and there was a <a href=\"https://groups.google.com/forum/#!topic/google-appengine/9PMjrTxVy4w\">forum post</a> about it any everything. At the bottom though there is a little note:\r\n<blockquote>After 16th April, 2015 we will begin automatically migrating all applications to the php55 runtime.</blockquote>\r\nYou may have also seen emails from\"Google App Engine\" reminding you of this.<b> </b>In those notices it has been changed to:\r\n<blockquote>in approximately 2 weeks we will begin automatically migrating your application over to use the PHP 5.5</blockquote>\r\nIf you need an extension on PHP 5.4 you can <a href=\"https://support.google.com/cloud/contact/php_request_form\">fill out a form to request one</a>.\r\n\r\nSo this change is coming, and this post is yet another heads up to remind people.','PHP on App Engine Updating to PHP 5.5','PHP on App Engine will be updating to PHP 5.5. Make sure you test your apps. ','inherit','open','open','','778-revision-v1','','','2015-04-16 20:52:31','2015-04-16 20:52:31','',778,'https://arctic-marking-865.appspot.com/blog/index.php/778-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(781,1,'2015-05-08 05:34:45','2015-05-08 05:34:45','<p dir=\"ltr\"><img class=\"alignright size-full wp-image-784\" alt=\"dbs\" src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/fZ7q4L6Q9FiX-HI4_nHiaCKRAJAso4e6XP-vpqOV4VW5Lc6uu5atbUq6dq4Sr38L1tkuRQkkgSeZbZjsOoQNcKr58f6E7ZXB=s0\" />Recently, Google Cloud Platform announced the availability of an additional database option for our customers: <a href=\"http://googlecloudplatform.blogspot.com/2015/05/introducing-Google-Cloud-Bigtable.html\">Google Cloud Bigtable</a>. Now Cloud Platform Developers have another Google managed solution for storing their data. So, when do you use which tool?</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">The contenders:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://cloud.google.com/sql/docs/introduction\">Cloud SQL</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://cloud.google.com/datastore/docs/concepts/overview\">Cloud Datastore</a></li>\r\n	<li><a href=\"https://cloud.google.com/bigtable/docs/\">Cloud Bigtable</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Cloud SQL</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Are you using some sort of relational database with tables, views, and indices? Does your application rely on stored procedures and custom table views or write joins? Do you need the certainty of transactions and ACID compliance? Do you generally both read and write to the data, not in equal amounts, but not lopsidedly one or the other? If you answered yes to a lot of these you probably want to investigate or stick with <a href=\"https://cloud.google.com/sql/docs/introduction\">Cloud SQL</a>, which as its name suggests, is an implementation of MySQL hosted by Google.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Cloud SQL does have all of the limitations of MySQL. Certain types of applications dont require the complexity of normalized data with no duplication. Other cases require scaling in a manner that SQL cannot handle without additional complexity, reduced performance, or higher cost. Going into the full pros and cons of SQL vs NoSQL is beyond the scope of this post, but rest assured there are reasons that both of them exist, and both are valid choices depending on circumstances.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>NoSQL: Datastore or Bigtable</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">If you are leaning towards a NoSQL solution you now have two Google managed NoSQL choices on our platform. What is the differentiator between Cloud Datastore vs Cloud Bigtable? They are both NoSQL solutions. Both are described as massively scalable. Both leave you with little to no management (or No Ops for those of you playing buzzword bingo). The answer lies in four areas:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Size</li>\r\n	<li>Structure</li>\r\n	<li>Analysis</li>\r\n	<li>Interface</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Size</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Bigtable is optimized for mind boggling huge sets of data. Seriously, it is most cost effective when dealing with datasets that start at 1 Terabyte. Datastore can handle large data sets too, but Datastore is performance and cost optimized to handle smaller sets of data too. Have a few GBs of data? Datastore would be the better call. Have data that might start out small, but grow to a Terabyte in time, still Datastore. Have data that starts at a Terabyte and will keep expanding? Then youve started down a path that might make Bigtable interesting. But size alone isnt the only factor.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Structure</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Bigtable stores data in a big honkin table. Yeah, the name is a little on the nose, but its true. There are rows and columns somewhat like relational database systems but not exactly. But it has a schema, and predefined structure.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Cloud Datastore, on the other hand, is more optimal for ad hoc storage of structured data representing objects. Basically you define an object and then push it into Datastore. You dont define a schema, create tables, or set up any other sort of structure before storing a record.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Analysis</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Do you need to analyze the data in massive aggregate scale while the database is still online and taking requests? Do you want to run MapReduce on your production data without copying it somewhere for study? Do you want to hook it up to various Big Data analysis toolkits? If this sounds like what you want to do, Bigtable makes more sense.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Interface</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">If you are coming to Google Cloud Platform from other technologies, and are working with HBase, Bigtable is for you. Bigtable is accessible through extensions to the HBase 1.0 API and is therefore compatible with a lot of the Hadoop ecosystem as well as other Big Data tools.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">On the other hand, there are also a few limitations. You cannot join. There is no SQL interface. The API gives you Put/Get/Delete individual records, or you can run Scan operations.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Datastore does not have SQL either, but has an API called GQL that while not exactly the same does abstract querying objects in a way that most SQL developers should be able to quickly understand.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Conclusion</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Finally the <a href=\"https://cloud.google.com/bigtable/docs/index\">product page</a> has a great explanation of Bigtables relation to other Google Cloud Platform offerings:</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<h2 dir=\"ltr\">Cloud Bigtable and other storage options</h2>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Cloud Bigtable is not a relational database; it does not support SQL queries or joins, nor does it support multi-row transactions. Also, it is not a good solution for small amounts of data (&lt; 1 TB).</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">If you need full SQL support for an online transaction processing (OLTP) system, consider <a href=\"https://cloud.google.com/sql/\">Google Cloud SQL</a>.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">If you need interactive querying in an online analytical processing (OLAP) system, consider <a href=\"https://cloud.google.com/bigquery/\">Google BigQuery</a>.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">If you need to store immutable blobs larger than 10 MB, such as large images or movies, consider <a href=\"https://cloud.google.com/storage/\">Google Cloud Storage</a>.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">If you need to store highly structured objects, or if you require support for ACID transactions and SQL-like queries, consider <a href=\"https://cloud.google.com/datastore/docs\">Cloud Datastore</a>.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">In short, there is a lot of awesome stuff about Cloud Bigtable, but it doesnt mean that it is right in all cases. Its a NoOps, NoSQL, Big Data analysis tool, meant to be used at massive scale in conjunction with other Big Data tools. I recommend that you check out the <a href=\"https://cloud.google.com/bigtable/docs/index\">documentation for Bigtable</a> as there is much more to be found there. And let me know if you need more clarification on anything.</p>','When to Pick Google Bigtable vs Other Cloud Platform Databases','The addition of Google Cloud Bigtable is awesome, but potentially confusing.  This should clear some of that confusion up. ','publish','open','open','','when-to-pick-google-bigtable-vs-other-cloud-platform-databases','','','2015-05-12 14:33:15','2015-05-12 14:33:15','',0,'https://arctic-marking-865.appspot.com/blog/?p=781',0,'post','',1),(782,1,'2015-05-06 23:24:42','2015-05-06 23:24:42','<p dir=\"ltr\">Today Google Cloud Platform announced the availability of a new database technology: <a href=\"http://googlecloudplatform.blogspot.com/2015/05/introducing-Google-Cloud-Bigtable.html\">Google Cloud Bigtable</a>. Now Cloud Platform Developers have another choice for storing their data. Which begs the question: <em>When do I use which tool?</em></p>\r\nThe contenders:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Cloud SQL</li>\r\n	<li>Cloud Datastore</li>\r\n	<li>Cloud Bigtable</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Are you a SQL developer? Are you using some sort of relational database with tables, indices, and the like. Can we assume that you want to write stored procedures and create table views to get a better look at your data? Do you generally both read and write to the data, not in equal amounts, but not lopsidedly one or the other? You probably want to choose or stick with Cloud SQL, which as it sounds, is an implementation of MySQL hosted by Google (we like our names to be pretty on the nose).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>NoSQL</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">If you are a NoSQL developer you now have two choices on our platform. What is the differentiator between Cloud Datastore vs Cloud Bigtable? They are both NoSQL solutions. Both are described as massively scalable. Both leave you with little to no management need. The answer lies in four areas:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Size</li>\r\n	<li>Structure</li>\r\n	<li>Analysis</li>\r\n	<li>Interface.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Size</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Bigtable was designed for mind boggling huge sets of data. Seriously, it works best when dealing with datasets that start at 1 Terabyte. Datastore can handle large data sets too, but Datastore is performance and cost optimized to handle smaller sets of data too. Have a few GBs of data? Datastore would be the better call. Have data that might start out small, but grow to a Terabyte in time, still Datastore. Have data that starts at a Terabyte and will keep expanding? Then youve started down a path that might make Bigtable your call. But size alone isnt the only factor.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Structure</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Bigtable stores data in a big honking table. Yeah, the name is a little on the nose, but its true. There are rows and columns somewhat like relational database systems but not exactly. Unlike relational systems sparse records cost nothing from a storage or performance standpoint, so its common to see very wide tables with large sets of columns that for most rows are almost always blank.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Cloud Datastore on the other hand allows for adhoc storing of highly structured data representing objects. Basically you define an object and then push it into Datastore. You dont really define tables or any other sort of structure before hand. Then the API has interfaces around getting that data out in object form.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Analysis</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Do you need to analyze the data in massive aggregate scale while the database is still online and taking requests? Do you want to run MapReduce on your current transaction set in real time without moving the data somewhere for study? If this sounds like what you want to do, Bigtable makes more sense.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Interface</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">If you are coming to Google Cloud Platform from other technologies, and are working with HBase, Bigtable is for you. Bigtable is accessible through the HBase 1.0 API and is therefore compatible with a lot of the Hadoop ecosystem as well as other Big Data tools.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">On the other hand, there are also a few limitations. You cannot join. There is no SQL interface. The API gives you Put/Get/Scan - thats it.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Datastore does not have SQL either, but has an API called GQL that while not exactly the same does abstract querying objects in a way that most SQL developers should be able to quickly understand.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Conclusion</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Finally the <a href=\"https://cloud.google.com/bigtable/docs/index\">product page</a> has a great explanation of Bigtables relation to other Google Cloud Platform offerings:</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<h2 dir=\"ltr\">Cloud Bigtable and other storage options</h2>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Cloud Bigtable is not a relational database; it does not support SQL queries or joins, nor does it support multi-row transactions. Also, it is not a good solution for small amounts of data (&lt; 1 TB).</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">If you need full SQL support for an online transaction processing (OLTP) system, consider <a href=\"https://cloud.google.com/sql/\">Google Cloud SQL</a>.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">If you need interactive querying in an online analytical processing (OLAP) system, consider <a href=\"https://cloud.google.com/bigquery/\">Google BigQuery</a>.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">If you need to store immutable blobs larger than 10 MB, such as large images or movies, consider <a href=\"https://cloud.google.com/storage/\">Google Cloud Storage</a>.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">If you need to store highly structured objects, or if you require support for ACID transactions and SQL-like queries, consider <a href=\"https://cloud.google.com/datastore/docs\">Cloud Datastore</a>.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</blockquote>\r\nIn short, there is a lot a awesome stuff about Cloud Bigtable, but it doesnt mean that it is right in all cases. Its a NoSQL Big Data analysis tool, meant to be used at massive scale in conjunction with other Big Data tools. I recommend that you check out the <a href=\"https://cloud.google.com/bigtable/docs/index\">documentation for Bigtable</a> as there is much more to be found there. And let me know if you need more clarification on anything.','','','inherit','open','open','','781-revision-v1','','','2015-05-06 23:24:42','2015-05-06 23:24:42','',781,'https://arctic-marking-865.appspot.com/blog/index.php/781-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(783,1,'2015-05-06 23:30:57','2015-05-06 23:30:57','<p dir=\"ltr\">Today Google Cloud Platform announced the availability of a new database technology: <a href=\"http://googlecloudplatform.blogspot.com/2015/05/introducing-Google-Cloud-Bigtable.html\">Google Cloud Bigtable</a>. Now Cloud Platform Developers have another choice for storing their data. Which begs the question: <em>When do I use which tool?</em></p>\r\nThe contenders:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Cloud SQL</li>\r\n	<li>Cloud Datastore</li>\r\n	<li>Cloud Bigtable</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Are you a SQL developer? Are you using some sort of relational database with tables, indices, and the like. Can we assume that you want to write stored procedures and create table views to get a better look at your data? Do you generally both read and write to the data, not in equal amounts, but not lopsidedly one or the other? You probably want to choose or stick with Cloud SQL, which as it sounds, is an implementation of MySQL hosted by Google (we like our names to be pretty on the nose).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>NoSQL</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">If you are a NoSQL developer you now have two choices on our platform. What is the differentiator between Cloud Datastore vs Cloud Bigtable? They are both NoSQL solutions. Both are described as massively scalable. Both leave you with little to no management need. The answer lies in four areas:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Size</li>\r\n	<li>Structure</li>\r\n	<li>Analysis</li>\r\n	<li>Interface.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Size</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Bigtable was designed for mind boggling huge sets of data. Seriously, it works best when dealing with datasets that start at 1 Terabyte. Datastore can handle large data sets too, but Datastore is performance and cost optimized to handle smaller sets of data too. Have a few GBs of data? Datastore would be the better call. Have data that might start out small, but grow to a Terabyte in time, still Datastore. Have data that starts at a Terabyte and will keep expanding? Then youve started down a path that might make Bigtable your call. But size alone isnt the only factor.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Structure</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Bigtable stores data in a big honking table. Yeah, the name is a little on the nose, but its true. There are rows and columns somewhat like relational database systems but not exactly. Unlike relational systems sparse records cost nothing from a storage or performance standpoint, so its common to see very wide tables with large sets of columns that for most rows are almost always blank.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Cloud Datastore on the other hand allows for adhoc storing of highly structured data representing objects. Basically you define an object and then push it into Datastore. You dont really define tables or any other sort of structure before hand. Then the API has interfaces around getting that data out in object form.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Analysis</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Do you need to analyze the data in massive aggregate scale while the database is still online and taking requests? Do you want to run MapReduce on your current transaction set in real time without moving the data somewhere for study? If this sounds like what you want to do, Bigtable makes more sense.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Interface</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">If you are coming to Google Cloud Platform from other technologies, and are working with HBase, Bigtable is for you. Bigtable is accessible through the HBase 1.0 API and is therefore compatible with a lot of the Hadoop ecosystem as well as other Big Data tools.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">On the other hand, there are also a few limitations. You cannot join. There is no SQL interface. The API gives you Put/Get/Scan - thats it.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Datastore does not have SQL either, but has an API called GQL that while not exactly the same does abstract querying objects in a way that most SQL developers should be able to quickly understand.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Conclusion</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Finally the <a href=\"https://cloud.google.com/bigtable/docs/index\">product page</a> has a great explanation of Bigtables relation to other Google Cloud Platform offerings:</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote><strong dir=\"ltr\">Cloud Bigtable and other storage options</strong>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Cloud Bigtable is not a relational database; it does not support SQL queries or joins, nor does it support multi-row transactions. Also, it is not a good solution for small amounts of data (&lt; 1 TB).</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">If you need full SQL support for an online transaction processing (OLTP) system, consider <a href=\"https://cloud.google.com/sql/\">Google Cloud SQL</a>.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">If you need interactive querying in an online analytical processing (OLAP) system, consider <a href=\"https://cloud.google.com/bigquery/\">Google BigQuery</a>.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">If you need to store immutable blobs larger than 10 MB, such as large images or movies, consider <a href=\"https://cloud.google.com/storage/\">Google Cloud Storage</a>.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">If you need to store highly structured objects, or if you require support for ACID transactions and SQL-like queries, consider <a href=\"https://cloud.google.com/datastore/docs\">Cloud Datastore</a>.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</blockquote>\r\nIn short, there is a lot a awesome stuff about Cloud Bigtable, but it doesnt mean that it is right in all cases. Its a NoSQL Big Data analysis tool, meant to be used at massive scale in conjunction with other Big Data tools. I recommend that you check out the <a href=\"https://cloud.google.com/bigtable/docs/index\">documentation for Bigtable</a> as there is much more to be found there. And let me know if you need more clarification on anything.','','','inherit','open','open','','781-revision-v1','','','2015-05-06 23:30:57','2015-05-06 23:30:57','',781,'https://arctic-marking-865.appspot.com/blog/index.php/781-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(784,1,'2015-05-06 23:31:15','2015-05-06 23:31:15','','dbs','','inherit','open','open','','dbs','','','2015-05-06 23:31:15','2015-05-06 23:31:15','',781,'https://storage.googleapis.com/arctic-marking-865.appspot.com/dbs.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(785,1,'2015-05-06 23:35:19','2015-05-06 23:35:19','<p dir=\"ltr\"><img class=\"alignright size-full wp-image-784\" alt=\"dbs\" src=\"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/fZ7q4L6Q9FiX-HI4_nHiaCKRAJAso4e6XP-vpqOV4VW5Lc6uu5atbUq6dq4Sr38L1tkuRQkkgSeZbZjsOoQNcKr58f6E7ZXB=s0\" />Today Google Cloud Platform announced the availability of a new database technology: <a href=\"http://googlecloudplatform.blogspot.com/2015/05/introducing-Google-Cloud-Bigtable.html\">Google Cloud Bigtable</a>. Now Cloud Platform Developers have another choice for storing their data. Which begs the question: <em>When do I use which tool?</em></p>\r\nThe contenders:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Cloud SQL</li>\r\n	<li>Cloud Datastore</li>\r\n	<li>Cloud Bigtable</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Are you a SQL developer? Are you using some sort of relational database with tables, indices, and the like. Can we assume that you want to write stored procedures and create table views to get a better look at your data? Do you generally both read and write to the data, not in equal amounts, but not lopsidedly one or the other? You probably want to choose or stick with Cloud SQL, which as it sounds, is an implementation of MySQL hosted by Google (we like our names to be pretty on the nose).</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>NoSQL</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">If you are a NoSQL developer you now have two choices on our platform. What is the differentiator between Cloud Datastore vs Cloud Bigtable? They are both NoSQL solutions. Both are described as massively scalable. Both leave you with little to no management need. The answer lies in four areas:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Size</li>\r\n	<li>Structure</li>\r\n	<li>Analysis</li>\r\n	<li>Interface.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Size</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Bigtable was designed for mind boggling huge sets of data. Seriously, it works best when dealing with datasets that start at 1 Terabyte. Datastore can handle large data sets too, but Datastore is performance and cost optimized to handle smaller sets of data too. Have a few GBs of data? Datastore would be the better call. Have data that might start out small, but grow to a Terabyte in time, still Datastore. Have data that starts at a Terabyte and will keep expanding? Then youve started down a path that might make Bigtable your call. But size alone isnt the only factor.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Structure</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Bigtable stores data in a big honking table. Yeah, the name is a little on the nose, but its true. There are rows and columns somewhat like relational database systems but not exactly. Unlike relational systems sparse records cost nothing from a storage or performance standpoint, so its common to see very wide tables with large sets of columns that for most rows are almost always blank.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Cloud Datastore on the other hand allows for adhoc storing of highly structured data representing objects. Basically you define an object and then push it into Datastore. You dont really define tables or any other sort of structure before hand. Then the API has interfaces around getting that data out in object form.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Analysis</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Do you need to analyze the data in massive aggregate scale while the database is still online and taking requests? Do you want to run MapReduce on your current transaction set in real time without moving the data somewhere for study? If this sounds like what you want to do, Bigtable makes more sense.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Interface</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">If you are coming to Google Cloud Platform from other technologies, and are working with HBase, Bigtable is for you. Bigtable is accessible through the HBase 1.0 API and is therefore compatible with a lot of the Hadoop ecosystem as well as other Big Data tools.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">On the other hand, there are also a few limitations. You cannot join. There is no SQL interface. The API gives you Put/Get/Scan - thats it.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Datastore does not have SQL either, but has an API called GQL that while not exactly the same does abstract querying objects in a way that most SQL developers should be able to quickly understand.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Conclusion</strong></p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Finally the <a href=\"https://cloud.google.com/bigtable/docs/index\">product page</a> has a great explanation of Bigtables relation to other Google Cloud Platform offerings:</p>\r\n\r\n<blockquote><strong dir=\"ltr\">Cloud Bigtable and other storage options</strong>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Cloud Bigtable is not a relational database; it does not support SQL queries or joins, nor does it support multi-row transactions. Also, it is not a good solution for small amounts of data (&lt; 1 TB).</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">If you need full SQL support for an online transaction processing (OLTP) system, consider <a href=\"https://cloud.google.com/sql/\">Google Cloud SQL</a>.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">If you need interactive querying in an online analytical processing (OLAP) system, consider <a href=\"https://cloud.google.com/bigquery/\">Google BigQuery</a>.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">If you need to store immutable blobs larger than 10 MB, such as large images or movies, consider <a href=\"https://cloud.google.com/storage/\">Google Cloud Storage</a>.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">If you need to store highly structured objects, or if you require support for ACID transactions and SQL-like queries, consider <a href=\"https://cloud.google.com/datastore/docs\">Cloud Datastore</a>.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</blockquote>\r\nIn short, there is a lot a awesome stuff about Cloud Bigtable, but it doesnt mean that it is right in all cases. Its a NoSQL Big Data analysis tool, meant to be used at massive scale in conjunction with other Big Data tools. I recommend that you check out the <a href=\"https://cloud.google.com/bigtable/docs/index\">documentation for Bigtable</a> as there is much more to be found there. And let me know if you need more clarification on anything.','','The addition of Google Cloud Bigtable is awesome, but potentially confusing.  This should clear some of that confusion up. ','inherit','open','open','','781-revision-v1','','','2015-05-06 23:35:19','2015-05-06 23:35:19','',781,'https://arctic-marking-865.appspot.com/blog/index.php/781-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(786,1,'2015-05-06 23:38:01','2015-05-06 23:38:01','','BigTable_512px_Retina','','inherit','open','open','','bigtable_512px_retina','','','2015-05-06 23:38:01','2015-05-06 23:38:01','',0,'https://storage.googleapis.com/arctic-marking-865.appspot.com/BigTable_512px_Retina.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(787,1,'2015-05-06 23:42:14','2015-05-06 23:42:14','<